<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Rebels     09-17 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Rebels,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas free five imprisoned comrades, kill hostage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing guerrillas firing automatic
weapons burst into a federal court building in the town of Buga
Friday and freed five of their comrades being held for trial,
police reported.
   They said a judge's administrative assistant was taken hostage
by the gunmen and his body was found with a bullet in the head
beside a highway near the town 160 miles southwest of Bogota.
   Two of the guerrillas freed by the attackers were captured after
an hour-long pursuit, the police said. They did not report any
other casualties or give further details.
   In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 government
soldiers and policemen captured in a raid last month and also
released two Colombian geologists seized in another attack, the
government and military announced.
   The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisoner
Aug. 23 by guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army and the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces during a joint attack on the
northwestern town of Saiza.
   A statement from the office of President Virgilio Barcos said a
one-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could be
released in the Uraba region, about 300 miles northwest of Bogota.
   Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocket
and mortar attack on the police station in Saiza, Gen. Jesus Arias
said in an interview with the radio station RCN. He did not list
their conditions or elaborate.
   The two geologists released Thursday were among five who worked
with coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 by rebels of another
guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, or ELN.
   Rebels freed the two geologists in an arranged meeting with a
group of reporters in the city of Bucaramanga, 200 miles northeast
of Bogota.
   An ELN communique said the three other geologists would be
released soon, but declared the guerrillas would launch an
offensive against foreign coal-mining companies.
   Exxon and the Colombian state company Carbacol are partners in a
$3 billion surface mine near Colombia's Caribbean coast.
   ELN guerrillas have attacked oil pipelines and oil installations
operated by Occidental Petroleum Co., Shell Oil and the Colombian
state company Ecopetrol 46 times this year, according to the
government. It placed the damage at $300 million.
   A Defense Ministry communique released Friday said 1,174 people
have been killed this year in guerrilla attacks and battles between
rebels and security forces.
   It listed the slain as 499 guerrillas, 378 civilians and 297
policemen and soldiers.
   The ministry has reported 2,037 people were killed last year in
fighting involving rebels, government forces and civilians caught
in the violence.
</TEXT>
