<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MondoArrest     09-17 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mondo Arrest,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cult Film Performer Arrested for Mice-Biting Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An underground performer who allegedly bites the
heads off two mice in the cult film ``Mondo New York'' has been
arrested on animal cruelty charges, an ASPCA spokesman said.
   Joe Coleman, 32, a Manhattan performance artist, was taken into
custody by ASPCA agents at his Greenwich Village apartment Friday,
said Jeffrey Hon, spokesman for the American Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
   Coleman was booked at a police station on charges under the
state Agriculture and Markets Law; if convicted, he could face up
to one year in prison and a $1,000 fine per mouse, Hon said.
   ``While this one act may seem fairly insignificant, the whole
issue of animals in entertainment is not,'' said Hon. ``We're
letting people from underground acts to Hollywood producers know
they can't get away with animal cruelty.''
   Coleman was still being processed by police and could not
immediately be reached for comment.
   ``Mondo New York,'' a cult favorite which plays in weekend
midnight shows at a Greenwich Village theatre, features an
assortment of bizarre acts from the downtown Manhattan scene.
   Although the film was released earlier this summer, Coleman was
not arrested because ASPCA investigators hoped to catch him in the
act during one of his live performances, Hon said.
   Authorities have an eyewitness to Coleman's performance and
decided to arrest him after receiving a tip that he was leaving for
Europe, he said.
   In his scene, Coleman allegedly bites the heads off two mice and
spits them into the audience. According to Hon, the scene has
outraged animal rights activists, including television game show
host Bob Barker.
   ``Bob Barker has been very keen for us to arrest this guy
Coleman so legislators can see exactly what's going on,'' said Hon.
</TEXT>
