<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Rivers     09-17 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Rivers,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rivers Negotiates for Talk Show Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Joan Rivers is currently in
negotation with with Tribune Entertainment Co. about hosting a
daytime television talk show, according to industry newspaper
reports.
   The former host of Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``The Late Show'' and
guest host of NBC's ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson'' is
said to be working out a deal for a 26-week cycle beginning in the
fall of 1989 that would serve as a counterpart to Tribune's
``Geraldo.''
   Neither Miss Rivers nor Tribune could be reached for comment in
calls made after business hours.
   Although a contract has not been signed, it was only a matter of
``crossing the T's and dotting the I's,'' according to Friday's
editions of The Hollywood Reporter.
   The talk show would be carried by the six Tribune-owned
television stations, including KTLA in Los Angeles, WPIX in New
York and WGN in Chicago, The Daily Variety reported in its Friday
editions.
   Miss Rivers is currently appearing on Broadway in Neil Simon's
``Broadway Bound.'' She also stars as the permanent ``center
square'' on television's ``Hollywood Squares.''
   Miss Rivers vacated the guest host spot on the NBC talk show in
1986 to take the starring role in ``The Late Show,'' which debuted
Oct. 9, 1986. The show got lower ratings than expected, and she
left the program in May 1987.
</TEXT>
