<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Vietnam     09-17 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Vietnam,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Vietnam To Search for MIA's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint U.S.-Vietnamese team soon will begin
an on-site investigation into the fate of missing American
servicemen, focussing on seven cases in which there is evidence the
victims were alive when they disappeared.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Friday the seven
are part of the 70 ``most compelling cases'' which U.S. officials
raised with Vietnamese authorities last year.
   Other officials said that although the 70 were presumed to be
alive when they became separated from their units, all have long
since been presumed dead because there is no evidence to prove
otherwise.
   This is the first time the United States and Vietnam have agreed
on a joint investigation involving more than one site. Officials
from the two countries participated in the excavation of a crash
site in search of missing servicemen in November 1985.
   Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, commander of the U.S. Joint Casualty
Resolution Center, said in a telephone interview Friday from
Honolulu, ``We're going to do joint investigations of incidents,
not just crash sites, but places where people were last thought to
be but we don't know exactly what happened to them.
   ``I think it's a very significant development,'' he said. ``We
think this will be the first of many such joint activities.'' The
inspections will be concentrated in an area north of Hanoi.
   On Friday, House Republican Leader Robert Michel of Illinois
urged the families of missing servicemen to ignore the rumors that
will be inevitable during the pending search.
   ``We have to continue to press for an accounting of each and
every one, even though the prospects of finding anyone alive
diminish with the passing of time,'' Michel told a crowd of several
hundred at a National POW-MIA Recognition Day ceremony on the steps
of the Capitol.
   All told, more than 1,700 Americans remain unaccounted for in
Vietnam since U.S. military involvement in the country ended 15
years ago. There is no firm evidence that any are alive although
officials routinely check out reports of live sightings.
   The two countries reached agreement on an on-site inspection
procedure during a meeting in Hanoi that ended Wednesday, Redman
said. The investigation will involve interviews with villagers and
other activities.
   A 90-day period, beginning Sept. 1, was set aside for carrying
out the investigations, Redman said, with each one limited to 10
days.
   After suspending cooperation with the United States on the MIA
issue in August, Vietnam recently agreed to resume discussions on
the issue.
   The suspension was precipitated by Hanoi's unhappiness with the
administration's policy of keeping Vietnam isolated diplomatically
and economically until that country withdraws its troops from
Cambodia.
   Vietnam is one of the few countries with which the United States
does not have diplomatic relations.
   While restoring cooperation on the MIA question, Vietnam has not
lifted a ban on discussions about a program to permit thousands of
former political prisoners to emigrate to the United States.
</TEXT>
