<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HouseMailings     09-17 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Mailings,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Suggests New Limits On Free Mailings For Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Election-year mass mailings by lawmakers have
risen dramatically and prompted leaders of a House committee to
call for new restrictions on how much mail can be sent at taxpayer
expense.
   Four members of the House Administration Committee, including
its Democratic chairman and senior Republican member, said in a
letter Friday that increased numbers of taxpayer-paid mailings this
year have caused a backlog in their processing and delivery. That
could cause some of the mail to arrive at voters' homes during the
height of the campaign season in late October, they said.
   Critics contend that some mailings, particularly newsletters,
are little more than government-paid campaign literature intended
to promote the re-election of officeholders.
   Under House rules, members cannot send a mass mailing less than
60 days before the date of a primary or general election in which
their name appears on the ballot. Mailings must be delivered to the
House folding room by that deadline for processing.
   The lawmakers said that after the cutoff period this month,
there were 58 million pieces of mail awaiting processing by the
Publications Distribution Service.
   There were 35.4 million pieces of mail ready for processing at
the same point in 1986, 36.7 million in 1984 and 33.3 million in
1982.
   A temporary second shift of workers was added to the House
folding room earlier this year at a cost of nearly $500,000, and
their employment has been extended through mid-October to help
handle the larger volume of mail, the lawmakers said.
   ``It is essential that additional limitations be considered to
prevent this situation from repeating itself to the detriment of
the House and its members,'' the lawmakers said in their letter.
   Generally, members are limited to six mass mailings for their
districts during a year, but that does not include town meeting
notices.
</TEXT>
