<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Homeless-Housing     09-17 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless-Housing,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Decision Expected Soon On House Auctioning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge is expected to decide soon
whether the Reagan administration has considered the needs of the
homeless before auctioning off about 47,000 foreclosed homes that
are owned by the government.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch declined Friday to decide
several challenges by the homeless to the federal government's
policies, but said he would make his decision as soon as possible
after taking the arguments under advisement.
   William Bradford, an attorney for homeless advocates, reminded
Gasch that two temporary restraining orders barring the Department
of Housing and Urban Development from selling houses in the greater
Washington area and in Michigan expired Friday.
   Gasch replied, ``I would hope they would maintain the status
quo.''
   Government attorneys told Gasch they would have to consult with
their clients, but HUD general counsel J. Michael Dorsey said later
through a spokesman that the housing agency would follow the terms
of the restraining order through the end of business next Wednesday.
   The coalition of advocates for the homeless argued the HUD has
violated the law by selling its stock of foreclosed single-family
homes to the highest bidder without determining whether they could
be beneficial to the homeless and low-income people.
   Bradford told Gasch that HUD receives 70,000 houses each year _
about 7,000 a month _ but the agency ``cannot proceed as if it is
simply in the real estate business. They must consider the
homeless.''
   In a related case, the National Coalition for the Homeless also
argued that the Reagan administration has defied a congressional
mandate to release underused federal property as housing for the
nation's homeless.
   Ms. Maria Foscarinis, a coalition attorney, said ``there are
thousands of properties underutilized which could be used for the
homeless.'' She said that of the 12 facilities that have been
officially identified as underutilized, only two have been made
available to the homeless.
   ``It's unconscionable - as well as illegal - that federal
buildings stand vacant while homeless men, women and children sleep
on the streets,'' she said.
   The suits want the court to order the government agencies to
survey their property, determine which is underutilized or no
longer needed and make those properties available for the homeless.
   Government attorney W. Robert Irwin argued that the 1987
homeless act does not apply to single family dwellings ``They want
to shut down a program that has been going on for 50 years,'' he
said. ``They want to tie up the program.''
   Arthur Goldberg, another government lawyer, said all the
agencies have complied with the requirements of the provisions of
the homeless act.
</TEXT>
