<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-CISPES     09-17 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-CISPES,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sessions Acknowledges Contacts With Salvadoran National Guard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions has acknowledged
contact between between a bureau intelligence source and the
Salvadoran National Guard.
   But in comments to a House subcommittee Friday, Sessions said it
will be impossible to determine whether the source gave the Guard
sensitive information from FBI files.
   Critics of the Salvadoran government claim links between the
National Guard and right-wing death squad killings in the Central
American country. Salvadoran political leaders reject the
allegations.
   Sessions told the subcommittee hearing on the FBI's
investigation of the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador that there were ``communications'' between former bureau
intelligence source Frank Varelli and the Guard.
   ``I do not know specifically what he gave to the El Salvador
National Guard,'' Sessions said. ``We have no way of establishing
that.'' He said it was possible Varelli passed along sensitive
information.
   It was disclosed last year that Varelli, who is suing the FBI
for back pay, had given congressional investigators a list of 13
Salvadorans facing deportation from the United States. He told
Congress in February 1987 that he had gotten the list from FBI
Agent Daniel Flanagan of Dallas, and he passed it along to the
Salvadoran National Guard. Flanagan subsequently resigned from the
FBI.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., suggested Varelli may have had
access to other such lists as well.
   ``It is quite possible,'' Sessions responded in testimony before
the House subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights, which
Edwards chairs. Sessions noted that the bureau took action to
ensure that the 13 Salvadorans ``were in fact informed'' their
names had turned up on the list.
   The FBI early in 1987 rejected a suggestion by Edwards, based on
information from Varelli, that the bureau was trading information
with the National Guard in El Salvador. Oliver Revell, executive
assistant director of the FBI, said at the time that such a
suggestion ``is not true.''
   Based on information supplied by Varelli, the FBI launched a
terrorism probe of CISPES in March 1983.
   Sessions disciplined half a dozen bureau personnel Wednesday for
negligence in the investigation. He said the bureau failed
initially to check out Varelli's unreliable background and that the
bureau broadened the probe unnecessarily in October 1983 to cover
rank-and-file CISPES members who had nothing to do with
international terrorism. The FBI closed the probe in June 1985
after failing to establish any substantial link between CISPES and
international terrorism.
   Sessions said the FBI in the CISPES probe committed no illegal
acts and no violations of constitutional rights.
</TEXT>
