<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Cannot Conceal Liberalism, Softness on Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FINDLAY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush is steeping
himself in the symbols and rhetoric of patriotism while stepping up
accusations that Michael Dukakis is an out-of-touch liberal who
acts like a chameleon on the campaign trail.
   In campaign appearances on Friday, the Republican presidential
candidate ridiculed Dukakis' campaign trip this week to plants and
other facilities run by defense contractors. In one appearance,
Dukakis rode in an M-1 tank.
   ``I can't say he's not trying, the opponent from Masachusetts,''
Bush told a rally in Findlay, Ohio, honoring the U.S. flag. ``He
drove a tank this week but after he drove it, the tank kept veering
left.''
   In a news conference earlier Friday, Bush accused the Democratic
Massachusetts governor of being a ``made over'' candidate who is
trying to hide a liberal record from American voters.
   After opposing the MX missile, the Midgetman, and the B-1
Bomber, ``Now suddenly he rides around in a tank, jumps out of the
tank, takes off the helmet and comes on with different positions,''
Bush charged.
   Dukakis has since modified his opposition on the B-1.
   ``The tank did not fit,'' he said. ``It's time to take another
message to Michael... You cannot fool the Soviet leadership by
knocking America's defense for 10 years and then riding around in a
tank for 10 minutes ... You can't fool the American people.''
   Bush made the comments in Columbus, Ohio, after a tour of the
Buckeye Steel plant where his grandfather, Samuel Prescott Bush,
was president in the early part of the centry.
   Later, the visual setting was all red-white-and-blue as Bush
spoke against a colorful backdrop of flags on his visit to Findlay
in northwest Ohio. His appearance in the city, which was formally
designated Flag City, USA, in 1974, was to help kick off the town's
three-day festival honoring the flag.
   He said the Findlay townspeople got Congress to designate their
city Flag City in 1974 because ``the time had come to stand up for
the American flag and the values it represented and that is good
old-fashioned patriotism.''
   A crowd of a few thousand crowded the town intersection where
Bush spoke from the steps of the stately old Elks Club building.
   Of the flag he said, ``It is the symbol of these United States
of America and to the liberty for which it stands one nation under
god, with freedom and justice for all.''
   Bush has made a campaign target of Dukakis' gubernatorial veto
of a Massachusetts measure to require teachers to lead their
students in the pledge of allegiance to the flag.
   Bush also said Dukakis is trying to hide his liberalism.
   ``He refuses to repeat the positions that he took in wrapping up
that Democratic primary,'' Bush said. ``He ran way out on the left
and now he's trying to move over, and I'd say make the American
people forget the positions that he ran on and the positions that
he's lived on since he's been the liberal governor of the state of
Massachusetts.''
   Later Bush continued to emphasize his own pro-defense themes
when he helped unveil a monument to the Airmen who died in Vietnam
at the Air Force Museum at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in
Dayton.
   Bush has planned a quiet weekend, with only one public event,
attending a naturalization ceremony today for a group of immigrants.
</TEXT>
