<HEAD>Quayle Rallies Farm Crowds With `Endive' Chant, One-Liners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle has a new campaign battle cry: ``endive!''
   Quayle got a lot of mileage in farm states Friday out of the
leafy vegetable and some pithy one-liners as he accused Democrat
Michael Dukakis of being ``out of touch'' with the nation's
heartland.
   ``We need people who will listen to agriculture, not talk down
to it,'' Quayle said in speeches in Omaha, Neb., and in Des Moines.
``I reviewed the farm program of the governor of Massachusetts. His
idea of farm production is growing flowers in Harvard Yard.''
   In his five-day campaign swing through the Midwest and Plains
states, Quayle increasingly turned to ridicule and hyperbole to
make his points.
   Quayle is spending the weekend at home in McLean, Va. He attends
a picnic today at the Virginia home of Sen. John Warner, the
ranking Republican on the Senate Armed Services Committee, on which
Quayle also serves.
   On Friday, Quayle ridiculed Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee, for suggestions that livestock and grain farmers consider
growing Belgian endive.
   ``During the primary season last winter, our opponent responded
that one of the answers to helping farmers was for them to grow
different crops,'' Quayle said. ``He suggested blueberries and
Belgian endive to pull farmers out of their economic doldrums.''
   Republicans have been making hay of Dukakis' endive remark,
which he made in Iowa, since the Republican National Convention.
   Quayle said the ``entire national market'' for Belgian endive is
worth less than $10 million per year.
   ``So if you start growing these little things, don't count on
paying off the farm debt,'' Quayle said.
   He got laughs from the crowds when he held up a head of endive
to show them ``just how the man from Massachusetts thinks he can
rebuild the farm economy.''
   In Des Moines, Quayle joined in after the audience started
chanting: ``endive! endive!''
   Dukakis, he said, doesn't understand the ``heartland of
America'' and is ``out of touch with the people across America.''
   He said Dukakis also had switched ``back and forth'' so much on
defense issues in recent days that ``I decided to sum it up this
way: His farm policy is the Belgian endive and his defense policy
is the Belgian waffle.''
   Quayle said a George Bush administration would open more markets
abroad for U.S. agricultural products, support development of
alternative fuels such as ethanol, which is made from grain, and
focus more on rural economic development.
   ``We'll get that capital gains tax down to 15 percent and that
will help small businesses which means more jobs here in the
heartland,'' Quayle said. ``I can also assure you that with us, you
get folks who are experienced in lowering interest rates, lowering
inflation, creating jobs, increasing productivity and keeping the
peace,''
</TEXT>
