<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     09-17 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Stepped-Up Drug Enforcement Would Pay For Itself</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis laid part of the blame
for Southern California's growing drug problem on George Bush as he
pledged more agents and prosecutors in a stepped up fight against
drug kingpins.
   ``George Bush was supposed to be in charge of that war, and we
all know what happened,'' the Democratic presidential nominee told
students at Roosevelt High School in the Latino section of East Los
Angeles on Friday.
   ``You know, if you don't show up at school, you fail, and if you
don't show up at your job as chief officer of the war on drugs, you
fail, the American people lose, and the drug lords take over,'' he
said.
   Dukakis, trying to reverse a slide in California polls, was
campaigning for a second day in the state today.
   He was meeting with campaign workers in Anaheim in Orange
County, a conservative Republican area where the campaign hopes to
cut into Bush's expected support. From there, Dukakis was flying
back to Washington to meet with members of the Congressional Black
Caucus at a dinner Jesse Jackson was expected to attend.
   The Massachusetts governor planned to resume campaigning Monday
with stops in Texas, possibly to visit hurricane-damaged areas,
while devoting much of the rest of his week to preparations for
meeting his Republican rival in their first debate.
   Dukakis made drugs the focus of his California foray, and he
suggested the Reagan administration had slighted California in
favor of Florida in allocating anti-drug resources.
   ``Today you have less than half the number of DEA (Drug
Enforcement Admininstration) agents they have in Miami,'' Dukakis
told rookies at the Los Angeles Police Academy. ``That's going to
change.''
   California, the largest state with 47 electoral votes, is
considered a crucial battleground along with Texas for the Dukakis
campaign _ while Florida remains virtually out of reach and has
been the object of little personal campaigning by the candidate.
   However, his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, visited
Florida on Friday and today.
   Dukakis pledged to double the 2,800 DEA agents nationally over
five years, beginning with 600 next year, and to add 800 new
federal prosecutors in an effort to speed up handling of drug cases.
   Dukakis promised to send the first 100 drug agents to Southern
California, where he said cocaine seizures have risen 3,500 percent
during the Reagan years and there have been ``massive increases''
in drug-related deaths.
   Campaign aides said the prosecutors would cost $40 million and
the new drug agents would cost $50 million the first year. Dukakis
asserted that the agents would pay for themselves, however, through
seizure and forefeiture of assets.
   ``It's really a no-cost step,'' he told police officers in Chula
Vista, just south of San Diego.
   Outside the Chula Vista police station, Dukakis was greeted by
demonstrators needling him for his prison furlough policy, which
was changed in the face of public opposition.
   Several demonstrators wore mock prisoner's stripes. They
chanted, ``Let me out, I'll kill again.'' One carried a sign saying
``Hey Mike, thanks for the weekend.''
</TEXT>
