<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Defends Dukakis In South</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen stood in a downtown ballroom, on courthouse steps and
at a shuffleboard court _ in three different cities _ to deliver
the same message.
   ``I'm looking for old friends who wandered away in recent
years,'' he said. ``I'm talking to the Reagan Democrats. I'm urging
them to come home, and they're responding.''
   Bentsen, the Texas senator who Michael Dukakis picked as running
mate to help woo the South, spoke Friday morning in a Memphis hotel
and in the afternoon at the Pitt County, N.C., courthouse in
Greenville.
   There, he spiced his stump speech with a rebuke of Vice
President George Bush's attempts to denigrate Dukakis' performance
as Massachusetts governor.
   ``Under Mike Dukakis, Massachusetts unemployment is the lowest
rate of any major industrial state in this union,'' he said.
``Wages are growing twice as fast as the national average, personal
income growing faster than any other state, and he submitted ten
balanced budgets in a row.
   ``When George Bush speaks out against Mike Dukakis. We should
all remember that when it came to speaking out against arms to
Iran, when it came to speaking out against cozy deals with Gen.
(Manuel Antonio) Noriega of Panama, when it came to speaking out
against economic policies that have almost tripled the national
debt, Geoge Bush didn't speak, he just voted present.
   ``I'll tell you, when it comes to strong leadership, George Bush
has got himself a bad case of laryngitis.''
   By evening, Bentsen was in Palm Beach, Fla., in a trailer park's
shuffleboard area next to a Coast Guard Cutter, where he tailored
his speech with an attack on the Reagan administration and Bush for
failure in the fight against drug imports.
   ``They asked him to lead'' the fight against drugs, he said.
``And he blew it badly.'' Bentsen was joined by Sen. Lawton Chiles,
D-Fla., an old friend from Washington who also accompanied him to
Panama City.
   The Palm Beach stop also included a ritzy, closed-door
fund-raiser at the home of a prominent attorney. About $50,000 was
raised for Bentsen's Senate re-election campaign.
   Under an unusual Texas law, Bentsen is running both for the vice
presidency and a fourth term in the U.S. Senate.
   The vice presidential campaign, which had been bogged down by
scheduling difficulties the day before, appeared to be picking up
the pace. ``We've had a helluva good day,'' Bentsen told reporters
on his campaign plane.
   Bentsen was returning to Washington this afternoon and heading
back on Monday to his home state of Texas to resume campaigning.
   Bentsen expressed relief that Hurricane Gilbert appeared to be
going ashore in a sparsely-populated area of Mexico. In addition to
his general concerns about Texas, Bentson's father has a ranch in
the Rio Grande valley near Brownsville, which apparently was being
spared major damage.
</TEXT>
