<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   09-17 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Shifts Focus From Law Enforcement, Patriotism To Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis pledged in California to fight the nation's drug
problem with more spending and more hiring, while George Bush
questioned his rival's sincerity on defense issues as both
candidates planned for the first presidential debate of the
campaign.
   In a speech Friday at the Los Angeles Police Academy, the
Democratic presidential nominee told recruits he would double the
number of Drug Enforcement Administration agents over the next five
years, paying for the increase with cash and other assets seized in
drug busts. Dukakis also pledged to hire 800 more federal
prosecutors.
   ``We're going to send a message to drug kingpins,'' he said.
``As far as Mike Dukakis is concerned, there's nowhere you can run,
there's nowhere you can sail, there's nowhere you can hide. There
will be no safe haven for dope peddlers and drug profits anywhere
on this Earth.''
   But Dukakis, in a later appearance, mistakenly said that DEA
agents at one point had to hold a bake sale to raise stakeout
money. Aides explained that the book that was the source of that
anecdote said the bake sale was held to raise money for drug
education.
   Bush, the Republican nominee, spent much of the day in Ohio,
where he derided what he called Dukakis' shifting positions on
defense.
   ``You cannot fool the Soviet leadership by knocking America's
defense for 10 years and then riding around in a tank for 10
minutes,'' Bush said Friday in Columbus, Ohio, making light of
Dukakis' well-filmed visit to a tank design facility. ``You can't
fool the American people.''
   Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, combined that
criticism with a jab at Dukakis' farm policy by referring to his
statement that cash grain and livestock farmers should consider
alternative crops such as Belgian endive and blueberries.
   Contending that Dukakis is out of touch with Middle America,
Quayle told an audience in Omaha, Neb.: ``I decided to sum it up
this way: His farm policy is the Belgian endive and his defense
policy is the Belgian waffle.''
   Quayle was finishing a five-day swing of Midwest and Plains
states.
   Quayle's Democratic counterpart, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, took
special aim during an appearance in Greenville, N.C., at Bush's
claim Thursday that Dukakis mismanaged Massachusetts' fiscal
affairs.
   ``When George Bush speaks out against Mike Dukakis,'' he said,
``we should all remember that when it came to speaking out against
arms to Iran, when it came to speaking out against cozy deals with
Gen. Noriega of Panama, when it came to speaking out against
economic policies that have almost tripled the national debt,
George Bush didn't speak, he just voted present.''
   Both Bush and Dukakis ran into some turbulence while campaigning.
   Outside the Chula Vista, Calif., police station, Dukakis was
greeted by demonstrators needling him for his prison furlough
policy, which was changed in the face of public opposition.
   Several demonstrators wore mock prisoner's stripes. They
chanted, ``Let me out, I'll kill again.'' One carried a sign saying
``Hey Mike, thanks for the weekend.''
   In Findlay, Ohio, where the annual flag celebration was held
Friday, some residents complained Bush had turned it into a
political photo opportunity.
   ``What was intended to be a non-partisan promotion of fun and
patriotism has turned into a partisan use of the flag for private
gain by a candidate,'' said local businessman Neil Scott.
   The vice president returned to Washington, where Dukakis also
was headed to meet with members of the Congressional Black Caucus
at a dinner that Jesse Jackson was also expected to attend.
   Both men have set aside large parts of next week to prepare for
their first debate of the fall presidential campaign, a 90-minute
nationally televised session a week from Sunday in Winston-Salem,
N.C.
   In Washington, members of the Dukakis campaign, the Democratic
National Committee and Jesse Jackson's National Rainbow Coalition
stressed unity during a news conference in which they announced a
stepped-up registration and get-out-the-vote effort aimed at
minority voters.
   Joseph Warren, the general election coordinator for the Dukakis
campaign, said the drive targets 42 cities in 14 states. The
Democratic Party will ``take the lead'' in the campaign, which will
try to register 2 million new voters and win a minimum 70 percent
black voter participation in the Nov. 8 election.
</TEXT>
