<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Deaver     09-17 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaver,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conflicting Testimony On Whether Alcoholism Hurt Deaver's Memory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge who will sentence Michael K. Deaver
for perjury is pondering sharply conflicting testimony about
whether alcoholism impaired the former presidential aide's memory
when he gave sworn testimony.
   Dr. William Flynn, Deaver's doctor during two hospital visits
for alcoholism in 1985 and 1986, said the former White House aide
likely suffered memory impairment from tranquilizers he took for
alcohol withdrawal.
   But Ralph Tarter, an alcoholism expert testifying for the
prosecution, said ``motivational reasons rather than neurological
reasons'' best explained Deaver's failures of recollection under
oath.
   Attorneys for Deaver offered two days of medical testimony to
show that alcoholism should be considered a mitigating factor when
the former presidential aide is sentenced for lying when his
lobbying was investigated for possible ethics-law violations.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is scheduled to
sentence Deaver on Sept. 23. The former deputy White House chief of
staff faces a possible five-year sentence and a $6,800 fine for
each of three perjury counts.
   Deaver was found guilty last year of lying when he said he
couldn't recall contacting former Reagan administration colleagues
on behalf of major corporations who paid him six-figure fees for
his services.
   Flynn, head of the alcoholism and drug abuse clinic at
Georgetown University Hospital, testified that Deaver
``definitely'' suffered memory and judgment impairments during two
hospital stays for detoxification.
   But on cross-examination, Flynn admitted to independent counsel
Whitney North Seymour Jr. that he never tested Deaver for memory
loss during the hospital stays and meant to say that ``people in
that situation have impaired memory and judgment.''
   Flynn also provided another piece of circumstantial evidence
that Deaver telephoned then-Secretary Elizabeth Dole on behalf of
Trans Word Airlines.
   Deaver was talking on the phone at 5 p.m. June 3, 1985 when he
first entered the former presidential aide's room at the hospital,
Flynn said. A log kept by Mrs. Dole's secretary that was produced
at the trial showed Deaver had called the Cabinet official at
precisely that hour.
   Among other things, Deaver was convicted of lying when he told a
federal grand jury on June 20, 1986 that ``I don't recall any
government contact I made on behalf of TWA.''
   The defense is trying to show that Deaver honestly couldn't
recall the telephone contact because he was drugged and suffering
from alcoholic withdrawal.
   But Flynn, who testified that Deaver later took heavy doses of
the tranquilizer Valium to counteract alcohol withdrawal, said the
former White House aide was neither drunk nor sedated by a dose of
Librium he took 30 minutes earlier.
   The defense countered with Dr. Dolores Morgan, a Miami physician
who treats alcoholics.
   She said medical records showed that by 1985 when Deaver had
resigned from President Reagan's staff his alcoholism had reached
an advanced stage.
   Kidney failure that kept Deaver from attending Reagan's second
inaugural in January 1985 was ``a classic example'' of the medical
complications of alcoholism, she said. It was misdiagnosed as an
allergic reaction to blood-pressure medicine because Deaver didn't
tell doctors he was drinking heavily.
   Morgan said Deaver probably understated his problem when he told
Flynn and other doctors six months later that he had only recently
started drinking more than a fifth of Scotch whisky a day.
   On appeal, the defense is expected to repeat arguments that
improper trial rulings by the judge put Deaver at a strategic
disadvantage that prevented him from testifying.
   The defense, confronted with these rulings from the bench, chose
to rest its case without calling Deaver or any of the medical
experts who were prepared to testify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SeabrookLicense     09-17 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook License,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seabrook Finances Now Lone Obstacle To Low-Power License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission says the idled Seabrook, N.H., reactor will not get a
low-power operating license until regulators are convinced the
plant's owners are financially stable.
   But Seabrook officials, buoyed by a commission vote Friday that
removed the only other regulatory obstacle to gaining the license,
said they will begin immediately preparing the reactor for
low-power testing in anticipation of a license.
   The NRC voted 4-0 for a rules ``clarification'' that will allow
nuclear plants to receive low-power permits without an emergency
siren system in place to alert neighbors within 10 miles of the
reactors of an atomic emergency.
   Commission regulations say financial qualification should not be
a consideration for a low-power license, but NRC Chairman Lando W.
Zech Jr. said there are extenuating circumstances in the Seabrook
case. For the first time, he said, Seabrook's finances would be a
factor in consideration of a low-power license.
   ``It's a serious issue,'' Zech told reporters after the hearing.
``We'll be watching closely to see the financial qualification
situation at Seabrook.''
   Zech's concerns focused on Public Service Company of New
Hampshire, a partial Seabrook owner which filed for bankruptcy
reorganization last January.
   ``In my judgment, bankruptcy is a special case,'' the chairman
said. ``... We should be satisfied that bankruptcy will not prevent
safe, low-power operation.''
   Massachusetts communities within Seabrook's 10-mile zone fought
successfully to have the emergency sirens removed. State officials
led by Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee,
believe those coastal towns, with their narrow roads and bulging
summer populations, would not be able to evacuate quickly. The new
rule takes effect in 30 days.
   Edward Brown, president of the reactor's owner, New Hampshire
Yankee, hailed the commission vote as ``another major step forward
for Seabrook.''
   Dukakis blasted the ruling, saying it ``defies logic and brings
new meaning to the word irresponsible.'' He derided the commission
as the ``Not Responsible Commission'' and said it ``is experiencing
a meltdown in its thinking process.''
   The lone regulatory obstacle remaining for Seabrook's low-power
license is a petition filed by plant opponents charging that the
reactor's owners are financially unfit to operate the plant.
   That question was tentatively scheduled for a vote following the
siren issue, but was postponed.
   The idle $5.6 billion reactor is losing $50 million each month
in maintenance and finance costs.
   Martin Malsch, NRC deputy general counsel, said he hoped the
commission would have the issue resolved within a month.
   Seabrook officials said they were optimistic of a favorable
ruling.
   ``We feel we have proved to the commission that we are
financially qualified,'' said Ronald A. Sher, spokesman for New
Hampshire Yankee.
   If the NRC rules that the Seabrook owners are financially fit,
the plant would be eligible for a low-power license, which allows
it to run tests at 5 percent power.
   The owners need the 5 percent permit before securing a
full-power commercial license, while opponents say low-power
testing would contaminate the reactor with radioactive fuel and
make a future conversion to a gas-fired plant much more expensive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseContracting     09-17 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Contracting,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Truth-in-Contracting' Rules Loosened By Pentagon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has slightly relaxed the
``truth-in-contracting'' regulations it imposed after this summer's
disclosure of a massive fraud investigation. But it refused to drop
the rules altogether as industry asked.
   The Pentagon on Friday said its Defense Department Task Force on
Procurement ``has determined that both the Certificate of
Contractor Business Ethics and Integrity and the Profit Recapture
Clause remain necessary to protect the government's interests....''
   The certification and profit recapture regulations were imposed
July 15 against defense contractors named in search warrants
obtained by the Justice Department. Fifteen companies are currently
subject to the special requirements.
   The investigation, which became public in June, concerns
allegations that defense contractors hired outside consultants to
obtain proprietary information on the bids of competing defense
companies, and that the consultants may have paid bribes to
Pentagon employees to get such information.
   The certification clause requires any of the contractors who
receive a contract worth at least $100,000 to certify that they
have not obtained any inside information. The profit recapture
regulation specifies the Pentagon can reclaim profits from any
company that has obtained sensitive information improperly.
   The Pentagon said it was narrowing the application of the
certification rule by specifying the written pledge would be
required only when a contractor is competing with other firms to
start a new project.
   Under the initial version of the rule, if a contractor was on
the Pentagon's list, the requirement was imposed regardless of
whether the contract was sole-source or competitive, and regardless
of whether it was for the start of a project or to expand work
awarded to the company earlier.
   A Pentagon official who asked not to be named said the change
was designed to lighten somewhat industry fears that firms could be
held accountable now for actions that dated back several years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
