<DOCNO> AP880917-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BaseballNewspage     09-17 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baseball Newspage,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perfect Game For Cincinnati's Tom Browning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati's Tom Browning pitched the 14th
perfect game in major league baseball's 108-year history, breezing
past the Los Angeles Dodgers 1-0 Friday night.
   It also was the first no-hitter since the beginning of last
season. Six no-hit bids were broken up this season, including one
by the Reds' Browning.
   A pitcher achieves a perfect game by allowing no batter to reach
base.
   Browning, a 28-year-old left-hander, struck out seven Dodgers.
   In the ninth, Browning completed the game by getting Rick
Dempsey on a fly ball to Paul O'Neill at the warning track in left
field, Steve Sax on a grounder to shortstop and pinch-hitter Tracy
Woodson on a strikeout to end the game.
   The last no-hitter was April 15, 1987, by Milwaukee's Juan
Nieves against the Baltimore Orioles in the American League.
   The last perfect game was by California's Mike Witt, a 1-0
victory over California on Sept. 30, 1984, also in the American
League.
   The National League's last perfect game was Sept. 9, 1965, by
the Dodgers' Sandy Koufax against the Chicago Cubs.
</TEXT>
