<HEAD>Man Arrested For Allegedly Threatening Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FINDLAY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ohio man sitting in a downtown
restaurant was arrested after someone allegedly overheard him
making threatening remarks against Vice President George Bush on
the day of Bush's visit in the city.
   Police said Charles T. Rode Jr., 35, of Findlay allegedly made
threatening comments at approximately 9 a.m. Friday shortly before
Bush's arrival in this northwest Ohio city. Police and Secret
Service agents arrested Rode, who did not resist and was not
carrying a weapon, officials said.
   Rode was detained in Findlay until Bush left the city, and then
was taken to the Lucas County jail in Toledo, where he was being
held today without bond on a felony charge of threatening the vice
president.
   Bush was in Findlay for a half-hour speech during the city's
Flag City Festival.
