<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Tom Selleck says he fulfilled a childhood
dream by going to bat with the Baltimore Orioles and hitting two
home runs.
   The former ``Magnum P.I.'' star spent most of the summer in the
Baltimore area on location for ``Her Alibi,'' a romantic comedy
film in which he plays a mystery writer who becomes involved with a
murder suspect.
   Filming for the movie, which also stars model Paulina Porizkova,
wrapped up Friday.
   The highlight of the summer was the day Selleck went to batting
practice with the Baltimore Orioles at Memorial Stadium, where he
hit two home runs, he said.
   ``It was about 120 degrees on the field. I had a great time,''
said Selleck, who played baseball in college. ``They helped my
fulfill a childhood fantasy.''
   He said he plans to appear in several more movies, but will take
a five- or six-month hiatus first to spend time with his wife and
baby.
   ``I need to get away from the business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suzanne Blum, the lawyer who represented the Duke
and Duchess of Windsor for 40 years, said she was fulfilling the
duchess' wishes when she allowed the couple's private letters to be
published, a newspaper reported.
   But the Daily Telegraph on Friday said Mohammed al-Fayed, an
Egyptian businessman who has bought the duchess' house in Paris,
has challenged Ms. Blum's authority to publish the letters and is
demanding she return them.
   He claims Ms. Blum took the letters and other papers from the
house during the duchess' final illness and immediately after her
death in 1986, a charge Ms. Blum denies.
   Some of the correspondence was recently included in books by
Michael Bloch, Ms. Blum's protege.
   One book, ``The Secret File of the Duke of Windsor,'' revealed
that the former King Edward VIII, who abdicated the British throne
in 1936 to marry American divorcee Wallis Simpson, referred to
Queen Elizabeth II as ``Mrs. Temple Junior,'' and ``Shirley.''
   Ms. Blum, 89, told the newspaper she was given the letters by
the duchess, who wrote a letter authorizing Ms. Blum to publish
them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOMERSET HILLS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local YMCA has a new building,
thanks in part to two of the area's residents, King Hassan II of
Morocco and former Rep. Millicent Fenwick.
   The $3.5 million building was dedicated last week, when it was
revealed that the king donated $100,000 to the cause.
   Hassan, who lives part of the year on a 493-acre, $7.5 million
Tudor mansion in nearby Peapack-Gladstone, is rarely seen by
neighbors.
   But Fenwick, who got to know the Moroccan ambassador in Rome
during her own service there as an ambassador to a United Nations
agency, wrote the diplomat a letter asking if the king would
contribute money for a new building.
   ``He was enthusiastic. I was amazed,'' Fenwick, a Bernardsville
resident, said Thursday. ``He said that is just the kind of thing
the king is interested in.''
   Robert Ohaus, a member of the YMCA's board of directors, said
the king gave them a check last year made out in Arabic. ``All we
could read was the $100,000, but that was enough.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock musician Boz Scaggs has opened a new
club in an old brewery in the city's burgeoning nightclub district,
where he hopes blues and jazz musicians will find enthusiastic
audiences.
   ``Music that comes most easily and gets to people where they
need to be gotten fastest is rhythm and blues, blues and jazz,
which touches people. It's immediate,'' Scaggs said at Thursday
night's opening of Slim's.
   Advance tickets for performances Friday and tonight sold out
days before the 298-seat club's doors opened.
   Scaggs is the San Francisco-based rock star of the 1970s who was
known for a sophisticated soul and rock sound. His hits included
``Lowdown,'' ``Lido Shuffle,'' and ``Loan Me A Dime.''
   Earlier this year, he released his first album in several years,
``Other Roads,'' which featured a softer, more toned-down sound
than he had earlier in his career.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors IV, who makes about 40
speeches each year on his Christian faith, said he has no problem
reconciling the message with his family's ownership of a major
brewery.
   ``I'm not one who says that a glass of beer or wine is wrong,''
Coors, whose grandfather founded the Colorado brewery that bears
his name, said after addressing a prayer breakfast Friday. The
brewery is run by his uncles and cousins, he said.
   Coors said he occasionally takes a glass of beer or wine with
his meals.
   ``The first miracle Christ performed was at a wedding feast,''
Coors said, ``when he turned water into wine. It wasn't grape
juice. It wasn't Kool-Aid. It was wine.''
   ``If it starts to control you, that's when you have a problem
and it's wrong,'' he said. ``The Bible says do everything in
moderation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne of Britain presented rosettes at
a riding school for the disabled after watching handicapped
horseback riders perform a traditional Chinese fan dance.
   The princess, the daughter of Queen Elizabeth, viewed
performances by disabled children and adults and spoke with
performers, volunteers and horse trainers during her visit Friday
to the Pokfulam Public Riding School.
   Anne, president of the British charity Save the Children, also
visited the organization's Hong Kong office and was briefed on the
organization's aid to Vietnamese refugees who have sailed into this
British colony.
   She planned to visit to two Vietnamese refugee camps today,
including a 12-story factory building that houses more than 4,000
people.
