<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     09-17 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Backs Administration Stance On Soviet Radar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has reiterated its overwhelming
support of the Reagan administration's contention that a giant
Soviet radar system violates the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   ``These violations are a threat to the security of the United
States,'' said Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., author of the
resolution that won 81-0 approval after only brief debate on the
issue Friday.
   It was the third vote in two years on the issue. The earlier
votes were 89-0 and 93-2.
   The dispute involves the Soviet radar station at Krasnoyarsk,
which the United States has argued is a violation of the 1972 pact
limiting defensive systems that each superpower can build. The
Soviets dispute the U.S. contention.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, without admitting any
violation, had proposed earlier in the day the Russians would be
willing to allow the radar station to be used as an international
space tracking system as part of an exchange for U.S. closure of
military bases in the Phillippines.
   The Senate's non-binding resolution said the radar station
question should be settled before there are any new U.S.-Soviet
agreements on limiting long-range atomic weapons.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Brady Sworn In As 68th Treasury Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicolas F. Brady has become the nation's 68th
secretary of the Treasury.
   With his wife Kitty standing at his side in the ornate Roosevelt
Room of the White House and pledging to aggressively push Reagan
administration economic policies, Brady, 58, was sworn in on Friday
by retired Supreme Court Justice Warren E. Burger.
   ``Your leadership has produced the longest sustained period of
prosperity in most Americans' memories,'' the Wall Street
investment banker told the president after finishing the
oath-taking. ``Not only have the economic statistics turned out to
be right, but what is more important is that they have meant better
lives for Americans.''
   Brady, co-chairman of the Wall Street firm of Dillon Read & Co.,
who headed the commission Reagan set up last year to investigate
the circumstances behind the Oct. 19 stock market crash, said the
Treasury Department under his leadership would ``do its homework''
to advance Reagan's policies on taxes and spending.
   Brady succeeds James A. Baker III, who left Treasury last month
to become chairman of George Bush's presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Korean War Memorial To Be Built on Washington Mall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial honoring the 5.7 million Americans
who served in the Korean War will be placed on the Mall in
Washington, near the Lincoln Memorial and opposite the Vietnam
Memorial.
   Approval of the site in Ash Woods, a grove of trees on the south
side of the Reflecting Pool in front of the Lincoln Memorial, was
announced Friday by Secretary of the Interior Don Hodel.
   The announcement marks the end of the site approval process
required by law.
   A nationwide competition, similar to the one for the Vietnam
Memorial, will be held for the design. The $6 million memorial will
be built with private funds and Gen. Richard Stilwell, chairman of
the Korean War Veterans Memorial Advisory Board has announced that
$2.4 million has already been raised.
   The Korean War ended July 27, 1953. There were 54,246 American
fatalities and 103,284 wounded.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Navy To Launch New Ship in New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy says it will launch a new amphibious
landing ship during ceremonies in New Orleans today, weather
permitting.
   The ceremony for the Tortuga, an LSD-class dock landing ship, is
set to begin at 10 a.m. at the Avondale Industries' shipyard in New
Orleans.
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., is scheduled to deliver the
principal speech.
   The Navy said Friday in its announcement that the ceremony might
be canceled at the last moment, depending upon the effects of
Hurricane Gilbert. The hurricane was in the Gulf of Mexico and
closing on Texas Friday afternoon.
   The Tortuga, 609 feet long, 84 feet wide and displacing about
15,726 tons when fully loaded, is the second U.S. Navy ship to be
named after a group of coral islets located off the coast of Key
West, Fla.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Former Intelsat Official Pleads Guilty to Fraud Conspiracy Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former No. 2 executive of Intelsat has
pleaded guilty to conspiracy to defraud the global satellite giant
of $4.8 million.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Friday set Dec. 5 as
the sentencing date for Jose L. Alegrett, former deputy director
general of the International Telecommunications Satellite
Organization, a consortium of 115 member countries that operates a
network of telecommunications satellites.
   Alegrett faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine or both.
   Alegrett, fired from Intelsat in December 1986, was the fourth
person found guilty of the intricate scheme involving unauthorized
payments, bid-rigging, kickbacks and phony commissions in
connection with the construction of the company's headquarters
here.
</TEXT>
