<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Hurricane 7thLd-Writethru a0845 09-17 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Hurricane, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0845,0973</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Left Homeless By Hurricane Gilbert; Makes Landfall In
Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE death toll from 17 to 21 in
Yucatan, picks up graf 16 pvs `The mayor...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert powered into Mexico's
eastern coast Friday for the second time in three days, forcing
thousands of residents from their homes after killing at least 21
people on the Yucatan Peninsula.
   Heavy rains from the storm also drowned eight people in
Honduras, where officials said about 6,000 people were homeless and
27,000 acres of crops were destroyed.
   The eye of the hurricane crossed onto land at 5:35 p.m. EDT
(4:35 p.m. CDT), sweeping ashore 120 miles south of Brownsville,
Texas, the National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla., said in
a statement. Brownsville is just across the Rio Grande from
Matamoros, a city of 280,000 people.
   Gilbert _ a 450-mile-wide hurricane with winds of 120 mph _ made
landfall just north of La Pesca, a fishing village on the Gulf of
Mexico. The coastal plain in that zone is sparsely populated.
   The confirmed Mexico death toll rose to 21, Jorge Galicia of the
National Civil Defense System told The Associated Press early
Saturday. All occurred in the three Yucatan peninsula states of
Campeche, Yucatan and Quintana Roo.
   Authorities said Friday that 10 people were missing in the
Yucatan state.
   The mayor of Soto la Marina, 20 miles inland from La Pesca, was
contacted by The Associated Press as the storm struck his town of
8,000 residents.
   Mayor Hinojosa Cortina said the situation in Soto la Marina was
``getting worse with every passing minute. There are very strong
winds. It's all dark. There is no electricity and no water. Trees
have been uprooted.''
   Cortina said some residents had fled the town in advance of the
hurricane but many remained. Other town officials said 3,000 people
from fishing villages along the coast were given shelter in Soto la
Marina.
   Many streets in Matamoros were flooded and officials said about
5,000 people fled their homes in low-lying coastal areas.
   At 9 p.m. EDT (8 p.m. CDT), the eye of the hurricane was near
latitude 24.4 north, longitude 98.1 west, or about 110 miles south
southwest of Brownsville, the National Hurricane Center said.
   It said Gilbert was moving toward the west-northwest at 12 mph.
The report said flash floods and tides of 7 to 11 feet above normal
were expected near and to the north of where the storm came ashore.
   Monterrey, an industrial city with a population of about three
million, is the closest major city that could be affected. It is
210 miles northwest of La Pesca but Sierra de Tamaulipas, a small
mountain range between Monterrey and the coast, should blunt the
hurricane's strentth, said Mark Zimmer, a meterologist at National
Hurricane Center.
   He said the range should break up circulation of hurricane and
accelerate drop in wind speed, which naturally occurs when storm
moves over land. But Zimmer said he expects very heavy rains as
warm hurricane winds rise into cooler mountain air. This could
cause flash floods and mudslides, he said.
   The hurricane struck the Mexican coast first Wednesday morning,
roaring into the Yucatan Peninsula.
   About 300,000 people were homeless in Yucatan State and 10,000
more were homeless in Campeche on the west coast of the peninsula,
the government news agency Notimex said.
   The mayor of Cancun, on the east coast of the peninsula, said
11,000 tourists and residents were evacuated from beachfront areas
before the storm hit.
   Power and communications were still out in much of Yucatan,
thousands of people remained in shelters, many areas were flooded
and transportation was only partially restored.
   The Cancun and Cozumel airports opened Friday, allowing 8,000
tourists to begin leaving the popular Caribbean resorts.
   The damage ``looks awesome and spectacular,'' Tourism Secretary
Antonio Enriquez Savignac said during an appearance on the private
Televisa network Friday after returning from a flight over the area.
   Matamoros, only 25 feet above sea level and 12 miles from shore,
lacks natural wind breaks such as hills or high buildings.
Authorities said their main worry was flooding, which already
affected some streets.
   Officials said about 5,000 people spent Thursday night in
shelters. Countless others already have fled the city for towns
farther inland, while thousands waited out the hurricane behind
boarded or taped doors and windows.
   ``Our house started flooding, so we called the police and they
brought us here,'' said Maria Crecencia Vazquez, a 45-year-old
mother of 10 who sought shelter in a church meeting hall, one of
126 shelters set up in Matamoros.
   The refugees, mostly poor families, said they spent all night
Thursday in the shelters without food or blankets.
   ``They closed a lot of stores because too many people were
packing in,'' said Jose Padilla, 29. ``Most of us didn't get any
food.''
   The Matamoros airport was closed at midmorning.
   About 100 miles south of La Pesca, heavy winds and rains pounded
the oil port of Tampico where 30 ships were anchored. Power was cut
in some areas and the airport and coastal highway were closed,
according to El Sol de Tampico, the local paper.
   Nearly 1,000 miles away from Matamoros, across the Gulf of
Mexico, much of the Yucatan Peninsula was in tatters.
   Glbert caused hundreds of millions of dollars in damages as it
rolled across three states of the peninsula destroying 90 per cent
of the corn and fruit crops.
   But tourism officials were optimistic they could put Cancun and
Cozumel back in working order in six weeks, in time for the height
of the fall and winter season.
</TEXT>
