<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia     09-17 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Burst Into Court Building and Free Five Comrades; One
Hostage Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed left-wing rebels burst into a
federal court building, freed five jailed comrades and abducted a
judge's assistant, who was later found shot to death, police said.
   They said the guerrillas fired automatic weapons as they entered
the building in the town of Buga, 160 miles southwest of Bogota.
   Police said they captured two of the guerrillas freed in the
attack after an hourlong chase. The body of the hostage was found
beside a highway outside of town, police said.
   They did not report any other casualties or further elaborate.
   In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 government
soldiers and policemen captured in a northwestern Colombia raid
last month and also released two Colombian geologists seized in
another attack, the government and military announced.
   The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisoner
Aug. 23 by guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army and the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces during a joint attack on the
town of Saiza.
   A statement from President Virgilio Barcos's office said a
one-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could be
released in the Uraba region, about 300 miles northwest of Bogota.
   Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocket
and mortar attack on the police station in Saiza, Gen. Jesus Arias
said in an interview with the radio station RCN. He did not
elaborate.
   The two geologists released Thursday were among five who worked
with coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 by rebels of another
guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, or ELN.
   Rebels freed the two geologists in an arranged meeting with a
group of reporters in the city of Bucaramanga, 200 miles northeast
of Bogota.
   An ELN statement said the three other geologists would be
released soon.
   A Defense Ministry communique released Friday said 1,174 people
have been killed this year in guerrilla attacks and battles between
rebels and security forces.
   It listed the slain as 499 guerrillas, 378 civilians and 297
policemen and soldiers.
   The ministry has reported 2,037 people were killed last year in
fighting involving rebels, government forces and civilians caught
in the violence.
</TEXT>
