<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Bases     09-17 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Bases,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino: U.S., Soviets Must Decide on Gorbachev Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
it was up to the United States and the Soviet Union to decide
whether to maintain or pull out their bases in Southeast Asia.
   Mrs. Aquino was responding to an offer Friday by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to abandon a strategic naval base in Vietnam
if the United States would abandon its bases in the Philippines.
   ``That is for the two superpowers to discuss and to talk
about,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters at the presidential palace.
   Gorbachev made the offer in a speech in which he outlined a
seven-point plan for defusing tension in Asia. His call came
against a backdrop of growing opposition to the U.S. bases in the
Philippines.
   Earlier today, Sen. Leticia Shahani belittled Gorbachev's
pullout offer, saying the Soviet and U.S. military facilities were
not ``comparable.''
   Ms. Shahani, chairwoman of the Senate's Foreign Relations
Committee, said the U.S.-run Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay Naval
Base were ``far bigger complexes'' than the Kremlin's base at Cam
Ranh Bay, Vietnam.
   Ramon Mitra, speaker of the House of Representatives said: ``It
is us (Filipinos) who will chart our own foreign policy.'' But his
deputy Antonio Cuenco said Gorbachev's offer was a ``sound
proposal.''
   Mrs. Aquino said Friday said she hoped the Philippines and the
United States could resolve their differences in talks over the
U.S. bases despite a deadlock over compensation and other issues.
   She said Filipino Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus, who is in
the United States, and Secretary of State George Shultz were trying
to narrow differences ``so I'm hoping they will.''
   On Thursday, Shultz said in Washington that the United States
wanted to keep Clark, Subic and four other installations in the
Philippines but that Manila's demands for more money were too high.
   ``There are alternatives which we are having now to examine,''
Shultz said shortly after meeting with Manglapus, chief of the
Philippine panel in the stalled bases talks that began in April.
   U.S. officials say Washington is considering moving the bases to
Guam or other sites.
   The United States pays about $180 million a year for use of the
six bases.
   Manglapus has said the Americans have offered about $502 million
in compensation but added the $1.2 billion annual Phillipine demand
is ``reasonable.''
   Cam Ranh Bay is the Soviets' major naval deployment base abroad,
while Clark and Subic are the United States's largest foreign bases.
   The United States says its bases are essential to prevent Soviet
military expansion in the Far East.
   About 40,000 troops, military dependents and Defense Department
civilians are stationed at the six bases in the Philippines, which
employ about 42,000 Filipinos. Annual salaries to Filipino
civilians total more than $83 million, the second largest payroll
after the Philippine government.
</TEXT>
