<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Clark, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0402,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastside Principal Joe Clark To Enter Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to say that Clark's school is in Paterson</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard-nosed principal Joe Clark, saying
``we've had enough of liberals,'' declared he's ready to expand his
tough talk beyond the halls of Eastside High School and run for
public office.
   Clark told several reporters and about 50 supporters Friday
night that he's running for Essex County Freeholder as a Republican
because he wants to inject his conservative philosophy into
politics.
   Clark gained national attention this past year as a
disciplinarian known for roaming the halls of his Paterson school
with a baseball bat and bullhorn. Some have criticized his tactics
as more flash than substance and condemned him for intimidating
students.
   Others ranging from newspaper editorial writers to the Reagan
administration credit Clark as an example of a tough black urban
educator who brought law and order to a rowdy, inner-city school.
   ``Don't look at the color of my skin,'' Clark said Friday.
``Look at me because of the contents of my ability.''
   Clark, who said he wouldn't give up his job as principal if he
won the election, was selected for the November ticket by a group
of county Republicans, said John P. Renna, chairman of the Essex
County Republican Party.
   ``We selected him because he has an excellent background,''
Renna said. ``He has an aggressive personality. He's nationally
known.''
   For his part, Clark said he was running because ``we've had
enough of liberals.''
   The principal will face Democratic nominee Leroy J. Jones Jr., a
finance manager for AT&T. ``I think everybody's entitled to the
political arena,'' Jones commented. ``I look forward to the
challenge.''
</TEXT>
