<DOCNO> AP880917-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hurricane-Galveston     09-17 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Galveston,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late A.L. Donahue, a native Texan who later
lived in Arizona, was 18 in September 1900 when a hurricane struck
Galveston Island just before midnight, killing 6,000 people. It was
the worst natural disaster in U.S. history. Here's his account of
that storm, as written, from his journal of some years later:
   It was on a Saturday and the wind was blowing from the south,
coming in from the Gulf and gradually increasing its velocity as
the day wore on.
   I and one or two of my brothers were cutting red-top cane by
hand and standing it in large round shocks. ...
   The clouds come up about the middle of the morning and got
thicker as the hours passed, and about 3:30 in the afternoon I
could head a deep low sound of thunder in the southeast and as it
slowly come close and closer, the very ground that I stood on would
vibrate for long periods. And the wind was increasing, and the
clouds looked nearly as black as bellows of coal smoke and (were)
down close to the tree tops.
   All birds stopped their singing and no cricket or frog made any
sound, just the wind and the continued sound of heavy thunder is
all that you could hear.
   There is a helpless feeling that accompanies any real storm
cloud for all of nature's life of low or high cast. ... (one has)
no idea just how unimportant and small and helpless a storm can
make anyone feel, and this storm on that September day is the
darkest of my memory.
   The waves come over the (50-foot) seawalls ... (and) all was
confusion. You could hear screams for help and the prayers and
cries of the drowning above the sound of the thunders and rolling
billows of the deep as they come in and over the entire town.
   In one of the higher buildings ... the third floor held the
central telephone switchboard, and the girls on duty stayed until
the water come through the windows and then all soon was washed out
into the tempest of surging water.
   Timbers, trees, logs, houses, people, horses, cattle, hogs, dogs
and chickens, turkeys and other animals and fowls was all mixed in
those waves as they come in and swept back out to sea, carrying in
their undercurrent everything that was caught as they boiled up
over and down and under, then back to repeat the same action over
and over for 12 to 14 hours.
   There was a Society Ball held on the third floor of a brick
building. They danced and sang and prayed, cried and screamed but
the music continued until the waves come through the windows and
all (were) taken.
   (When daylight finally came, ``a death-shrouded dawn,'' he was
in the water.)
   There was a young woman bobbed up right near holding to a heavy
timber with one hand and under the other arm she held a baby or a
small child, and soon as she could she cried for help. I was near
on a timber or timbers that seemed to be the wood ceiling of a
large room. I could almost reach out and catch them, but ... as I
was about to get a good hold, the bottom fell out of where we was
and everything went down and down. But I still stayed with my
timbers and when I come to the surface again and got the salt water
out of my face and eyes, I looked in every direction, and by the
flashes of lightning I saw my young lady again, but she was not
close and she did not have that child. ... Very soon there was a
mountain of water between she was and me ... and I never seen her
any more to know it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Donahue became an oil millionaire in Texas but lost his wealth
when Texas banks failed during the Great Depression. He and his
family moved to Arizona and he made his living by making saleable
items from cactus and clay and by gathering Gila monsters,
rattlesnakes and lizards for sale to reptile gardens.
   He was also known for making archaeological finds, and artifacts
from his collection are to be found in the Smithsonian Institution
and Arizona museums today.
   The account of the Galveston storm in Donahue's journal is part
of the family archives of his daughter, Dorothy Strait of Chandler,
and was made available with her permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
