<DOCNO> AP880917-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Indictment-Marcos     09-17 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indictment-Marcos,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Clears Legal Hurdles in Marcos Indictment, Newspaper
Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials have overcome major legal
obstacles in their case against Ferdinand Marcos and it is now
likely they will ask a federal grand jury to indict the former
Philippine president for fraud, the Los Angeles Times reported
today.
   However, the indictment is expected to deal only with
accusations of wrongdoing after Marcos left office in February
1986, the newspaper said.
   The case was narrowed to overcome doubts about whether U.S. law
could apply to the deposed president's alleged efforts to
misappropriate billions of dollars in Philippine taxpayers' funds,
according to anonymous sources cited by the newspaper.
   The indictment, anticipated for months, has been delayed by a
number of circumstances.
   Acting Associate Attorney General Francis A. Keating II
expressed reservations at one point about the quality of the case
when draft charges were brought before him.
   The investigation is now focusing on allegations that Marcos and
his wife, Imelda, conspired with Saudi Arabian financier Adnan
Khashoggi and others to violate U.S. district court injunctions.
They allegedly secretly transferred ownership of hundreds of
millions of dollars in stolen art and Manhattan real estate bought
with Philippine government funds.
   Court records in related civil lawsuits allege that Marcos took
control of the funds while he was still in power but used elaborate
schemes involving front companies and agents to hide his ownership
and liquidate properties after he went into exile in Hawaii.
   The inter-agency Police Review Group, which became more
prominent in the wake of the diplomatically embarrassing attempt to
prosecute Panamanian strongman Manuel A. Noriega on federal drug
charges in Florida, helped settle problems with the legal case
early in the week, the Times said.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani in New York, along with his
staff, outlined details of proposed criminal charges against Marcos
at a White House meeting of the review group Tuesday, The Times
said. President Reagan did not attend.
   Intelligence advisers are expected next week to offer their
opinions on how the case could affect foreign relations.
   In a statement issued from the Philippine embassy in Washington,
D.C., Severina Rivera, general counsel for his government's
Presidential Commission on Good Government, said:
   ``There has been considerable skepticism in Manila about
President Reagan's willingness to approve the indictment of Mr.
Marcos. ... If he approves it, Filipinos everywhere will applaud
Mr. Reagan and the American system of justice that applies the full
force of the law to corrupt dictators who violate U.S. laws.''
   However, some concern has been expressed that Marcos may flee to
Mexico or another country because the indictment is imminent, a
source told The Times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-17 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Carl Peve and two members of the
village board have quit in a pig-headed dispute over pork
sandwiches and control of a town festival.
   A third village board member is threatening to resign after a
board meeting this week failed to resolve questions about who
should monitor the annual Lafayette Reunion Days.
   ``I'm done. I'm through being called names and having people
wave their fists in my face,'' said Mayor Peve.
   The dispute concerns an ordinance empowering the village board
to oversee the activities of a committee that organizes summer
festivals.
   Gene Scott, president of this year's organizing group, the
Reunion Committee, said the three-day festival in August was a
success and drew more than 1,500 visitors to the town of 277.
   But Peve insists the committee needs to be monitored, and some
of the loudest squealing concerned the mayor's allegation that the
committee slaughtered several hogs and sold pork sandwiches without
having the meat properly inspected.
   Dennis Lovins of the Illinois Department of Agriculture said
meat products must be inspected before being sold. Scott, who noted
communities commonly slaughter hogs for fairs, said his only
mistake was in not asking people to make a donation for the
sandwiches instead of buying them.
   ``This town is supposed to be a community of little helpers, but
some members of the board got pigheaded and decided to play God and
butt into our business,'' Scott said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORTE MADERA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of items frequently touted
for ``safe sex'' made for some unsafe driving conditions.
   As many as 5,000 condoms still in their packages spilled onto a
highway Friday afternoon, but went unclaimed by the owner,
according to the California Highway Patrol.
   The two fast lanes of the southbound side of Highway 101 were
closed for about 30 minutes as three officers and several motorists
picked up the condoms, said CHP Officer Mark Peischke.
   Officer Mike Turnham said some of the people who helped to pick
up the hermetically sealed condoms took them home.
