<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForestFiresRdp     09-17 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires Rdp,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Wet Weekend Expected In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters looked
forward to another wet and cool weekend in Yellowstone National
Park, but elsewhere across the West forest fires continued to rage
under the whip of shifting winds.
   The fires that have affected half of the park's 2.2 million
acres stayed within containment lines although flames shot through
the park on Friday, with temperatures increasing to the mid-60s and
steady winds approaching 35 mph, authorities said.
   Today's forecast called for a chance of light snowshowers this
afternoon and temperatures in the 50s. Heavy winds also were
expected, but park spokeswoman Sonya Capek said the high humidity
and cool temperatures would keep the fires down.
   Firefighters in Glacier National Park in Montana were not as
lucky Friday. About 200 firefighters were forced to retreat from a
blaze after winds gusting to 40 mph pushed a wall of fire past
containment lines.
   ``It was just an incredible show,'' fire information officer Kim
Berns said of the 300-feet high flames.
   Shifting winds pushed the 34,500-acre fire up a drainage along
the northeast flank where crews were reconstructing lines that blew
out Thursday, Berns said.
   In Idaho, officials were throwing all available manpower and
equipment at a wilderness fire in the north-central Gospel Hump
Wilderness as wildfires continued to burn in most of the state's
national forests.
   ``I don't know if we're over the hump as far as the fire season
goes, but we've been saying we're guardedly optimistic,'' said
Sandi Sacher, an information officer at the Boise Interagency Fire
Center.
   Fires that have consumed more than 190,000 acres remained out of
control and outside wilderness boundaries in the Nez Perce,
Challis, Panhandle and Salmon national forests, she said.
   Firefighters in Washington state, meanwhile, contained three
large fires that have charred more than 70,000 acres.
   In Yellowstone, 30 Canadian firefighters arrived Friday to help
battle the flames burning within nearly 1.2 million acres of the
2.2 million-acre park. The ``helitak'' group was the first Canadian
crew to arrive on scene since the U.S. Forest Service accepted that
country's offer to help.
   The experienced firefighters are a first-attack group, which
fights flames from a helicopter, Capek said.
   This past week, firefighters took advantage of the wet cold
weather to strengthen existing lines around fires and extend the
lines. By Friday, 50 percent of the 335,500-acre North Fork fire,
the most troublesome of the blazes in the park, had been contained.
   Officials believe the rain and snow that fell in the park had
dampened fuels sufficiently so that only seven days of continued
dry weather would bring back the tinder-dry conditions that allowed
fires to grow by thousands of acres daily, said Denny Bungarz,
North Fork fire incident commander. Officials predicted they would
contain that blaze by mid-October.
   Military personnel were stationed on either side of U.S. Highway
191, the fire's western edge, to keep it from jumping the road.
   ``If you put two hot shot crews in competition with each other,
it's a situation of two plus two equals five,'' Bungarz said. ``I
think the Army and the Marines will react the same way.''
   About 700 Marines from Camp Pendleton in California arrived
Friday, bringing the military force in the park up to 4,100.
   Fire information officer Marvin Crocker said the Marines
probably would be out on the fire lines today.
   In Oakridge, Ore., a $5,000 reward was offered for information
leading to the arrest and conviction of the person responsible for
starting a forest fire burning in the Willamette National Forest.
   A fire patrol plane crew and witnesses have given fire
investigators solid leads about vehicles seen in the area when the
blaze was only about an acre in size, forest officials said.
   The fire had grown to 7,300 acres Friday, but Forest Service
officials predicted it would be contained by next week and
controlled by the end of the month.
</TEXT>
