<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kurdistan     09-17 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kurdistan,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Presents Kurds Who Support Baghdad, Condemn Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSUL, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq, trying to counter charges it used
poison gas against its Kurdish minority, brought foreign
correspondents to the heart of Kurdistan and paraded Kurds who
denounced the rebels and praised Iraq.
   The local Kurds denied the government used poison gas against
them, and scorned the rebels who fled to Turkey last month.
   ``If one of them comes, I would drink his blood like water. They
are the traitors of our country,'' Naima Khader Hussein told
reporters Friday in Sulaymaniyah.
   She said her husband died fighting the rebels in 1985. Around
her were dozens of other relatives of Kurds killed by insurgents,
many holding pictures of their loved ones.
   The Iraqi government, infuriated by mounting Western charges
that it used poison gas to crush Kurdish insurgents, arranged the
one-day trip for journalists to show the accusations were baseless.
   Journalists from the around the world were flown by jetliner
Friday from Baghdad to the oil center of Kirkuk. There they boarded
Soviet MI-8 helicopters and flew to Sulaymaniyah, then on to Mosul
by dusk. There was also a side trip by bus to meet Kurdish refugees
who had accepted an amnesty program in Arbat, near Sulaymaniyah.
   Government officials in green uniforms hovered over each
interview and helped translate some Kurdish to Arabic and then to
English. They often cut off talks after a few minutes to rush
reporters on to the next engagement.
   At a new cinder block village, a group of Kurds greeted the
journalists, chanting: ``With blood and soul we sacrifice ourselves
for you Saddam,'' referring to President Saddam Hussein.
   Officials said the group came ``from dirty villages,'' but
several of them said they had moved from the city of Sulaymaniyeh
to take advantage of free houses.
   The towns themselves were busy, full of Kurdish men in sashed,
baggy trousers and distinctive head scarves.
   But the view during the helicopter flight from Sulaymaniyah
appeared to confirm reports that the government is relocating many
Kurds from remote villages into new concrete housing complexes and
destroying old settlements.
   Reporters saw several new housing complexes laid out in
geometric order near highways on the Kurdish plain.
   There were few if any villages of the traditional style visible
from the air, and dozens appeared demolished. A few were scorched
with fire.
   On Thursday, Defense Minister Adnan Khairallah said villagers
were being relocated away from the border for security reasons and
also to provide them with improved services.
   None of the Kurds brought forward by the government accused
Iraqi officials of knocking down villages.
   ``The rebels used to burn the villages and take the families
away,'' said Majid Karim Sharif in Arbat.
   Camp officials said more than 4,200 Kurds had returned to the
Arbat center, about 56 miles from the border with Iran, to take
advantage of the amnesty announced by the Iraqi government last
week.
   The government has said previously that more than 11,500 Kurds
have sought amnesty.
   In a separate development, a spokesman for the Kurdish rebels
claimed that 2,400 Kurdish civilians trapped in a mountain ravine
were killed in a poison gas attack Aug. 30 by Iraqi warplanes.
   Word of the alleged slaughter was delayed because it took the
handful of Kurds who survived the attack 10 days to reach southern
Turkey and contact rebel officials, the spokesman for the Kurdistan
Democratic Party reported in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press in Cyprus.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
victims were fleeing an Iraqi military offensive by trekking to
Turkey.
   He claimed the casualties raised the number of Kurds killed by
Iraqi chemical weapons since early August to around 4,300.
   The official also said that Kurdistan Democratic Party
guerrillas, battling an estimated 60,000 Iraqi troops pushing into
rebel-held mountains in northern Iraq, killed 140 in a major clash
several days ago.
</TEXT>
