<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gilbert's Strength Diminishes; Elswhere, Fair Skies the Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert was downgraded to a tropical storm this
morning as its sustained winds decreased to 65 mph, and the storm
was expected to further weaken as it continued on a west-northwest
course along the Texas-Mexico border.
   Elsewhere, fair weather conditions were the rule, except for
some rain in parts of Washington state and Montana, the northern
Rockies into the Plains, and the Great Lakes through the upper Ohio
Valley into the Tennessee Valley.
   Because of the Gilbert, tides of seven to 11 feet above normal
were reported from Brownsville to Port O'Conner in Texas and four
to six feet above normal elsewhere along the Texas coast.
   A tornado watch continued in parts of south Texas and adjacent
coastal waters this morning, and a flash flood watch remained in
effect for much of south Texas.
   More than 4{ inches of rain fell in Brownsville in 24 hours
ended early this morning.
   Showers and thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain to parts of
Alabama Friday, and numerous roads were under water. Flash flood
watches or warnings were in effect for much of the state.
   Today's national weather forecast called for thunderstorms due
to Gilbert in south-central and southwest Texas; and showers and
thunderstorms from the Gulf Coast states into the Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys, from the Carolinas to southern New
England, from the upper Ohio Valley to New York state, and from the
Pacific Northwest to Montana.
   High temperatures were expected in the 70s and 80s across much
of the nation.
   Highs were likely to approach 90 degrees in the central Plains,
and the middle Mississippi and lower Ohio valleys; 90 to 95 in
Florida and parts of the Gulf Coast states; 90s to about 100
degrees in the desert Southwest; 60s in the north Atlantic Coast
states and the Pacific; and 50s and 60s in Montana and Idaho.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33 degrees
at McCall, Idaho, to 84 at Homestead, Fla., Phoenix and the Naval
Air Station at Corpus Christi, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 64 rain; Boston 53 partly cloudy; Buffalo 65
showers; Charleston, S.C. 71 cloudy; Cincinnati 69 foggy; Cleveland
68 partly cloudy; Detroit 68 foggy; Miami 81 fair; New York 57
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 54 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 62
showers; Portland, Maine 44 fair; Washington 60 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 54 fair; Chicago 68 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
79 cloudy; Denver 52 fair; Des Moines 71 fair; Indianapolis 67
foggy; Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 61 fair; Nashville
70 rain; New Orleans 80 foggy; St. Louis 70 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 59 fair; Anchorage 49 cloudy; Las Vegas 74
fair; Los Angeles 62 hazy; Phoenix 83 fair; Salt Lake City 70
cloudy; San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 54 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 partly cloudy; Toronto 55 showers.
