<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Valerie'sLawsuit     09-17 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Valerie's Lawsuit,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valerie Harper Wins Court Battle Over Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Valerie Harper was awarded $1.85
million and a share of the profits from the show ``Valerie'' by a
jury that found the Lorimar production company acted in bad faith
in firing her.
   The jury foreman said the message of Friday's verdict was, ``You
just have to treat people fairly.''
   Miss Harper said she felt ``vindicated, gratified, thrilled''
with the verdict, which her lawyer said could earn the actress up
to $15 million.
   ``The truth did prevail,'' she told reporters. ``We won
financially. We won morally. I don't see any loss of any kind.''
   The Superior Court jury spent nearly a month hearing evidence
and took 4{ days to reach a complex verdict that required them to
answer more than 30 questions.
   Lorimar Telepictures Corp., which produces the NBC series,
originally sued Miss Harper, claiming she breached her contract by
quitting the show. A countersuit by the actress and her husband
contended she was wrongfully fired in August 1987. NBC and
individual producers were dropped from that suit during trial.
   The jury found that Miss Harper, her husband, Tony Cacciotti,
and their company, AV Productions, had lived up to their contracts
with Lorimar.
   But they said Lorimar acted ``in bad faith, without a reasonable
basis or probable cause'' by firing the actress.
   Jurors believed that Lorimar witnesses lied when they said Miss
Harper was out to ``submarine the show,'' said the jury foreman,
postal worker Archie McDaniels.
   The firm should not have held a crucial meeting in Miss Harper's
absence before firing her, he said.
   ``The television business is just like any other business,''
McDaniels said. ``You have good and bad. This verdict doesn't
condemn the TV industry. You just have to treat people fairly.''
   The panel awarded the $1.85 million in general damages for lost
wages, but declined to award punitive damages to Miss Harper and
her husband, who was a supervising producer on the NBC series.
   Miss Harper also was granted a 12{ percent share of adjusted
gross profits for the 1987-88 season, including fees for
syndication of the show. Her contract would have run through 1991.
   Her attorney, Barry Langberg, said the share of the gross
profits could bring the actress $10 million to $15 million in the
long run.
   Lorimar's attorney, Donald Engel, expressed relief that punitive
damages were not awarded.
   ``It could have been worse,'' he said, adding that an appeal was
unlikely because ``the verdict is so small.''
   But Lorimar spokeswoman Barbara Brogliatti disagreed. ``We're
disappointed in the verdict,'' she said. ``And our attorney has
advised us there are grounds for an appeal and we are considering
it.''
   Some of the jurors lined up in the hallway after delivering
their verdict to get Miss Harper's autograph.
   At the trial, the company claimed that Miss Harper was
emotionally unstable and menopausal, a position she denounced
Friday as ``sexist.''
   Sandy Duncan replaced Miss Harper on the show, which was
retitled ``The Hogan Family.
</TEXT>
