<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Subejano     09-17 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Subejano,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ramon Subejano, War Hero, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramon Simpas Subejano, a Philippine native who
became one of the United States' most decorated war veterans, died
at the Veteran's Administration Hospital in Boston. He was 83.
   He had been hospitalized for a brief illness before his death
Friday.
   Subejano left the Philippines for the United States in 1927,
when he stowed away aboard a freighter. He traversed the world as a
seaman before buying a pool hall in Brooklyn with $32,000 he won
one night in a casino.
   But he lost all his money in the Great Depression and went to
work as a busboy. Subejano was drafted in the Army in 1942 and
became one of the most effective soldiers in Europe, killing more
than 400 German soldiers from Normandy to the Rhineland.
   He was wounded four times and came home disabled but covered
with medals, including a Silver Star and decorations from the
French, Dutch and Belgian governments.
   He was awarded the Silver Star for the single-handed capture of
a Nazi-held factory near Dillingen, Germany. According to his
service record, Subejano crept into the ravaged factory against
heavy machine gun fire and grenade explosions, killing five
Germans, wounding six and forcing the surrender of 37 others.
   Subejano, a lifelong bachelor who was described as polite and
easygoing, made the news last year when he was involved in a slight
altercation with his landlord over a rent increase.
   The landlord filed a criminal complaint against 5-foot-2
Subejano, claiming that he had threatened him even though the
landlord stood 6-foot-2 and weighed 250 pounds.
   At the time of the incident, a neighbor said Subejano was
``still out every day in a beautifully pressed white shirt, little
suit with suspenders and a spit-shine polish on his shoes. I don't
know what he did in the war but he's still a tough little guy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   09-17 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0492,a0497,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Thousands Protest, Troops Shoot and Wound Three</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines previous urgent series, recasts lead to add hundreds
of thousands protesting, edits. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred thousand anti-government
protesters took to the streets of the capital today to demand
democracy, and troops opened fire on a crowd surrounding government
buildings, wounding at least three.
   Most of the protesters today marched peacefully in lines through
the streets of the capital, some carrying placards that read: ``If
we don't get it, we will hit out.''
   But a violent scene developed around the Trade Ministry
building, where troops opened fire to disperse an angry crowd. At
least three people were wounded.
   The sound of gunfire attracted a much larger crowd, and many
threatened to burn down the building. Buddhist monks intervened
before the threats could be carried out.
   Soon after, a group of students clambered over adjacent rooftops
to break into the Ministry building. It was not immediately clear
whether the students remained in the building or had been persuaded
to leave.
   Protesters also surrounded two other nearby government
buildings, City Hall and the Central Bank. Shooting was heard in
the area but it could not immediately be determined who was
involved.
   Troops had not been reported to fire on anti-government
protesters since mid-August.
   About 100 soldiers were posted at both the Central Bank and City
Hall but only a few were at the Trade Ministry.
   Today's protests indicated that the population of Rangoon, the
nation's capital, was unsatisfied with yet another concession by
the government.
   State radio announced Friday that all military personnel and
civil servants must resign from the ruling Burma Socialist Program
Party and refrain from membership in all future political parties.
   The decision, the radio said, was made at the recommendation of
a recently formed election commission which is to supervise
multi-party elections in about three months. The opposition has
rejected this move, saying an interim government must be formed
before elections take place.
   About two-thirds of the 2.5 million members of the ruling party
come from military and civil service ranks.
   Some opposition leaders, who are believed to be negotiating with
President Maung Maung's government, have been attempting to stop
mob violence from escalating.
   On Friday, prominent dissident Aung Gyi defused a potentially
bloody confrontation between soldiers and more than 100,000
demonstrators moving on the Ministry of Defense armed with spears,
swords and knives.
   Aung Gyi, a former brigadier general, asked the crowd to ``fight
without bloodshed.''
   ``We cannot blame these soldiers for the faults of some of their
commanders,'' he told the crowd. ``Soldiers are born of the people.
They are the people's army.''
   One Burmese intellectual who watched the confrontation said of
the protesters: ``They don't seem to be afraid of the guns. They
are angry and frustrated.''
   Interviews with a number of Burmese government employees today
also indicated that a government warning that all civil servants
return to work by Sept. 26 or face official action would go
unheeded.
   Virtually all government employees, including some police and
military personnel, have been on strike since Aug. 8, causing an
almost total administrative breakdown.
   Massive protests began after strongman Ne Win, who seized power
in 1962, resigned last July. His replacement, hardliner Sein Lwin,
attempted to restore order by ordering the military to fire at the
swelling number of protestors but resigned 17 days later.
   On Aug. 19, the relatively moderate Maung Maung became Burma's
first civilian leader in a quarter century, but he has also been
unable to stop the nationwide uprising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
