<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Olympics-Protests     09-17 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympics-Protests,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Radical Students Mount Anti-Olympic Protest In Seoul</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Olympics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 radical students took to the
city's streets today in an anti-Olympic protest on the Games'
opening day, and police arrested about a dozen of them, witnesses
said.
   The students marched from a shopping center toward Myongdong
Cathedral, shouting ``Oppose single-host Olympics!'' and ``Down
with military dictatorship!'' witnesses said.
   Soon after the march began, about 100 plainclothes police
charged the demonstration and arrested about a dozen protesters,
the witnesses said.
   No tear gas was fired and no injuries reported, they said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   It was the first known anti-Olympic street demonstration in
Seoul in recent weeks. Most student protests have been carried out
on university campuses.
   Radical students, who form a small minority in South Korea, are
demanding that the Olympics be shared with North Korea to help
unify the Korean peninsula, which was divided at the end of World
War II in 1945.
   North Korea boycotted the Olympics after its demand to co-host
the Games was turned down by the International Olympic Committee.
</TEXT>
