<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySwap     09-17 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney May Seek Genetic Tests Of Florida Girl In Baby-Swap Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney may seek a court-ordered
genetic test to determine if a 9{-year-old Florida girl is the
daughter of a Pennsylvania couple who filed suit claiming a
baby-switch conspiracy in 1978.
   Marvin Ellin, a Baltimore malpractice lawyer, said he will first
ask the girl's father to allow his daughter to be tested, but will
ask a court to mandate the test if he refuses, The Baltimore Sun
reported today.
   The girl's father said he would not allow her to be tested and
that they had the wrong child.
   The test would compare inherited factors in the girl's blood
with the blood chemistry of Ernest and Regina Twigg of Langhorne,
Pa.. The Twiggs are plaintiffs in a $100 million suit alleging
three doctors and a nurse at Hardee Memorial Hospital in Wauchula,
Fla., switched their healthy baby girl with a child suffering from
a congenital heart defect.
   The small hospital also was named as a defendant in the federal
suit.
   Mrs. Twigg said Friday she will seek custody of the girl if she
turns out to be her daughter and if she is not happy and safe. The
girl, whose mother died of cancer seven years ago, now lives with
her father.
   Arlena, the child Mrs. Twigg brought home from the hospital 10
years ago, died Aug. 23 at the Deborah Heart and Lung Center in
Browns Mills, N.J.
   The Twiggs discovered that Arlena's Type B blood made it
unlikely she was their daughter since they have Type O blood.
Sophisticated protein-matching tests at the Johns Hopkins
Immunogenetics Laboratory in Baltimore also concluded the child was
unrelated to the Twiggs.
   A third test known as ``genetic fingerprinting'' is scheduled to
begin next week.
   The Twiggs, who have seven surviving children, moved from
central Florida two years ago.
   Using public records, the St. Petersburg Times said Friday it
had located a blond, blue-eyed girl, the only other white girl
reported born at Hardee Memorial at the time Regina Twigg gave
birth, in a southwest Florida city.
   To protect the child, the paper did not identify her.
   Relatives of the girl discount the notion that she was part of a
baby-swapping scheme.
   ``My sympathy goes out to those people,'' the girl's father said
Thursday evening. ``They have every right to pursue their real
child. (My daughter) is not their child. ... She will never be
their child.''
   The father told the newspaper he knew nothing of any baby swap.
He would not disclose his daughter's blood type and said he would
resist any attempts to draw the girl into the Twiggs' battle. The
girl knows nothing of the search for her.
   ``Until they get an indictment or a conviction ... I have
nothing to say,'' he said. ``I'm an innocent bystander.''
</TEXT>
