<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingBoat     09-17 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Boat,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors of Boat Accident Spent 18 Hours in Frigid Water</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of a fishing boat accident spent
18 hours clutching to a small life raft trying to stave off
disorienting hypothermia that caused the last victim to jump from
the raft into the Pacific Ocean.
   Five people survived, but four others died before being rescued
Friday by Coast Guard helicopters about 35 miles from the coast.
   Dr. Esther Sewell, who treated some of the survivors, said some
were in the life raft, some had hung onto the side and some clung
to a bulkhead that became detached from the 45-foot tuna fishing
charter boat Cougar as it sank.
   The last person to die was in the raft, Sewell said, but
hypothermia apparently made him confused.
   ``He saw the helicopter and he got out of the raft and started
swimming for it. He started taking off his life jacket,'' Sewell
said.
   One of the survivors, Clyde Sloan, 41, spent the entire 18 hours
in the water clinging to the side of the life raft, his relatives
said.
   ``He thought he was going to die,'' said his son, Rocky Sloan.
``My dad's friend died in his arms.''
   Sloan said his father told him all nine tied themselves together
and took turns in the life raft. When a woman in the raft died,
they tied her to the bulkhead and someone else took her place in
the raft, he said.
   After their rescue, the survivors were taken to Pacific
Communities Hospital in Newport, about 115 miles southwest of
Portland.
   The Coast Guard was still trying to determine exactly why the
charter boat went down in apparently calm seas.
   The boat's engine room apparently flooded, but the crew didn't
notice until the vessel already had begun to sink, said Veronica
Cady, of the Coast Guard public affairs office in Seattle.
   Five helicopters, two airplanes and the Coast Guard cutter Iris
participated in the search, which began Thursday night when the
Cougar, a former Navy launch, was reported overdue at Depoe Bay.
   The boat, owned by Depoe Bay Sports Fishing & Charter, was hired
for a day of tuna fishing.
   Helicopter crews located the survivors and three of the bodies
at about 10:30 a.m. Friday, about three hours after the search had
resumed. A fourth body was located nearby a few hours later.
   The boat was equipped with citizens band and marine radios, but
no distress calls had been monitored on any frequencies, said Coast
Guard Capt. Michael Lovett.
   The dead were identified as Pat Watson, 40, owner and operator
of the boat; Rick Moore, 26, of Depoe Bay, a crewman; Richard
Boxwell, 36, of Corvallis, and Hallie Wynne, no age available, of
Lincoln City.
   Along with Sloan, the survivors were identified as Andy Liddell,
34, of Depoe Bay, a charter boat skipper who was acting as a
crewman; Dale Powell, 56, of Aumsville; Peter Russell Erickson, 47,
of Albany, Ill., and Gary Williams, no age available, of Lincoln
City.
   Three of the survivors were admitted to the Newport hospital in
serious condition suffering from hypothermia, and two were treated
for exposure and released, said hospital administrator Tom Olsen.
</TEXT>
