<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet-Tourism,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Border Towns To Begin Tourist Exchanges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two towns on the Chinese-Soviet border will begin
tourist exchanges across the Amur River, the official China Daily
said today. The river towns were once the scene of bloody military
clashes between the two nations.
   Officials of Heihe in China and Blagoveshchensk in the Soviet
Union agreed daylong tours will be organized, with the first group
of 40 Chinese crossing the river later this month. The newspaper
said two exchanges a month are planned between the two river towns.
   In 1969, the two communist powers engaged in border fighting
along the Amur, or Heilongjiang, River and the Ussuri River of
northeast China.
   The two nations began normalizing economic and other
non-political ties in 1982, and border trade now is thriving.
