<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Gorbachev     09-17 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Gorbachev,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Peng Says Summit Possible, China Seeks Better Ties With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng said today that a Chinese-Soviet
summit can be held if lower-level meetings bring the two sides
closer together on issues such as Cambodia.
   He also denied that the leadership is split over how to proceed
with troubled economic reforms and said that reports of major
resistance to reform are groundless.
   The premier, meeting with The Associated Press board of
directors and executives, said improved relations with Moscow were
in the interests of China and world peace and would not threaten
China's ties with Japan and the West.
   It was the most favorable Chinese response yet to the Soviet
Union's repeated invitations for a summit meeting to end a
quarter-century of estrangement between the communist neighbors.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev renewed the invitation in a
speech Friday in Siberia in which he said he was ready to begin
summit preparations without delay.
   The People's Daily and the official English-language China Daily
reported Gorbachev's offer without comment.
   Although Li noted China's longstanding ``three obstacles'' to a
Chinese-Soviet summit, he seemed to play down the differences while
emphasizing that China ``would like very much to normalize
relations.''
   The three obstacles are the Soviet troop presence in
Afghanistan, the nine-year occupation of Cambodia by Soviet-allied
Vietnam, and the heavy Soviet troop presence on its border with
China.
   Progress recently has been made in all three areas.
   Li, speaking through an official interpreter at Beijing's
Diaoyutai state guesthouse, said the most important issue was for
Vietnam to pull out of Cambodia. Hanoi has already begun a partial
troop withdrawal from the embattled country.
   Chinese and Soviet negotiations who met last month to discuss
Cambodia were ``relatively close'' on the need for a Vietnamese
withdrawal, he said.
   ``It still takes a series of negotiations between the two sides
to bring their views closer together,'' Li said. ``Once there is
further agreement the subject of a summit meeting will be placed on
the agenda.''
   China has consistently used the leverage of a potential summit
meeting to try to resolve one of its primary security concerns: the
fear of an expansionist Vietnam on its southern border.
   Li said Chinese-Soviet relations could not return to the
comraderie of the 1950s, when the two nations were close allies and
the Soviet Union sent thousands of technicians to help develop
industry in China, which was devastated by a civil war.
   The two countries split bitterly in the early 1960s over
strategic and ideological differences.
   Li also sought to reassure Japan and the West, with whom China
has developed friendly ties and trade in the past decade, that they
have nothing to fear from a Soviet-Chinese rapproachment.
   ``Improvement of Chinese-Soviet relations will not impair
relations between China and the United States, and it will be in
the interests of world peace,'' Li said.
   In his 40-minute interview, Li stressed that ``rumors going
around the world'' of a serious rift in the Chinese leadership were
untrue. ``All this is groundless,'' he said.
   Li, who heads the government, claimed in particular that there
is no political division between himself and Zhao Ziyang, general
secretary of the Communist Party.
   Li is regarded as more cautious toward reforms that will reduce
the role of central planning in running the economy, while Zhao is
thought to be China's strongest advocate for bold steps to
introduce market-oriented principles.
   Reports in the Hong Kong and Western press have speculated that
Zhao's powers have declined as a result of the 20 percent inflation
rate, out-of-control public spending, panic buying and corruption
that now plague the economy.
   In the past month the government has taken several measures to
calm consumers and cool off the economy, including pegging bank
interest rates to inflation to end runs on banks and pledging there
will be no more price hikes this year.
   Li said these decisions were made by top party and government
leaders ``under the directorship of General Secretary Zhao Ziyang
and some were proposed by him himself.''
</TEXT>
