<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kenya-Libya     09-17 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kenya-Libya,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Allegedly Training Guerrillas To Topple Kenyan Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor claimed that Libya is
training Kenyan guerrillas to topple President Daniel arap Moi's
government, Nairobi newspapers reported today.
   The three English-language newspapers also published photographs
of nine men who allegedly have traveled to Libya for guerrilla
training since April.
   Kenya last year accused Libya of training 200 Kenyans in
guerrilla warfare to overthrow the government. Officials said
Kenyan dissidents abroad had promised money to the trainees. The
government later closed the Libyan Embassy in Nairobi after
accusing diplomats of operating a spy ring.
   The prosecutor made the claim in the court case of Gibson Maina
Kimani.
   Kimani was sentenced Friday to seven years in prison after he
pleaded guilty to charges of possessing seditious literature from
the clandestine Kenya Patriotic Front and the Kenya Revolutionary
Movement.
   It was the first time officials acknowledged the existence of
the rebel groups. The Kenya Patriotic Front is allegedly led by
Koigi wa Wamwere, a former legislator living in exile in Norway,
and the Kenya Revolutionary Movement, is said to be led by Raila
Odinga.
   Odinga, the elder son of former vice president and government
critic, Oginga Odinga, was detained Sept. 9 under security laws
that allow for detention without trial. He and nine other detainees
had been freed Feb. 5.
   Odinga was Kenya's longest-serving detainee under Moi, having
been detained after an abortive 1982 coup by disgruntled junior
officers in the air force.
   Bernard Chunga, deputy public prosector, said in court that
Kimani, a businessman, helped coordinate activities between the two
opposition groups.
   Chunga said Kimani met Wamwere three times this year, twice in
Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, and once in Kampala, Uganda, to discuss
recruitment of men to receive guerilla training in Libya.
   Wamwere, Chunga said, gave Kimani $1,666 to recruit potential
trainee guerrillas at a Feb. 11 meeting in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
This was in addition to $289 Kimani had received by mail, the
prosecutor said.
   Chunga said Kimani escorted three recruits to Tanzania on April
29 and they left for Libya May 16.
   Chunga said Kimani learned Odinga headed the Kenya Revolutionary
Movement when he delivered a letter from Wamwere after a May 27
meeting in Kampala, Uganda.
   Kimani then met Odinga June 26 and later provided travel
documents for other recruits from the Kenya Revolutionary Movement,
the prosecutor said. They flew to Libya from Dar es Salaam on Aug.
22, Chunga added.
   The government has recently been cracking down on members of the
opposition. More than 80 people _ including lawyers, journalists,
civil servants, university lecturers and students _ have been
jailed for admitting links with banned opposition groups.
   Human rights groups such as the London-based Amnesty
International claim confessions have been coerced.
</TEXT>
