<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0503 09-17 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0503,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Refused to Commit on Solidarity, Participant Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs at bottom to UPDATE with reports from Soviet
media.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity leader today said Interior
Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak told members of the independent labor
movement that he sees a future for the banned group but refused to
promise legalization.
   Wladyslaw Frasyniuk described the six-hour meeting he attended
Friday, and said the opposition side emerged ``with a feeling of
victory.''
   At the meeting, Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa and government
officials agreed to hold broad-based talks in mid-October to focus
on national problems and the future of Solidarity.
   ``Our positions got closer. I am satisfied,'' a tired-looking
Walesa said after the meeting at a government guest house outside
Warsaw.
   Walesa last month persuaded striking workers to end a wave of
walkouts after obtaining the government's agreement to hold talks.
He had not met with the government for six years.
   For the first time Friday, other Solidarity members and
representatives of the official trade union alliance OPZZ were
brought into talks to prepare for October's discussions.
   According to Frasyniuk, the leader of a Solidarity chapter in
the southwestern city of Wroclaw, Gen. Kiszczak told opposition
representatives that he sees a place for Solidarity in Poland's
future but could not take a decision now because his hands are tied.
   Alternate Politburo member Stanislaw Ciosek told the meeting
there was strong resistance to the idea of legalizating Solidarity
among the police and army, who ``fear this symbol,'' according to
Frasyniuk.
   ``They clearly said, `Give us time,''' Frasyniuk said.
   There was no immediate government confirmation of Frasyniuk's
account.
   Frasyniuk told reporters that the union decided to continue
talks even without a firm commitment because it did not want to be
seen as being the first to break off the process of negotiation.
   After the meeting, participants had ``a feeling of victory,'' he
said. ``You could see that the problem of Solidarity was the
dominant one, and nobody directly attacked Solidarity.''
   The trade union movement, the first ever permitted in the Soviet
bloc, was broken up in 1981 under martial law and later banned.
   The meeting, the second between Walesa and communist authorities
in two days, was called to set terms for a round-table meeting of
groups, including Solidarity, that represent various sectors of
Polish society. They are to address major Polish problems,
including the future of the outlawed Solidarity and of trade union
pluralism.
   ``Some bitter things were traded,'' said mediator Andrzej
Stelmachowski.
   The recent labor unrest posed the most serious threat to
Solidarity since it was crushed in 1981.
   Stelmachowski, a law professor who has been the go-between in
arranging the meetings, reported that no decisions were taken ``but
there was some progress.''
   In the Soviet Union, meanwhile, the state-run media softened
their hard-line support of the Polish government, saying both
officials and protesters are to blame for many of Poland's problems
and that the two should compromise.
   The daily newspapers Sovietskaya Rossiya and Izvestia carried
commentaries Friday suggesting that workers were driven to strike
by the government's mishandling of sharp price increases in the
spring.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said trust in Poland's government has eroded
so badly that the leadership may not survive.
   ``Will the incumbent government stay in power or will it resign?
This issue has become a political reality and will be discussed by
the Polish parliament,'' wrote V. Runov, Warsaw correspondent for
the official Tass news agency. The dispatch appeared in Sovietskaya
Rossiya.
</TEXT>
