<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru a0489 09-17 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Pushing `Training' Wage As Alternative To Kennedy Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 12th graf, Kennedy's bill, to CORRECT figure for 1990 to
$4.15.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans are planning to whittle away at
Democratic-proposed increases in the $3.35 minimum wage for the
first time in eight years through a subminimum ``training'' wage _
but not until next week.
   With many senators taking Friday off to campaign for re-election
in their home states, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, was unwilling to
risk a vote on a Democratic measure aimed at killing his proposal
for a 80 percent subminimum wage.
   Under the Hatch proposal, employers could pay the ``training''
wage during the first 90 days a worker is on their payroll.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the chief author of the mininum
wage bill, was ready to vote Friday on his proposal to double the
number of student exemptions that employers can now use to pay
part-time workers 15 percent below the wage floor _ or $2.85 an
hour presently.
   Hatch called Kennedy's proposal a ``mock training wage,'' saying
it would would not give employers any incentive to ``open the door
to those who have nothing, who are undereducated and unskilled.''
   He said his subminimum training wage advocated by the Reagan
administration, Vice President George Bush and Bush's running mate,
Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., could ``create hundreds of thousands of
new jobs.''
   With presidential and congressional elections just eight weeks
away, President Reagan, Bush and other Republicans have softened
their opposition to any increase, but have not said how large it
should be.
   In June, Quayle offered before the Senate Labor Committee a
proposed raise to $4 an hour over two years but coupled it with a
subminimum training wage. The measure was never voted on.
   Bush, campaigning in Ohio, said Friday that a lower training
wage, the administration's euphemism for a subminimum rate that it
has advocated since 1981, must accompany any increase for him to
support it.
   Kennedy called the Republican proposals a Trojan Horse, saying
Quayle's proposal for a $4 minimum wage amounts to a 10 percent cut
in buying power after taking inflation into account from when
Reagan and Bush took office.
   ``And from that miserly floor, he proposes a further cut for all
new hires,'' Kennedy said. ``Can this be what George Bush means
when he talks about a kinder, gentler America?''
   Kennedy's bill would raise the minimum wage 40 cents an hour in
each of the next three years _ to $3.75 in 1989; $4.15 in 1990 and
$4.55 in 1991 _ directly benefitting about 15 million workers now
paid less than $4.50 an hour.
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said he hoped to get a
vote on Kennedy's and Hatch's different subminimum proposals next
Tuesday and a vote on final passage by the end of next week.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said the House will take up
and ``likely pass'' it as soon as the Senate acts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
