<HEAD>China Names Women Generals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's military, now restoring a ranking system
abolished 23 years ago, has awarded the rank of major general to
five women, the official Xinhua News Agency said Saturday.
   The report said the awarding ceremony was Friday, two days after
the People's Liberation Army named 17 men to the post of general.
   The five women major generals are now the only women generals in
the army. They are:
   _Nie Li, vice-director of the Science and Technology Committee
of the Commission of Science and Industry for National Defense.
   _Liao Wenhai, vice director of the army's General Hospital.
   _Wu Xiaoheng, vice director of the army's No. 1 Medical
University.
   _Li Xikai, vice director of the army's No. 3 Medical University.
   _Hu Feipei, vice president of army's Louyang Foreign Languages
Institute.
   Xinhua said Li Zhen, a Long March veteran, became China's first
woman general in 1955. Mao Tse-tung eliminated ranks in 1965.
