<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-17 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Demonstrate Against Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Radicals, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police Saturday dispersed and
beat radical students who staged an anti-Olympic protest in the
heart of the capital on the opening day of the Olympics. About 20
protesters were arrested.
   Students later held a rally at Korea University in the north of
Seoul and burned an effigy painted with an American flag in the
shape of a nuclear bomb.
   ``Oppose dictator's Olympics,'' students chanted at both
protests.
   About 200 students shouting anti-Olympic slogans tried to march
through Seoul's main shopping district towards Myongdong Cathedral
to protest the opening of the Games. The brief protest was held
about 10 miles from the Olympic venues.
   Scores of riot police charged the march after it had gone about
150 yards. Police roughly dispersed the protesters.
   Riot police punched and kicked protesters and arrested about 20
who were forced into a bus and taken away. Others protesters fled
as police chased them.
   It was the first protest staged in the city center in several
weeks. Protesters did not attempt to fight police.
   Nearly 10,000 Olympic athletes from 160 countries opened the
biggest athletic show on earth Saturday under a massive security
blanket and the jealous glare of communist North Korea.
   A colorful, 3{-hour spectacle, mixing ancient Korean rituals
with space-age technology, kicked off 16 days of athletic
competition at the Summer Games. The Games will produce the first
all-out East-West gold rush since the 1976 Games in Montreal.
   Later Saturday, about 300 students staged an anti-American
protest at Korea University. They denounced the South Korea and
U.S. governments and demanded the Olympics be shared with communist
North Korea.
   ``Yankee go home,'' students shouted as they shot their fists
into the air.
   About 400 riot police kept watch outside the school, but did not
intervene and students dispersed without a confrontation.
   Radical students have staged many protests against the Olympics
and the government of President Roh Tae-woo.
   The radicals are demanding the Olympics be shared with North
Korea to help unify the two Koreas which were divided at the end of
World War II in 1945 and which fought the 1950-1953 Korean War
   North Korea boycotted the Olympics after its demand to co-host
the Games was turned down by the International Olympic Committee.
   The radicals contend the United States helps to enforce the
partition of the Korean peninsula. Radicals demand the expulsion of
the 42,000 U.S. troops based in the nation under a mutual defense
treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Secrecy Bjt   09-17 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Secrecy, Bjt,0858</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alarm That Official Secrecy Becoming Censorship Under Thatcher</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Subscribers to Index on Censorship got a surprise
this month. Instead of the usual reports of suppression of free
speech by dictatorships, the entire issue of the small but
respected journal was devoted to Britain.
   It reflected growing alarm among editors, broadcasters and civil
libertarians that Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government is
adding censorship to Britain's already extensive official secrecy.
   From repeated attempts to suppress news about Northern Ireland
to a worldwide government campaign to ban the publication of an
intelligence veteran's memoirs, the list of recent controversies
over media freedom has grown dramatically.
   ``If freedom is diminished in the United Kingdom, where
historically it has deep roots, it is potentially diminished
everywhere,'' wrote Matthew Hoffman, an assistant editor of the
Independent newspaper. Hoffman edited the special issue of the
Index of Censorship, a monthly journal on freedom of speech and
censorship.
   Mrs. Thatcher insists she is trying to bolster national
security, deny terrorists a platform and restore discipline to a
leaky civil service. But during her nine-year tenure, Britain has
gained a reputation as the most secretive of the Western
democracies.
   ``Secrecy from the top of our society to the bottom is
preventing newspapers from telling the public what is really
happening,'' the Guild of British Newspaper Editors charged in a
recent report, ``Officially Secret.''
   The problem was underscored when Mrs. Thatcher ignored calls to
explain a mysterious incident in which a Cuban diplomat was
expelled last week after firing a gun on a London street.
   Those who felt the public was entitled to know why lives were
put in danger received a stock response: The government never
``makes statements on matters relating to national security.''
   The March shooting of three Irish Republican Army members on a
bombing mission in Gibraltar also stirred the secrecy debate.
   When two British television companies turned up witness'
accounts suggesting soldiers deliberately shot to death the three
men instead of trying to arrest them, the government pressured the
networks to suppress the films, arguing they would prejudice the
inquest.
   The networks refused and the films were screened on schedule.
   Other incidents have raised concern over official secrecy:
   _A police raid on British Broadcasting Corp. studios to seize
tapes of a documentary about a secret spy satellite.
   _A legal bid this year to stop BBC radio broadcasting from
interviews with current and former members of the intelligence
services.
   _The confiscation of unscreened TV film of street violence in
Belfast; a court order delaying screening of a film about an
IRA-related trial.
   _The banning of a BBC film about an IRA sympathizer that
provoked a one-day protest strike at the BBC.
   Overshadowing all for sheer cost and persistence is the Thatcher
administration's worldwide two-year court battle to suppress
``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs of retired intelligence operative Peter
Wright.
   Mrs. Thatcher says she is defending a principle _ the life-long
oath of secrecy taken by secret agents. She has lost her battle in
foreign courts, but in Britain it drags on. The Guardian and
Observer newspapers are still fighting in court to publish extracts
of ``Spycatcher.''
   In Bath, southern England, bookseller Peter Marsh this month
received a summons for contempt of court for selling copies of
``Spycatcher'' that had been imported from Ireland.
   Marsh works alone and said he could be bankrupted by legal
costs, but added in a telephone interview: ``I sell books, it's my
living and I don't see why I should be deprived of that right
because of some overweening authority.''
   Since coming to office in 1979, Mrs. Thatcher's government has
used the all-embracing 1911 Official Secrets Act in at least 24
prosecutions, compared with 34 the previous 68 years. The act makes
it an offense for a civil servant to disclose any information,
however trivial, without authorization.
   The government has unveiled a proposed reform confining the act
mainly to defense, intelligence and foreign relations matters,
saying this would dispel any notion it was being used to protect
the government from embarrassment.
   But the proposals reinforce the lifetime gag on intelligence
officers and shield the intelligence services from any
parliamentary scrutiny.
   Some newspapers have responded by printing sensitive stories
under headlines pointing out that under the new law, such stories
will be unpublishable.
   Novelist John Mortimer wrote in Index of Censorship: ``In
healthier days most newspapers ... attacked the government of the
day, whichever government it might be. Now, however, too many
journalists censor themselves.''
   Maurice Frankel, chairman of the Campaign for Freedom of
Information, which is pressing for a U.S.-style law, said, ``Press
freedom is deteriorating ... And it's notable how relatively little
opposition there's been from the press itself.''
   Ronald Dworkin, professor of jurisprudence at Oxford University,
concluded in Index on Censorship: ``Censorship is no longer an
isolated exception. ... The sad truth is that the very concept of
liberty is being challenged and corroded by the Thatcher
government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CentenaryCollege     09-17 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Centenary College,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Male Students Adjusting To Life At Former Women's College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attending a school where the ratio of
women to men is 63-to-1 may seem like heaven to some young men, but
for the first seven full-time male students admitted to Centenary
College in 78 years, it can be a little strange.
   Ken Strauss, a 21-year-old junior from Mount Olive, acknowledged
that he was ``a little uncomfortable with all girls in class'' but
said he was able to adjust by the time he attended his second class
after school opened Sept. 7.
   Strauss, a psychology and elementary education major, recalls
how a female student saw him standing outside a classroom and
mistook him for the professor.
   ``Most of the girls are friendly. It seems like they know me
more than I know them,'' said Richard West, 21, a freshman business
major.
   West said his decision to attend the school was supported by all
his friends _ except his girlfriend, who is a sophomore.
   ``She's not too happy about my going here,'' West said.
   West doesn't expect to be distracted by his female counterparts,
or at least ``not so much on my part but on the girls' part because
I'm the new element.''
   Centenary College was founded in this northwestern New Jersey
town as a coeducational preparatory school in 1867. Admission was
limited to girls in 1910 and Centenary became a women's junior
college in 1940. The four-year college was formed in 1976, and men
were allowed to enroll only in the Continuing Education Division,
consisting mainly of night classes. In April, the trustees decided
to admit male students full time.
   Dorothy Prisco, vice president for academic affairs and dean of
the college, said the board decided it was ``the right time and the
right circumstances'' to admit men full time.
   She said the school responded to the success of the continuing
education division and the fact that male students were requesting
admission to full-time programs.
   ``We felt very strongly that we were operating from a foundation
of constraints and that it was the time to go coeducational,'' she
said.
   ``It certainly broadens the perspective of the classes,'' Ms.
Prisco said. ``The teaching challenge, I think, becomes greater ...
the richness of discussion in class becomes greater ... it brings a
whole new perspective.
   ``However, it doesn't mean that we are going to forsake our
mission of providing a strong education for women. I don't think we
have to give up one for the other.''
   Total enrollment is about 450 students. There were 192 incoming
students in 1987, down from 235 in 1986 and 261 in 1985, according
to admissions department statistics.
   Adding male minds to the campus will not precipitate changes in
the curriculum, Ms. Prisco said.
   ``I think we have strong academic programs and I think that's
why we have the seven male students ... because they've realized
our programs are strong,'' she said.
   All seven are commuters, but dormitory space for men will be
available in 1989, Ms. Prisco said.
   John Stowe, 23, a transfer student who lives within walking
distance, said he decided to attend Centenary because it is a
small, private school.
   ``I enjoy the campus and it's terribly convenient for me,'' he
said. ``It's been a really neat experience for me ... but it is a
little strange walking into a room full of girls and not seeing
another guy there.''
   Stowe's girlfriend also is not too happy with his choice of
academic institutions.
   ``She's not pleased a bit but she's getting over that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
