<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill One Palestinian, Wound 24 During General
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Egyptian statement on
anniversary of Camp David accords. Pickup 5th graf pvs,
``Underground leaders...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops killed one Palestinian and
wounded 24 in the occupied lands today, Arab sources said, as
residents observed a general strike to mark a massacre of
Palestinians in Lebanon six years ago.
   Today also was the 10th anniversary of the signing of the Camp
David accords which called for Palestinian self-rule in the
occupied lands and paved the way for the Israeli-Egyptian peace
treaty of March 1979.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir issued a statement on the accords
saying:
   ``These agreements created a turning point in the history of the
Middle East. They proved that it's possible to achieve peace
between Israel and its neighbors, that the hatred which prevailed
is not eternal.''
   Egypt marked the anniversary by once again blaming ``Israeli
intransigence'' for the accords' failure to give the Palestinians
in the occupied lands a voice in ruling themselves.
   But except for the bitterly worded statement by Butros Ghali,
minister of state for foreign affairs, the anniversary passed
largely unnoticed in Cairo.
   Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising called for the
general strike to mark the massacre of hundreds of Palestinians in
Beirut's Sabra and Chatilla refugee camps by Israeli-backed
Christian militiamen in September 1982. The strike turned violent
in several towns and villages.
   In Jenin, dozens of Palestinians blocked the road with stones
and burning tires and threw rocks at passing military vehicles, an
Arab reporter said.
   Troops opened fire with rubber bullets and tear gas. When the
rioters failed to disperse, the soldiers opened fire with real
bullets, killing 18-year-old Emad Arkawi. A military spokesman
confirmed a dead Palestinian was brought to the hospital but said
the army was investigating the circumstances.
   Arkawi was the 267th Palestinian to die since the intefadeh,
Arabic for uprising, began nine months ago. Six Israelis have also
been killed.
   Arab reporters said three Palestinians between the ages of 17
and 20, including one woman, were wounded in the incident.
   Another 21 Palestinians were wounded, at least one critically,
in clashes with troops in other parts of the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   The army said it was investigating the reports.
   The general strike was fully observed throughout the occupied
territories.
   In Jenin, Palestinians painted graffiti in Arabic and Hebrew
saying: ``Death to the Jews,'' and ``The End Is Near.'' It was the
first time Arab insurgents have painted graffiti in Hebrew.
Palestinian flags, outlawed by Israel, flew from the homes of many
Jenin residents.
   In all the cities of the occupied territories, workers stayed
away from their jobs, transportation ground to a halt and the
streets were deserted.
   In Gaza City, Palestinian flags were hoisted on electricity
wires and protesters burned tires. Protesters littered the highway
linking Gaza and Khan Yunis with nails to prevent cars from
travelling.
</TEXT>
