<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HearinKidnapping     09-17 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hearin Kidnapping,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearin's $100,000 Reward Doesn't Bring Kidnap Case Break</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $100,000 reward is on the table and
nearly $1 million has been paid in ransom, but authorities say they
still haven't gotten a break in the kidnapping of the ailing wife
of a Jackson multimillionaire.
   Earlier this month, FBI officials released a statement by Robert
M. Hearin offering the reward and asking for the safe return of his
wife, 72-year-old Annie Laurie Hearin, who was abducted from their
home July 26.
   Mrs. Hearin suffers from intestinal ileitis, a disease that can
result in life-threatening complications without medication.
   ``Nothing is new,'' said Police Department spokesman Sgt. Chip
Pippen. ``To my knowledge, at least in the police department, we've
had no response to the reward.''
   FBI agent Wayne Taylor said federal authorities had nothing new
to report.
   ``The investigation is ongoing at this time,'' he said. ``The
community is concerned, but we just have nothing to report.''
   Since Mrs. Hearin's disappearance, the only word from her has
been a letter, which the FBI said was in her handwriting, with an
Atlanta postmark.
   Hearin could not be reached for comment; calls to his home were
not answered.
   A typed ransom note was left at the house when Mrs. Hearin was
abducted. Small spots of blood were found inside and outside the
front door of the two-story house.
   The crudely phrased note, the only direct word from the
kidnappers, instructed Hearin to pay an unspecified amount of money
to 12 people he had allegedly wronged.
   The people named in the letter are current or former franchisers
with School Pictures of Mississippi Inc., which handles portraits
of school children, of which Hearin was once the largest
stockholder. The company filed suit against the 12 in the early
1980s, claiming they owed money from operating loans, materials and
film processing fees.
   Hearin researched the monetary amounts involved in the lawsuits
to decide how much to pay each of the 12. Although neither the FBI
nor Hearin has said exactly how much was paid, the payments
``totaled nearly one million dollars,'' according to Hearin's Aug.
23 statement.
   The story of the kidnapping was voluntarily embargoed by the
news media for about 30 hours because officials believed publicity
might endanger the victim. The kidnapping was disclosed at a news
conference July 28 after family members decided to go public
because of the vagueness of the demands in the ransom note.
   On Aug. 23, FBI officials announced that Hearin had followed the
instructions and that payment had been mailed to the 12 named in
the letter, or their survivors, on Aug. 16, the day after Hearin
received the letter from his wife.
   The letter promised that Mrs. Hearin would be returned if the
payments were made.
   Taylor said he could not comment on whether any of the 12 people
had returned the money. At least one _ lawyer N. Alfred Winn of St.
Petersburg, Fla. _ reportedly did send back a check he received
from Hearin.
   Hearin's worth reportedly exceeds $100 million. In addition to
being co-owner of Mississippi Valley Gas Co., he and his partner,
New Jersey oil man Leon Hess, own controlling interest in Lamar
Life Corp., a life insurance company which is the largest
stockholder in Trustmark National Bank, Mississippi's
second-largest financial institution.
   Mark Dale, lead researcher for ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' NBC-TV's
series on unsolved crimes, said producers plan to broadcast a
segment about the kidnapping this fall if Mrs. Hearin is not found.
Last year, the segments produced tips that led to the capture of
nine fugitives and solving of eight cases.
</TEXT>
