<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TaftHome     09-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taft Home,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Taft's Boyhood Home Renovated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly renovated boyhood home of President
William H. Taft opened to the public Saturday and the federal
official who oversaw the completion of the 19-year project was
delighted.
   ``I'm very excited. I feel like we've really done something
important,'' said Steven Kesselman, National Park Service
superintendent for the house. ``It looks great, if I do say so
myself.''
   The 18-room, three-story house includes five furnished rooms,
exhibition rooms and work space for Park Service staff.
   Taft, the only American to serve as both president and U.S.
chief justice, was born at the house in 1857. His father, Alphonso
Taft, bought the house and its 1.82 acres for $10,000 in 1851,
after moving from New England, and added a wing for more space. The
family sold the house in 1899 and auctioned off many of the
furnishings.
   Park Service officials had no original blueprints to guide the
restoration. They had only an 1868 photograph of the house, with
young William Taft in the front yard, to show the home's 19th
century appearance.
   Taft, a lawyer who made his national reputation by serving as
civil governor of the Philippines and later as secretary of war
under President Theodore Roosevelt, was the nation's 27th
president, from 1909 to 1913.
   Taft lost a re-election bid to Woodrow Wilson and served as
chief justice from 1921 to 1930. He died in Washington in March
1930, a few weeks after resigning from the Supreme Court.
   The house, built in the 1840s, was acquired by the Park Service
in 1969. Kesselman, who arrived in 1985 to direct the final stages
of restoration, said the total job cost $3 million of public and
private funds.
   The private Friends of William Howard Taft Birthplace Inc.
raised nearly $600,000 of that total to buy furniture. Some
furniture was donated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
