<HEAD>Hurricane Hobbles Tourist Industry at Famous Resorts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs, ``Escalante said...'' with 1 graf to
UPDATE Mexican death toll to 39. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``He
said...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The destructive force of Hurricane Gilbert
has put this Caribbean resort, popular with U.S. and other
tourists, out of commission for up to three months, Cancun's mayor
said.
   Nearly 6,000 tourists were stranded in the resort area Friday
and 2,000 other vacationers were in the neighboring resort island
of Cozumel, just south of Cancun.
   With Cancun still without electricity or telephone service after
Gilbert hit Wednesday, the tourist industry's priority today was
``to get the tourists out of here,''said Gabriel Escalante,
president of the Cancun Hotel Association.
   Mayor Jose Gonzalez Zapata said Cancun's luxury beachfront
hotels, many flooded and windowless, ``should be operating by
December.'' The tourist high season starts on Dec. 15.
   Tourism Minister Antonio Enriquez Savignac was more optimistic,
saying that damages to Cancun's hotels would be repaired within six
weeks.
   Escalante said it was too early to estimate financial losses
suffered by Cancun's tourist industry when Gilbert slammed into the
city with 160 mph winds. At least 39 people died in Mexico in the
storm, which forecasters have called the most intense on record.
   He said a figure would have to wait ``until experts come in to
evaluate the damage.''
   About 1,500 tourists jammed the local airport Friday afternoon
waiting for a flight out.
   Eleven commercial flights left Cancun Friday from an airport
working only during daylight hours because its control tower
suffered serious damages. Temporary controller equipment was being
shipped in from Mexico City.
   Among the most seriously damaged of the nearly 50 beachfront
hotels were the Club Med and the Presidente.
   Craig Rowley, a Club Med employee from Whittier, Calif., said
about half the luxury resort's installations were destroyed by the
hurricane.
</TEXT>
