<HEAD>Car Smashes Into Line For Prince Tickets, One Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car slammed into a line of people waiting to buy
tickets to a concert by rock star Prince early Saturday, killing a
17-year-old and injuring five other people, police said.
   The driver of the car, a 21-year-old Cambridge man, told police
he was rear-ended by another vehicle, but police said they would
charge the man Monday with vehicular homicide, running a red light
and driving to endanger.
   ``They were on line and at about 1:45 a.m., this individual lost
control of his car,'' said Boston police spokesman Jim Jordan. He
said the car crossed a median and crashed into a line of people
waiting to buy tickets at a record store.
   Jordan said the 17-year-old, whose name was withheld pending
notification of relatives, was pronounced dead at Beth Israel
Hospital. Five other people were taken to two other hospitals, he
said.
   The 21-year-old driver was released. Although some witnesses
corroborated the driver's story of being hit, police believed the
man's actions contributed to the accident, Jordan said. However, he
said, there was no evidence of alcohol use.
   Tower Records receptionist Bobby Harris said ticket buyers had
started lining up Friday morning. The tickets for the Oct. 5
concert at the Worcester Centrum went on sale Saturday morning.
   Massachusetts General Hospital said three people taken there
were all treated and released, while officials at Brigham and
Women's Hospital said they would not immediately release
information on the condition of two ticket-buyers brought there.
