<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Poland     09-17 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Poland,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Press In Rare Critique Of Polish Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Polish leadership must share the blame with
strikers and protesters for many of Poland's problems, the
state-run Soviet press said in a rare critique of a Moscow ally.
   The daily newspapers Izvestia and Sovietskaya Rossiya suggested
in commentaries Friday that Polish workers were driven to strike by
the government's mishandling of sharp price increases in the spring.
   Trust in Poland's government has eroded so badly that the
leadership may not survive, Sovietskaya Rossiya said.
   ``Will the incumbent government stay in power or will it resign?
This issue has become a political reality and will be discussed by
the Polish parliament,'' wrote V. Runov, Warsaw correspondent for
the official Tass news agency. His dispatch appeared in Sovietskaya
Rossiya.
   Izvestia said recent unrest should not cause the Polish
government to back away from reforms.
   ``The country has approached a point in the process of socialist
renovation and democratic development where it shouldn't stop.
Further steps forward are necessary to overcome dogmatic and
sketchy thinking,'' said correspondent L. Toporkov. ``One should
compromise, each to the other.''
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the strikes and their aftermath are
just another step in democratization.
   ``But at the same time, economic decline is occurring. Progress
in reform over the last two or three years has been small and the
workers themselves have failed at reform,'' the newspaper said.
   When protests swept Poland earlier this year, the Soviet media
called the strikes ``groundless and harmful both from the political
and economic viewpoints.'' Commentaries carried by the papers then
also accused Western countries of agitating strikers.
   The latest wave of strikes in August posed the most serious
threat to Poland's government since it imposed martial law and
banned Solidarity in 1981. Lech Walesa, leader of the independent
union federation, agreed to end the strikes after the government
agreed to talks on legalizing the movement.
   ``On Aug. 20, when the strike wave reached its culmination
point, it was clearly determined that the workers' protest in major
cases is resistance to the failed economic policy conducted
recently,'' Sovietskaya Rossiya said.
   The Polish government this year raised prices 42 percent, a move
officials said was necessary to balance goods with the money
supply. Thousands of workers struck in protest and another wave of
strikes began in August.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said Poland's council of ministers was given
extraordinary power to push through economic reforms, but ``it
hasn't given any tangible results.''
   Runov said the government has responded with immediate measures
to speed the country's economic reform program, but ``a problem of
trust in the government is still an open one.''
</TEXT>
