<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Longood     09-17 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Longood,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health and Human Services Speechwriter Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert James Longood Sr., director of
speechwriting in the Office of Public Relations at the Department
of Health and Human Services, has died at 61.
   Longood died of cancer Sept. 10 at the Washington Home Hospice.
   A resident of Rockville, Md., Longood was born in Crafton, Pa.
During World War II he served in the Army in the Pacific. He
graduated from Indiana University in 1952 and became a reporter
with the Yonkers (N.Y.) Herald Statesman the following year.
   Longood joined the New York State Health Department in 1958 as
head of public relations. He later became the head speechwriter for
the New York commissioner of health and a speechwriter for Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller.
   In 1971, Longood moved to the Washington area and became a
speechwriter with the Department of Health, Education and Welfare,
which became HHS in 1979.
   He was a freelance speechwriter and editor during the late
1970s, but returned to the federal government in 1980 and remained
with HHS until his death.
   Survivors include his wife, Wilma; sons Robert Jr., of Eugene,
Ore.; David, of Oakland, Md.; and Matthew, of Schenectady, N.Y.;
his daughter, Amy Keller, of Philadelphia; his mother, Esther
Longood, and a brother, William Longood, both of Mansfield, Ohio.
</TEXT>
