<HEAD>Reagan Salutes U.S. Olympic Athletes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today saluted America's
Olympic athletes, calling them ``as patriotic as the Pledge of
Allegiance, as red, white and blue as the flag.''
   ``Our athletes are a remarkable group, not only for their
achievements, but also for how they represent so much of what is
good and beautiful and splendid about this sweet and promised
land,'' the president said in his weekly radio address.
   As he has in most of his recent radio speeches, the president
mentioned Republican presidential nominee George Bush, saying that
the vice president was ``representing all of us'' when he saw the
athletes off to Seoul, South Korea, two weeks ago.
   ``You can see the American spirit in the lives of every one of
our team members at these games,'' Reagan said. ``This team comes
from all over our nation _ from the rough and tumble streets of our
brawny cities to the quiet lanes of our vast countryside, from the
suburban hills of Southern California to riverfront towns in the
Midwest.''
   ``There is so much we have to be proud of in our Olympic team
this year,'' Reagan said.
   ``Our athletes have a love, a happiness and an exuberance in
being American,'' he said. ``They're as patriotic as the Pledge of
Allegiance, as red, white and blue as the flag. They're filled with
the spirit of our land.''
