<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Davis     09-17 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Davis,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin American Scholar Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEVY CHASE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Eugene Davis, a Latin American
scholar and professor emeritus at American University, is dead at
the age of 85.
   Davis died Tuesday of cancer at his home in this Washington
suburb.
   He served on the American University faculty from 1947 until he
retired in 1973, and continued to teach part time until the fall of
1986.
   Davis had been chairman of the history and government
department, director of the university's language center, dean of
the College of Arts and Sciences and a professor in the schools of
international studies and government and public administration.
   He traveled extensively in Latin America and spent sabbaticals
there. Among his books were ``Americas in History,'' ``Latin
American Social Thought'' and ``Latin American Thought: A
Historical Introduction.''
   Born in Girard, Ohio, Davis grew up in Niles, Ohio, and
graduated from Hiram College. He earned a master's degree at the
University of Chicago and a doctorate in history at what is now
Case Western Reserve University.
   In addition to his wife, Audrey, Davis is survived by a
daughter, Barbara Lee Owen of Bethesda, Md.; a sister, Marjorie
Pearce of Dunedin, Fla.; a brother, L. Gordon Davis of St. Louis;
three grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
