<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     09-17 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Reagan Democrats Returning To Their Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen, finishing a four-day Southern campaign swing,
declared Saturday that Democrats who voted for President Reagan in
1980 and 1984 are ``coming back in droves.''
   The Texas senator told an enthusiastic, partisan audience in a
small college auditorium that his ticket represented ``the
difference between performance and promise. It's a message we
understand here in the South.''
   ``I've spent a lot of time in the last month going around
visiting ... Democrats that have voted for Reagan,'' he said. ``And
I've gone to them and said, `Come home' ... and they're coming back
in droves.''
   Vice President George Bush had failed in his role as Reagan's
appointee to lead the fight against drug imports in Florida,
Bentsen said.
   ``And now George Bush wants a promotion,'' he said, drawing
laughter from the crowd. ``And he wants to pass the torch of
failure on to the junior senator from Indiana,'' Republican vice
presidential candidate Dan Quayle.
   Bentsen spoke in front of a huge American flag, behind a
collection of nautical items including a ship's wheel and lobster
traps.
   On the stage with him was Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., with whom
Bentsen has gone quail hunting in the past. ``We're opening Quayle
season a little early this year,'' Bentsen said, repeating one of
his favorite lines.
   In this conservative area of the Florida panhandle, near two
major military installations, Bentsen tried to underline what he
said was a commitment to a strong defense by Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis.
   ``Our message to the new South, our message to America, is
strength and stability for national defense,'' he said.
   ``We support a strong nuclear deterrent. We support the triad,
powerful reliable strategic weapons on the land, in the air and
under the sea,'' he said.
   He did not mention Dukakis' opposition to two programs for
modernizing the land-based leg of the triad, the MX and Midgetman
missiles. Bentsen himself has supported both of those programs.
   Chiles described Bentsen as ``the third senator from Florida''
for all the work he's done for the state.
   But even enthusiastic supporters in the audience doubted the
panhandle would go for the ticket.
   ``You're in the middle of the redneck Riviera,'' said Kay
Horton, who was the area's lone Dukakis delegate to the Democratic
National Convention.
   Jerry Miller, Democratic chairman of nearby Okaloosa County,
said Reagan took the area 65 percent to 35 percent last time.
   ``The comparison with four years ago is like night and day,'' he
said.
   ``We've got a fighting chance at even this time,'' he said.
   Bentsen was returning to Washington Saturday afternoon to attend
to Senate business on Monday.
</TEXT>
