<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Olympics     09-17 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Olympics,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Salutes U.S. Olympic Athletes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan saluted U.S. Olympic athletes
Saturday and urged Americans to ``remember, win, lose or draw, how
much we have to be proud and thankful for.''
   The president devoted most of his weekly radio address,
delivered from the presidential retreat at Camp David in Maryland's
Catoctin Mountains, to the games that began Friday in Seoul, South
Korea.
   The patriotic tone of the address recalled Reagan's acceptance
speech at the 1984 Republican National Convention, in which he
spoke of that summers's Olympics.
   In that speech in Dallas, Reagan likened the Olympic runners'
torch to ``another torch, the one that greeted so many of our
parents and grandparents ... Miss Liberty's torch.''
   In Saturday's address, the president said he agreed with the
remarks of Vice President George Bush, who saw the athletes off to
Seoul two weeks ago.
   In his send-off speech, Bush said the athletes ``stand for the
country of the little guy, the country where no matter what the
circumstances of your birth and background, you can go anywhere and
do anything.''
   The vice president, said Reagan, was ``representing all of us''
in his remarks.
   ``Our athletes are a remarkable group, not only for their
achievements, but also for how they represent so much of what is
good and beautiful and splendid about this sweet and promised
land,'' the president said.
   ``They're as patriotic as the Pledge of Allegiance, as red,
white and blue as the flag,'' he said.
   ``So as you watch these Olympics, remember, win, lose or draw,
how much we have to be proud and thankful for. After all, we're
Americans.''
</TEXT>
