<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Coleman     09-17 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Coleman,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coleman Blasts Bush's Handling Of Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has been ``non-combatant'' as the
Reagan administration's point man in the war on drugs and the grim
toll has climbed, with ``more deaths, more wasted lives, more
shattered families,'' a Texas Democrat said Saturday.
   ``While George Bush was in charge, he himself said the nation is
losing ground in the war on drugs. That's because he's used only
one weapon in the war: hot air,'' Rep. Ron Coleman said in the
Democratic response to President Reagan's weekly radio address.
   Coleman accused the vice president of supporting funding cuts to
enforcement and drug treatment programs, slashing personnel and
leading an ineffective border interdiction system that even the
head of the Drug Enforcement Administration recommended be
abolished.
   Coleman pointed to a survey of drug enforcement officials by the
watchdog General Accounting Office that showed more than half
believing that Bush's anti-drug programs had ``no effect'' or had
``somewhat worsened'' drug interdiction efforts.
   He also took aim at a proposal by the Republican presidential
nominee to put his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, in
charge of the drug fight if the two are elected.
   ``This is the fellow who, until last week, wasn't even aware his
boss had been directing the administration's anti-drug efforts,''
Coleman said of Quayle.
   ``The Medellin Cartel (Colombian drug dealers) isn't exactly
worried at the thought that J. Danforth Quayle might take aim at
their deadly business with his press releases,'' Coleman said,
referring to Quayle's work as a public relations officer for the
Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam War.
   ``How can he be put in charge of this war when he wouldn't fight
in the last one? We still haven't forgotten the last time he was
given the opportunity to carry a rifle for his country,'' Coleman
said. ``This is a fellow who sat out the last war typing press
releases in Indiana.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NY-09-17-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Coleman-Text     09-17 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Coleman-Text,660</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address:
   Hello. I'm Congressman Ron Coleman from Texas.
   Those of us along the U.S.-Mexico border live on the front lines
of the war on drugs. You can walk into the desert from my home in
El Paso any night and hear the drone of aircraft flying north with
their deadly cardo.
   The Reagan-Bush administration's point man in the war on drugs
is the man who would be president _ George Bush.
   But the stubborn facts are these:
   While George Bush was in charge, he himself said the nation is
losing ground in the war on drugs. That's because he's used only
one weapon in the war: hot air.
   While George Bush was in charge, he tried to cut $238 million
from drug enforcement funding for state and local police
departments.
   While George Bush was in charge, he tried to cut drug treatment
funding by 50 percent.
   While George Bush was in charge, not once did Mr. Bush demand
economic sanctions _ under a law he said he wanted _ against
countries that won't cooperate in the war on drugs.
   While George Bush was in charge, 2,000 Coast Guard personnel
have been cut from the war on drugs.
   While George Bush was in charge, the Reagan-Bush administration
created the tough-sounding National Narcotics Border Interdiction
System, but it worked so badly that the head of the Drug
Enforcement Administration said it should be abolished.
   While George Bush was in charge, the Reagan-Bush administration
tried to kill the program that helps state and local governments
pursue drug traffickers.
   While George Bush was in charge, Panama's drug-smuggling
dictator, General Noriega, was on the U.S. government payroll _
lining his pockets and returning the favor by lining our morgues
with the bodies of our young people.
   While George Bush was in charge, the cost of cocaine in Miami
plummeted 600 percent.
   While George Bush was in charge, cocaine deaths doubled
nationwide.
   While George Bush was in charge, the grim drug toll has climbed
_ more deaths, more wasted lives, more shattered families.
   The verdict of drug enforcement officials nationwide in a survey
by the watchdog General Accounting Office? More than half said
George Bush's anti-drug program had ``no effect'' or had ``somewhat
worsened`` drug interdiction efforts.
   And what's George Bush's latest proposal? Putting vice
presidential hopeful J. Danforth Quayle in charge. You'll remember
this is the fellow who, until last week, wasn't even aware his boss
had been directing the administration's anti-drug efforts.
   Imagine. J. Danforth Quayle in charge of the war on drugs. How
can he be put in charge of this war when he wouldn't fight in the
last one? We still haven't forgotten the last time he was given the
opportunity to carry a rifle for his country.
   This is a fellow who sat out the last war typing press releases
in Indiana. This is a fellow who voted to drop drug charges against
Panama's indicted dictator.
   Putting the vice president in charge of the war on drugs isn't a
new idea. President Reagan tried it. It didn't work then. And it
certainly won't work now under the country club direction of golfer
J. Danforth Quayle.
   The stubborn fact is the George Herbert Walker Bush and J.
Danforth Quayle have been noncombatants in the war on drugs. The
Medellin Cartel isn't exactly worried at the thought that J.
Danforth Quayle might take aim at their deadly business with his
press releases.
   Several days ago, the nation was shocked by the story of a
little boy in New Orleans named Shrimpy. Shrimpy worked for two
years for drug dealers and lost a bag of crack. He got a bullet in
his head from point-blank range. Shrimpy was 11 years old.
   The problem isn't just saying no to drugs. It's getting a new
president and vice president who will say yes to fighting the war.
   This is Congressman Ron Coleman from Texas for a drug-free
America. Thank you, and have a good weekend.
</TEXT>
