<HEAD>Reagan Assures Texans of Government Help in Hurricane Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan sent a ``special message to
the people of Texas'' Saturday, assuring them the federal
government is ready to help clean up the damage caused by Hurricane
Gilbert.
   ``Today, as you wait for the waters to recede and the cleanup to
begin, Nancy and I and all Americans hold you in our prayers,'' he
said in his weekly radio address, delivered from the presidential
retreat at Camp David.
   ``We all have one blessing to count. Warning came early. You
were ready. So were we,'' he said.
   ``The federal government has spent the last week preparing to
help during and after the storm,'' Reagan said.
   ``We have offered help also to our international friends who
felt Gilbert's full fource. As I told Jamaican Prime Minister
Edward Seaga, we are ready to play an active role in helping them
rebuild.''
</TEXT>
