<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Africa     09-17 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Africa,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maureen Reagan Heading Delegation To Three African Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is sending a team headed by
his daughter, Maureen, on a mission to Malawi, Mozambique and
Uganda, the White House announced Saturday.
   Ms. Reagan is co-chairwoman of the Republican National
Committee. The six-member delegation will also include her husband,
Dennis Revell.
   The delegation will leave Monday on the seven-day mission.
   ``The purpose of the mission is to gain a better understanding
of the effects of the refugee and humanitarian crisis in Malawi and
Mozambique and to follow up on the Aug. 22-24 Oslo Conference on
Southern Africa Refugees, Returnees and Displaced Persons,'' the
White House said.
   There are nearly 6 million refugees in southern Africa,
according to United Nations and other reports. In Mozambique alone,
2 million people have been displaced by the country's lengthy war
against anti-government guerrillas.
   In Malawi, the team will visit refugee camps, meet with
President H. Kamuzu Banda and talk with government officials,
refugees and others, the announcement said.
   In Mozambique, Ms. Reagan and her colleagues will meet with
President Joaquim Chissano and refugee and relief workers in the
Maputo area.
   The delegation will return by way way of Uganda, where Ms.
Reagan will meet with President Yoweri Museveni to reciprocate his
recent visit to the United States.
   Other members of the delegation include C. Payne Lucas,
executive director of Africare; Leonard Robinson, president of the
African Development Fund; Stephanie-Lee Miller, assistant secretary
for public affairs of the Department of Health and Human Services;
and Phyllis Dobyns, vice presidernt of programs for the Save the
Children Federation.
   The delegation will be accompanied by Alison Rosenberg, deputy
assistant secretary of state for African affairs.
</TEXT>
