<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     09-17 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Waite Will Be Released Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beirut weekly said Saturday that
missing Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite will be released soon.
   Ash-Shiraa cited no sources for its report that Waite will be
released ``as a result of an orchestration between Britain and
Iran, including London's denunciation of Iraq for using chemical
weapons against the Kurds.''
   Ash-Shiraa broke the story of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in
1986, but has not been accurate in its recent reporting on foreign
hostages in Lebanon, including several reports that hostages would
be released imminently.
   Waite, 48, disappeared Jan. 20, 1987 after leaving a seaside
hotel in Moslem west Beirut to negotiate with kidnappers of
American hostages.
   There has been no confirmed claim of responsibility for his
abduction.
   Ash-Shiraa said Iran ``is now directly in charge of the
hostages' affairs in Lebanon.''
   The report said the release of German hostage Rudolf Cordes on
Monday ``sparked anger and confusion within Hezbollah (Party of
God) because it was carried out without consulting the party.''
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiite Moslem zealots loyal to Iran's
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, is believed to be the umbrella group
for those holding foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Cordes' release leaves 17 foreigners missing in Lebanon,
including nine Americans.
   The longest held is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped in Beirut
on March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
