<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Quinn     09-17 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Quinn,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Character Actor Louis Quinn Who Starred On `77 Sunset Strip' Dead
At 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Quinn, a veteran gag writer turned
character actor who became known to millions of TV viewers as
Roscoe the horse player on the hit 1950s and '60s detective show
``77 Sunset Strip,'' has died at age 73.
   Quinn died Wednesday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center of lung
cancer.
   He began his writing career in radio after graduation from Los
Angeles High School, turning out material for such stars as Orson
Welles, Paul Whiteman and Milton Berle and for such shows as ``The
Breakfast Club.''
   When Berle moved from radio to television, Quinn followed and
wrote for ``The Texaco Star Theater,'' which featured the comedian.
   He went on to act as host of some of his own shows, including a
program on Los Angeles station KHJ-TV and radio interview shows
broadcast from Chicago's Crossroads Lounge and New York City's
Copacabana.
   He also appeared in such movies as ``Gypsy,'' ``The Al Capone
Story'' and ``The Crowded Sky.''
   Quinn gained perhaps his widest audience from 1958 to 1963 when
he played Roscoe, the comical horse-race handicapper who hung
around a Los Angeles detective agency in ``77 Sunset Strip.''
   Other TV credits included appearances in such westerns as
``Lawman,'' ``Maverick'' and ``Sugarfoot.''
   Quinn is survived by a daughter, brother and four sisters.
</TEXT>
