<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Rapture     09-17 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rapture,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publisher Bought Land Despite Book Predicting Rapture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book publisher bought land for a new
headquarters in April while planning to publish a booklet
predicting the beginning of the end of the world would occur in
September.
   Norvell Olive, 47, executive director of the World Bible Society
in Nashville, spent $114,000 for the land as he arranged to publish
the booklet, ``88 Reasons Why the Rapture Will Happen in 1988.''
   The booklet, written by Edgar Whisenant of Little Rock, Ark.,
predicted that Jesus would ``rapture the church'' and believers
would be taken up to heaven during the Jewish new year. He
initially said the `rapture' would occur by sunset Tuesday but
later revised it to Wednesday morning.
   Whisenant, a retired engineer and self-taught Bible student,
also said there would be seven years of plague, famine and nuclear
war before Christ's Second Coming.
   Olive said he went ahead with the purchase of the 3.13 acres of
land in Nashville because negotiations had taken a long time.
   ``We had had a contract on the property for a year,'' Olive said.
   He said the World Bible Society would disperse profits from the
booklet if the predictions in it do not come true by the end of the
year. In a news release, the society did not say how the profits
would be dispersed, and telephone calls to the society's officer
were not answered Saturday.
   The organization estimated net proceeds at between $200,000 and
$300,000.
   The society, a non-profit corporation Olive founded in 1979,
said it has distributed more than 2 million copies of the booklet
but more than 1 million books were given away free. The booklet,
priced at 30 cents to $2 each, cost 15 cents to produce and is now
out of print.
   ``The book has created a sweeping revival across the country,''
the news release said. ``It is estimated that up to 100,000 people
may have made new confessions of faith.''
   Orders for the booklet are still coming in but won't be filled,
Olive said.
   The Nashville Banner reported Saturday that Olive awaited the
rapture on a 68-foot luxury houseboat on nearby Percy Priest Lake.
   ``Yes, I live comfortably,'' he said. ``The Lord has helped me
to live comfortably.''
</TEXT>
