<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hurricane-GoingHome Bjt   09-17 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Going Home, Bjt,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evacuees Head Home As Storm Abates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Gracia in 3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broken trees and traffic lights
littered city streets Saturday, but many residents were just happy
to have homes to return to.
   More than 5,000 people left shelters around town early Saturday
after the main force of Hurricane Gilbert passed through Mexico
about 100 miles to the south.
   ``I'm kind of glad to be back home. I didn't know what I was
going to find. My house is 80 years old and I thought it was going
to be blown away but it wasn't,'' said Odilon Gracia, 75.
   He said he waited out the storm at an elementary school with a
leaking roof and wet floors. ``I feel a little better in my house
than at that school,'' he said.
   While the shelters emptied, the city grew congested. Restaurants
and food stores closed for two days opened their doors again. Cars
lined up at gas stations.
   Residents pried protective plywood from windows and doors and
mopped up water that had leaked in. Others cut up fallen trees and
hauled them away.
   Despite wind still gusting at more that 30 mph Saturday, work
crews were out picking up dangling traffic lights and downed power
lines that caused some temporary outages Friday.
   Southern Texas was spared the 120 mph wind that whirled around
the eye of Gilbert, but was battered by rain, high wind and
tornadoes spun off by the system.
   ``I thought it was going to be worse, but thank God it wasn't,''
said Gloria Zapata, 40, while she and her family picked up garbage
strewn in their yard by the wind.
   ``I'm thankful it wasn't as hard as it probably could have been
or else everything here would have been blown away.''
   Rosalinda Delgado and her three children spent the night in a
shelter, and were relieved to find their home in good shape.
   ``I was scared, the children were scared, that we weren't going
to have any furniture left when we got back. But everything seems
to be OK,'' Ms. Delgado said.
</TEXT>
