<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Politics     09-17 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Politics,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Candidate: Won't Return If Elected Unless Israelis
Withdraw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese presidential candidate Raymond
Edde said Saturday he will not return home even if he wins an
election scheduled for Thursday unless Israeli forces withdraw from
south Lebanon.
   Meanwhile, U.S. envoy Richard Murphy met for more than two hours
Saturday in Damascus with Syrian President Hafez Assad to try to
help Lebanon out of a political crisis threatening to re-ignite
that country's civil war.
   Murphy, assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs,
was accompanied by Washington's new ambassador to Syria, Edward
Djerejian, and David Newton, head of the Syria, Jordan and Lebanon
desk at the State Department.
   American and Syrian officials would not elaborate on the talks,
although one U.S. source close to the delegation said Murphy may
travel to Lebanon this weekend for meetings with Lebanese
officials, including President Amin Gemayel.
   The United States and Syria have been trying to ensure a
president is elected in Lebanon before Friday, when Gemayel's
six-year term expires. Under the constitution, he cannot seek a
second consecutive term.
   Edde, speaking in a telephone interview from Paris, where he has
been living since 1976 after three assassination attempts in
Lebanon, said the success of Thursday's vote was ``unfortunately''
dependent on the Damascus negotiations.
   An attempt to convene Lebanon's parliament Aug. 18 to elect a
president collapsed when Christian deputies, opposed to Syria's
candidate, former President Suleiman Franjieh, boycotted the
session.
   Lebanon's U.S.-aided Christians oppose Syria's efforts to impose
a settlement to end the 13-year-old civil war. Franjieh was the
only serious contender until Edde announced his candidacy last week.
   Edde, a 75-year-old Maronite Christian, said once Israel
withdraws its troops from a so-called ``security zone'' in south
Lebanon, he can ask Syria to withdraw its forces.
   ``Without that, Lebanon is not independent, with the presence of
both the Israeli and Syrian armies,'' said Edde, a former interior
minister.
   The government-run Syrian press, after virtually ignoring Edde,
quoted him Saturday as saying the presence of their army in Lebanon
was legal.
   The article was interpreted as a sign Edde is emerging as a
compromise candidate in the discussions between the Syrian and U.S.
sides.
   Edde confirmed he said Syrian troops were in Lebanon legally
because they were invited there in 1976 by the Lebanese government
and had a peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League. But he said
there would be no need for them once Israel withdrew.
   ``I am convinced there will be no more civil war if there is a
withdrawal because I am confident in the Lebanese people from both
sides, both Moslem and Christian,'' he said.
   Edde said if Israel did not withdraw he would not return to
Lebanon and would instruct parliament instead to elect another
president.
</TEXT>
