<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gilbert-Louisiana     09-17 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert-Louisiana,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gilbert Leaves Grand Isle's Highway Just 100 Feet From Shore</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert's waves washed away 25
feet of coastline, leaving the highway connecting the island to the
mainland in danger if another storm hits the Gulf of Mexico, an
official said Saturday.
   ``Now the state is really going to have to get into the scene
because there is a threat to the highway,'' said Mayor Andy
Valence, who ordered the 2,000 inhabitants to evacuate during the
storm.
   Altogether, he said, the resort community lost 100 feet of land
from hurricanes Gilbert and Florence. Now Louisiana Highway 1 is
only 100 feet from shore in some places, he said.
   Grand Isle's losses are only a small part of the coastal erosion
in a state which loses more than 50 square miles of coastal
wetlands each year. But it's a significant amount for an island
about a mile wide and eight miles long facing the open Gulf of
Mexico due south of New Orleans.
   Other parts of the state apparently escaped Gilbert's passage
across the Gulf unscathed, aside from minor damage from a tornado
Friday in Slidell, north of New Orleans.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer will join Valence next week to survey the
coastal damage to the state's only populated barrier island.
   Valence has been trying raise money to build two stone jetties
to stop or at least slow down the erosion.
   The jetties were a major campaign platform for the new mayor,
who took office 75 days ago. Since then, he's had to evacuate the
island four times for hurricanes Beryl, Florence and Gilbert, and a
tropical storm.
   Valence said that's a record for Grand Isle. ``People are very
sensitive to weather conditions here,'' he said. ``At the same
time, we're equally sensitive to Grand Isle's beauty and charm.''
   Valence and about 12 emergency workers rode out the storm on the
island. At its worst point Thursday night, the pounding of the surf
created a salt mist that shorted out and exploded hundreds of power
company transformer connectors.
   Valence lifted his evacuation order Saturday morning, but police
dispatcher Linda Blanchard said many residents went home much
earlier while Gilbert was hitting Mexico.
   ``We started coming back Friday afternoon,'' she said. ``There
was no water on the roads then.''
</TEXT>
