<DOCNO> AP880917-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrailofTears     09-17 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trail of Tears,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Trail Of Tears' Wagon Train Commemorates Indians' Forced March In
1838</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCLE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A steady rain fell Saturday as a small
wagon train departed from Red Clay State Historical Park for
Tahlequah, Okla., to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the
infamous ``Trail of Tears.''
   ``It's fitting,'' observed Ray Morris, the coordinator of the
project. ``From what I've read, the first bunch of Cherokees were
forced to leave on a day much like this one.''
   Morris, of Golconda, Ill., drove one of the six covered wagons
that will make the 1,000-mile journey, scheduled to end in early
December. Participants hope to call attention to the federal
government's forced removal of the Cherokees from their eastern
homelands in 1838.
   ``I think the blackest chapter of our nation's history began
with the Indian Removal Act of 1830 and culminated with the
relocation of the Cherokees in 1838,'' Morris said.
   ``The government called it a treaty but what it really amounted
to was   ...   at gunpoint. They were made
to leave their homes and walk to Oklahoma so the white settlers
could have their land.''
   According to historical accounts of the trek, the first group of
Cherokees, numbering about 1,000, departed Oct. 1, 1838, from Red
Clay, their last tribal council ground in the East. They were
accompanied by federal troops and state militia. In all, 13 groups
of Indians made the trek.
   ``About 4,000 of the Indians, or more than one-third of those
who started out from Tennessee in the fall of 1838, died along the
way,'' Morris said. ``Yet, there are only two marked graves, in
Hopkinsville, Ky., along the entire route of the Trail Of Tears.
It's a page of our history that's largely been ignored.''
   The wagons that left Red Clay on Saturday were pulled by four
mule teams and two teams of horses. A half-dozen riders on
horseback also joined the first leg of the trek.
   Among the riders was Ricky Todd, a farmer from Woodbury, Tenn.,
who said he first heard of the Trail of Tears as a little boy when
he saw it mentioned on a plaque. Woodbury was one of the towns the
Indians went through.
   Todd is the project's Tennessee coordinator.
   ``This is an educational project and we'd like for people to
come out and walk or ride with us for a while,'' he said. ``In my
town, I know, the schoolchildren will be coming down to see the
wagon train and learn more about what happened on the Trail of
Tears.''
   ``We want them to know that the Cherokees weren't savages in
loincloths, that they were a civilized people whose land was stolen
by the white man.''
   Morris said the wagons represent each of the six states the
Cherokees went through on their way to Oklahoma.
   ``The Cherokees followed a circuitous route through Tennessee,
Kentucky, Illinois, Missouri, Arkansas and Oklahoma, a route that
later would be known as the Trail of Tears,'' he said. ``We're
going to stay as close to that route as is possible.''
   Prior to embarking, Morris read a letter from Wilma Mankiller,
the principal chief of the Cherokee Nation at Tahlequah.
   ``Those of you who are taking part in this commemoration of the
Cherokee Trail of Tears cannot conceive the human misery of those
you now honor,'' she wrote.
   ``The Cherokee people had lived much like their rural southern
neighbors. They were a settled, agricultural people with a
democratic form of government. The effect of the removal was to
thrust the Cherokee people back into the Stone Age.''
   Morris, an agricultural adviser, said he expects the trip to
take 76 days, or about half as long as it took the Cherokees to get
to Oklahoma. Participants are financing the trip out of their own
pockets, except for $1,000 donated by the state of Illinois, he
said.
   ``I know we'll run into some problems along the way, but they
won't be anything compared with the sacrifices the Cherokees had to
make,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, bonta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
