<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hurricane-Mayor     09-17 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Mayor,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Has Had Hectic Three Months in First Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-term Mayor Ygnacio Garza never
wanted to be in the spotlight, but he has had a hectic summer
dealing with a store roof collapse that killed 14 and coordinating
efforts to prepare for a hurricane.
   By city charter, the mayor's post is not very powerful, but
Garza has taken control of a city where several former top
officials were accused of wrongdoing.
   Garza, a 35-year-old certified public accountant who served as a
city commissioner in 1979-83, said he stayed out of politics after
his first venture because he didn't think it was for him.
   He returned last year to help manage his native city's
administration after it was rocked by scandal.
   ``Although the city charter gives the mayor very little power,
the leadership has to be shown regardless of what the charter
says,'' said Garza, a 6-foot-6 man nicknamed ``Nacho.'' ``You have
to assume a leadership role if you are going to lead a city through
a crisis.''
   On July 7, the roof of the Amigo Store collapsed under the
weight of torrential rain, trapping dozens and killing 14 people.
   Garza took control, coordinating initial rescue efforts and
later talking to officials from across the country who offered
equipment, food and medical supplies for the victims and their
families.
   Garza learned that the city lacked some heavy equipment and
communications gear, but said he was pleased that numerous private
companies offered their assistance almost immediately.
   This past week, while Hurricane Gilbert moved through the
Caribbean toward the Texas-Mexico border area, Garza and other city
officials prepared for the worst, although the storm ran inland to
the south in Mexico.
   The store roof collapse had one effect on the city's
preparations for the storm.
   ``What the roof collapse did was give us confidence in our
rescue procedures, that we could deal with a disaster as
devastating as a hurricane,'' Garza said. ``The roof collapse was
more reactionary and with the hurricane we did have some lead time
and we knew what we wanted to do.''
</TEXT>
