<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     09-17 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Two Palestinians, Wound 27 In Day Of Strikes, Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians staged a general strike Saturday
to mark the sixth anniversary of a Beirut refugee camp massacre.
Israeli soldiers shot and killed two Palestinians and wounded 27,
Arab reports and hospital officials said.
   The army clamped curfews on 250,000 Palestinians in the occupied
Gaza Strip and arrested more than 100 alleged Arab ringleaders in
the occupied West Bank in a nighttime raid aimed at heading off the
disturbances.
   The 1.5 million Arabs of the occupied territories obeyed orders
issued by underground leaders to stage a general strike marking the
massacre of hundreds of Palestinians in Beirut's Sabra and Chatilla
refugee camps by Israeli-backed Christian militiamen in 1982.
   In a related development, Egypt marked the 10th anniversary of
the Camp David peace accords by again blaming ``Israeli
intransigence'' for the U.S.-brokered plan's failure to give the
Palestinians a voice in ruling themselves.
   Butros Ghali, minister of state for foreign affairs, said in
Cairo: ``Egypt had hoped that this anniversary would come at a time
when there was peace in the Middle East and Palestinians enjoyed
the right of self determination.
   ``But because of Israeli intransigence, and the continuation of
its occupation of the West Bank and Gaza strip, and its
continuation of repressive measures which stand against all
international laws as well as U.N. principles, the Palestinian
people still live under tragic circumstances.''
   The signing of the two accords, which laid down a framework that
led seven months later to the only peace treaty between Israel and
an Arab country, followed 13 days of negotiations at the U.S.
presidential retreat at Camp David, Maryland.
   Egypt considers that accord frozen since negotiations among
Israel, Egypt and the United States broke down in 1982.
   Ghali's statement noted the uprising that began in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza last Dec. 8. He said the Palestinians ``have
refused and rebelled against (Iraeli occupation) in a huge popular
uprising.''
   Palestinians Saturday stayed away from their jobs and kept
indoors except for knots of mostly young protesters who took to the
streets to burn tires and stone Israeli forces.
   Late Friday, the army, bracing for trouble, arrested over 100
Palestinians suspected of organizing demonstrations in Nablus,
Dahariya and Tulkarm in the occupied West Bank, a military
spokesman said.
   But the move did not prevent the most widespread and intense
violence in several weeks.
   In Jenin, Israeli soldiers opened fire after dozens of
Palestinian protesters blocked a main road with burning tires and
stones and threw rocks at military vehicles, Arab reporters said.
   The troops killed 18-year-old Emad Arkawi, Palestinian hospital
officials said.
   Arab reporters said Israeli troops also shot and killed
25-year-old Munjed Sarhan, from the village of Lubban Sharqiya.
Sarhan died immediately. His body was draped in a Palestinian flag
and buried, the reporters said.
   A military spokesman confirmed a dead Palestinian was brought to
Jenin hospital but said members of the family took the corpse for
burial and the army could not investigate the cause of death. The
spokesman said he was investigating the reported death in Lubban
Sharqiya.
   Saturday's fatalities brought the Palestinian death toll to 268
since the intefadeh, Arabic for uprising, broke out nine months
ago. Six Israelis also have died.
   Of the 27 Palestinian casualties reported Saturday, the army
confirmed only the wounding of one boy in Gaza.
   In Jenin, insurgents scrawled graffiti in Arabic and Hebrew that
said ``Death to the Jews'' and ``The End is Near.'' It was the
first time protesters have painted graffiti in Hebrew.
</TEXT>
