<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FishChase     09-17 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Chase,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Site Turns To Fish Grab, And Grabbers Get Ticketed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A highway construction site turned into a
fish grab when part of a bayou was drained, leaving a wide, muddy
hole where men with nets, buckets and spears sloshed around after
fish.
   But not for long: state wildlife and fisheries agents armed with
ticket books quickly put the brakes on the landlubber fishermen
Friday.
   ``The people who got citations were the ones in the water
actively chasing the fish,'' said Capt. Burton Wiley of the
wildlife department. ``We didn't write up anyone who was picking up
dead fish off the bank. If they want to scavenge, that's their
business.''
   Agents ticketed only people who caught gamefish such as bass or
perch from the water, letting them keep trash fish such as catfish,
gar and buffalo fish, he said.
   But men at the construction scene after the incident disputed
Wiley, saying the game wardens confiscated all of the fish,
including catfish and buffalo fish. And, they said, nobody was
allowed to pick up any of the fish at the site.
   ``I don't think it is right for us to have to pay a big fine for
catching fish that were going to die anyway,'' the Alexandria Daily
Town Talk quoted an unidentified participant as saying. The minimum
penalty for violating state gamefish regulations is $25.
   Wiley said the best thing for the contractor to have done with
unharmed fish stranded in the pool have been to dump them into the
bayou on the other side of the earthen dam.
   Project engineer Raymond Boniol of the State Department of
Transportation and Development said he was not present when the
tickets were issued and is not familiar with state laws governing
taking fish at a construciton site.
   ``That's not in the plans and specifications we drew up for this
project,'' he joked.
</TEXT>
