<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-17 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school English class took on a task of epic
proportions when they decided to read aloud Homer's epic poems,
``Iliad'' and ``Odyssey.''
   It took them 29 straight hours.
   Carol Samson's class at Columbine High School started at 7 a.m.
Thursday and took turns reading every word of the ``Iliad.'' When
the students finished a little after 10 p.m., they started on the
``Odyssey,'' completing that work just before noon Friday.
   The marathon reading session developed after Samson told the 72
students that it took 31 hours for the Greeks to sing ``Iliad.''
Someone wondered how long it would take to read it, and Samson
suggested they find out.
   Samson had Greek food brought in for the reading, and the
students made paper Greek shields to add to the ambiance in the
classroom.
   Samson said her students didn't care for Achilles, a Greek
warrior and hero in ``Iliad.''
   ``He's proud and arrogant, and when he pulls back and won't
fight, they don't care for that,'' she said. ``One of the students
said, `You know, this Achilles is not a happy camper.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TILFORD, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massie family has learned to step
lightly around the house since moving to the Black Hills in
southwestern South Dakota.
   It seems they have a den of rattlesnakes for neighbors.
   Charles and Ima Massie and their children moved into their rural
home in 1976, and ever since they've had periodic encounters with
snakes.
   ``We keep our eyes open all the time,'' Mrs. Massie said.
   Their first summer, they killed six snakes, she said, including
one that coiled up near a cupboard in the house.
   Through the years, rattlesnakes also have been spotted and
killed in the driveway, in grass, even coiled around the mailbox.
   State officials have inspected the home and determined that a
rattlesnake den was within slithering distance of the house, but
nobody had been able to find it, Mrs. Massie said.
   On Thursday, the Massies returned home to find their neighbor,
Annette Peldo, had just used her .22-caliber rifle to shoot a
rattlesnake that had been coiled near the Massies' backdoor.
   ``The snake had crawled around the corner of the house,'' Mrs.
Massie said. Peldo ``went home and got her .22, jumped up on the
car and shot at him until she killed him. It was really long, about
2{ to 3 feet, and really big.''
</TEXT>
