<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru a0558 09-17 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0558,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Blesses Civil War Victims In Mozambique</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf, `But life...' to UPDATE
with Pope in Nampula; picks up 15th graf pvs: Some Mozambican...
^By DENNIS REDMONT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRA, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday blessed
wheelchair-bound victims of Mozambique's 13-year civil war and
noted improvements in the Marxist government's relations with the
Roman Catholic Church.
   On the last portion of a 10-day, five-nation tour of southern
Africa, the pope flew from the capital, Maputo, to Beira, an Indian
Ocean city of 300,000 isolated except by air and water because of
intense guerrilla activity in the region.
   Beira, the country's second-largest city after Maputo, has been
plagued by almost daily cuts in electricity and water shortages
caused by sabotage from anti-Marxist rebels of the Mozambique
National Resistance movement.
   Protected from a blazing sun by a thatched altar shaped like a
native hut, the pope delivered a Mass at the edge of a golf course
where the grass had been cut for the first time in 14 years, local
officials said. Security surrounding the pope was tight.
   ``The picture frequently described by missionaries who live with
you is not without shadows, due to the prevailing situation of
insecurity, which ... generates violence, anxiety and distress,
leaving limited space for freedom,'' the pope said.
   The civil war, which began after Mozambique gained independence
from Portugal in 1975, has forced about 1 million Mozambicans to
flee to neighboring countries. Relief agencies estimate 6 million
of Mozambique's 14.5 million populace require food aid.
   At the open-air Mass before 50,000 people, the pope blessed a
tractor driver who lost his legs when his vehicle hit a landmine
and a young man whose legs were paralyzed after he was hit by
bazooka fire in a rebel ambush.
   Port and rail links from Beira reach into landlocked African
nations and have been a frequent target of attack by rebels, known
by their Portuguese acronym Renamo.
   The Mozambican government has been openly hostile to churches in
the past, but now is working to improve strained relations.
   The government recently returned church-run schools and
hospitals that it said were mistakenly confiscated when many such
institutions were nationalized. The rector of Beira seminary,
Manuel Machabo, said the government returned two churches in his
area that were being used as a warehouse and a gymnasium.
   In an apparent reference to anti-church government policies, the
pontiff said social ills develop when men begin ``shutting
themselves off to God.''
   But the pope acknowledged the improvements, saying, ``I would
like to recognize also the efforts that are being made at this
moment for the difficulties to be overcome.''
   Life for Beira's residents remains difficult. Communications are
poor, stores lack many basic foods, transportation is difficult and
residents almost never travel outside the city for fear of rebel
attacks.
   ``But life is improving,'' says Maria do Ceu, a Portuguese nun
who teaches languages at a local school. ``Five years ago a piece
of meat was an event, now we have it from time to time.''
   Later, John Paul spoke to about 5,000 people at the airport in
the northern city of Nampula, where he heard more horror stories
about the civil war. The Portuguese archbishop of Nampula, Manuel
Vieira Pinto, said rebels killed 8,000 civilians and plundered
about 600 towns in the past five years.
   John Paul also met with clergy in Nampula before flying back to
Maputo, where he was scheduled to speak Sunday.
   Some Mozambican bishops have urged the government to talk with
the rebels. But President Joaquim Chissano's government has refused
to negotiate and has criticized the bishops for advocating talk
with ``armed bandits.''
   The rebels have been accused of widespread civiian atrocities, a
charge they deny. The U.S. State Department, in an April report,
estimated the rebels have killed 100,000 civilians in the last two
to three years.
   The rebels earlier announced a cease-fire during the pope's
visit and wished the pontiff a good stay.
   Chissano met the pope last May in Rome, but the Vatican appears
to be holding off the establishment of diplomatic relations as an
incentive to advancing the peace process.
   Mozambique, ravaged by drought in recent years, receives most of
its military assistance from the Soviet Union, but increasingly has
been making overtures to Western nations. The United States is the
largest donor of food aid in Mozambique, and Britain has been
providing military training.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
