<DOCNO> AP880917-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Rebels     09-17 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Rebels,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas And Rebels To Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government and
U.S.-backed rebels plan to resume talks Monday after a three-month
stalemate in their search for an end to seven years of war.
   Both sides called the planned two-day conference in Guatemala a
preliminary step toward reopening the high-level talks that broke
off June 9.
   The left-wing Sandinistas and rebels, known as Contras, signed
an accord March 23 to seek a negotiated settlement to the conflict
the government says has claimed the lives of 28,000 Nicaraguans.
   The agreement called on the rebels to lay down their arms in
exchange for democratic reforms. Shortly before the talks broke off
in June, the Sandinistas proposed a timetable for disarmament and
political reforms.
   But the Contras rejected the plan, saying it did not go far
enough. They insisted on the immediate release of political
prisoners, disbanding of the supreme court and full democratic
guarantees.
   A March 21 agreement to suspend offensive military operations
remains in place but both sides accuse the other of violating the
truce.
   The Defense Ministry issues frequent communiques claiming Contra
ambushes of government forces. Bosco Matamoros, spokesman for the
rebels, said recently Sandinista troops attacked Contra positions
93 times in August.
   Earlier this month the Sandinistas proposed preliminary talks in
Guatemala to be followed by a conference in Managua.
   The Contras initially rejected the suggestion, saying the
government had restricted their movements during four earlier talks
in Managua and they would not return to the capital. They also
wanted Nicaragua's opposition parties to participate in the next
round of talks.
   Last weekm the rebels added a new condition. They demanded the
release of more than 40 opposition leaders arrested by police
during a demonstration on July 10.
   Matamoros recently proposed Sept. 26 for the next high-level
talks to be held in a still-to-be decided location.
   The Sandinistas maintain the talks should be held in Managua and
that only the government and the Contras take part.
   Overt U.S. military aid to the rebels ended Feb. 29 and the
Contras have few bargaining chips left.
   Over the past four months, most of the rebel forces fled from
Nicaragua back to base camps inside Honduras where they receive
non-lethal aid suplied by the United States.
   Contra sources say only 2,000 fighters remain inside Nicaragua,
with more than 9,000 in base camps near the border in eastern
Honduras.
   The rebels, saying the Sandinistas still get large amounts of
Soviet-supplied war materiel, are seeking renewed U.S. military aid.
   Both sides are anxiously awaiting the U.S. presidential
elections in November. The Sandinistas hope for a Democratic
victory by Michael Dukakis, who opposes more Contra aid, while the
Republican contender, Vice President George Bush, has supported aid
to the rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
