<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AppleCrop     09-17 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apple Crop,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apples Ready For Consumption, Maybe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the worst growing seasons in recent
memory will mean a smaller-than-usual apple crop in the nation's
second-largest apple-producing state, growers said.
   The effects of late spring rain showers just when pollination
began and a dry summer is coming into focus even as the state's
major apple variety, the McIntosh, is being harvested in orchards
across New York this weekend.
   ``It's too early to tell any numbers, but this year's crop is
definitely down,'' said Lee Peters, a vice president of Fowler
Brother's Orchards in Wolcott.
   Statewide, production this year is estimated to be about 2
million bushels down from last year's 18.8 million bushels,
according to industry figures. It's also the smallest apple crop
since 1972.
   Raymond Lemka, a fruit grower in East Greenbush, said he was
just beginning his harvest, and his crop is looking farily good.
But there is usually a 10-day period in which McIntosh apples can
be picked, he said, and any extended period of rain would be yet
another setback.
   According to the National Weather Service in Albany, a cold
front was headed into the state and showers are likely.
   In Washington state, the nation's leading apple producer,
growers have largely avoided the drought.
   A July forecast for the Washington fall apple crop calls for
total production about one-third less than the record 1987 crop,
but that's largely because trees naturally bear less fruit the year
after a big crop. The total would be about the same as the 1986
crop.
</TEXT>
