<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iceland-Government     09-17 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iceland-Government,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iceland's Government Resigns in Dispute Over Economic Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 15-month-old coalition government
of Prime Minister Thorsteinn Palsson resigned Saturday night after
failing to agree on a program to deal with the country's acute
economic problems.
   President Vigdis Finnbogadottir was expected to decide within a
day whether to call new elections or to ask a leader of one of the
three coalition parties to try to form a government.
   Iceland's fishing industry, which produces 70 percent of the
North Atlantic island nation's export income, has suffered heavy
losses.
   The economic crisis became so severe that on May 14, two days
before he was to have left for Washington, Palsson postponed an
official visit to the United States. He subsequently made the trip
on Aug. 9.
   Also, on May 14, the government temporarily suspended currency
trading because of a drain on foreign reserves caused by
speculation the currency, the crown, would be devalued by 20
percent.
   Leaders of the fishing industry had demanded that sharp a
devaluation, which would have made the prices of exports cheaper
and more competitive but would have increased the prices of imports.
   The economic package under discussion included a 6 percent
devaluation and a new tax package.
   After weeks of negotiation, Palsson of the Party of
Independence, his Social Democratic Finance Minister Jon Ealdvin
Hannibalsson and Foreign Minister Steingrimur Hermannsson of the
Farmer's Party failed to agree.
   The three coalition parties, which formed the government in June
1987, have said they did not want new elections, but the Women's
Ticket party is reported to favor elections because opinion polls
show it gaining popularity.
   Hannibalsson and Hermannsson said Saturday they had been
discussing economic measures, were close to agreement and were
seeking talks with opposition parties to see if they could gather
enough support if either should be asked to form a new government.
   Under a North Atlantic Treaty Organization agreement, Iceland,
with a population of 250,000, is the site of a major U.S. air base
at Keflavik, 25 miles southwest of the capital Reykjavik.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
