<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BookmakingArrests     09-17 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bookmaking Arrests,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Deputies Break Up Alleged Bookmaking Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sports bookmaking operation
that took in more than $1 million a day in receipts was broken up
Saturday by Los Angeles County sheriff's deputies, and four people
were arrested, authorities said.
   Deputies raided two residences at 9:30 a.m. and seized
computers, television monitors and two wire service teletype
machines, said Deputy Detta Roberts.
   The raid followed a five-month investigation, she said.
   ``The daily receipts were in the millions,'' she said. ``This
was a pretty big operation.''
   The teletypes carried a sports report put out by Sports Network
of Huntington Valley, Pa.
   General Manager Bill Rohrer described the service as a
comprehensive package of sports scores, stories and statistics
geared to broadcasters. He said private individuals also use the
information.
   Arrested for investigation of conspiracy for bookmaking were
Clarence Austin, 47, Fred Cohen, 55, Mark Mitzenmacher, 28, and
Chas Rizzuto, 43, said Ms. Roberts.
</TEXT>
