<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0607 09-17 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Proposes New Federal Department Of Environment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for 5th graf pvs, ``From California ...'' to
UPDATE with Dukakis speech to Black Caucus; INSERTS 1 graf after
11th graf, ``The environment ...'' with reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENA PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, declaring
Republican George Bush has provided ``zero protection for the
environment,'' proposed Saturday elevating the Environmental
Protection Agency to a Cabinet department.
   ``And the first secretary of the Environment is going to be as
committed to protecting the environment as George Bush has been to
neglecting it,'' the Democratic presidential candidate told a
cheering crowd of campaign workers.
   Dukakis drew a roar of approval from several hundred volunteers
when he referred to rhetorical flubs by the Republican ticket.
   ``Dan Quayle doesn't know what century he's in and George Bush
can't remember the Pledge of Allegiance,'' he said.
   From California, Dukakis flew to Washington, D.C., to share the
spotlight at the annual Congressional Black Caucus dinner with
Jesse Jackson and to plead for high turnout among black voters,
acknowledging blacks will be essential to a Democratic victory.
   ``Our adversaries are not just George Bush and Dan Quayle,''
Dukakis said in prepared remarks. ``Our adversaries are despair and
resignation and indifference and complacency.''
   He struck several themes important to blacks, including civil
rights, law enforcement, increasing the minimum wage, support for
black colleges and sanctions against South Africa's repressive
apartheid regime.
   Dukakis laid out his plan for a new Cabinet department at a
rally in a union hall at which his campaign was signing up precinct
workers for the drive to capture California's 47 electoral votes _
the biggest single prize on Election Day.
   With politicians and pollsters agreed that the fight for
California's critical electoral votes was currently a dead heat,
Dukakis was recruiting thousands of precinct workers to his cause.
   At a series of meetings across the state, similar to the one at
which Dukakis spoke, the campaign hoped to sign up 5,000 precinct
captains. The process will be repeated on upcoming weekends in an
effort to have a worker in each of the state's 23,000 precincts.
   The environment is a major issue in California and one of the
most volatile aspects is the controversy over offshore oil drilling.
   Following Dukakis' announcement, National Wildlife Federation
President Jay D. Hair called it ``exactly the kind of presidential
leadership needed to address some of the most complex and important
human and environmental health issues before our society.''
   While the Reagan administration has advocated pushing ahead with
drilling off the California coast, Bush said last spring that he
favored a delay in approving pending leases to determine if they
were environmentally sound.
   ``He's done more somersaults than an Olympic gymnast on the
subject of offshore drilling off the California coast,'' said
Dukakis. ``When he's in Texas _ he's for it. When he's in
California, he says _ well, maybe not.
   ``My friends, we need a president who won't change his position
with the time zone.''
   ``There'll be no drilling in Santa Monica Bay,'' he pledged.
``And we're going to send the administration's five-year oil and
gas leasing plan back to the drawing board.''
   Dukakis ridiculed Bush's record on the environment, saying ``he
calls for `zero tolerance' against those who poison our water with
toxic chemicals, but for seven and a half years, he's provided zero
protection for the environment of this country.''
   He said that as chairman of the White House task force on
regulatory reform Bush ``diluted, delayed and destroyed scores of
regulations to preserve the environment.''
   In a fact sheet distributed by the Dukakis staff, it was noted
that the EPA budget already is larger than those for the State and
Commerce departments and that it employs more people than the
departments of Housing and Urban Development and Education.
   The cost was described as ``insignificant,'' perhaps as little
as a few hundred thousand dollars.
   Dukakis spoke in front of banner that read, ``Orange County
Volunteer Victory Team.'' The volunteers all received red, white
and blue Dukakis for president signs and were told to put them up
in front of their homes and urge neighbors to do the same.
   ``Don't let anybody tell you this campaign is just television,''
he told the volunteers.
   But the Dukakis forces have an uphill fight in Orange County, a
Republican bastion. The best Democrats hope for in the area is to
hold down the GOP majority to a level they can overcome with votes
from heavily Democratic areas of the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
