<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     09-17 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims It Resettled Kurds In Modern Villages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAMARNI, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq has transformed the face of its
northern Kurdish region with battles and bulldozers, and an
official said Saturday that residents of hundreds of razed villages
were moved to new, more modern towns.
   The government, which has accused of attacking Kurdish
separatist rebels with chemical weapons, flew foreign reporters by
helicopter to this devastated village and over much of the region
Friday and Saturday.
   Guides ate grapes growing in one area allegedly attacked by
chemical weapons to support the government's denial it used poison
gas during its recent offensive against the Kurds.
   Rebel leaders claim 4,300 Kurds died in Iraqi gas attacks.
   Many other areas visible from the air have been bulldozed in
what officials describe as a plan to concentrate Iraqis throughout
the country in towns more easily served with power, water and other
amenities.
   ``We are bringing together the families of the villages'' into
new towns of 2,000 to 3,000 people, Namuk Raqib Sorji, the
provincial governor, told reporters in Dihok, 210 miles south of
the Turkish border and 250 miles north of Baghdad.
   ``The villages are isolated and far-flung,'' he said. ``It is
very difficult to bring services to people.''
   Dihok is one of three governorates in Iraq's Kurdish region,
where about 3.5 million Kurds live.
   ``About 200 small villages in Dihok alone'' have been
eliminated, the provincial governor, Sorji told reporters.
   Bamarni, 12 miles south of the Turkish border, fell victim to
the Iraqi army's massive thrust against Kurdish rebels, who had
been supported by Iran. The offensive began shortly after a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the eight-year-old Iran-Iraq war went
into effect on Aug. 20.
   A bulldozer stood on a hill overlooking the smashed concrete and
mud-brick houses. Grape vines still flourished near broken bicycle
frames, old shoes and an abandoned baby doll. Fire had scorched the
orchard on the town's edge. There were no residents.
   Iraqi government escorts took reporters to what they identified
as the Balisian Valley, 95 miles southeast of Bamarni. They said it
is where the rebels claimed gas attacks occurred, but there was no
obvious evidence of that _and no people either.
   The United States and several other western European states have
urged the United Nations to dispatch a team to Iraq to investigate
charges of poison gas attacks but Baghdad has refused.
   On a 90-mile flight from Sulaymaniyah to Arbil, geometric grids
of new concrete dwellings rose along highways or on the outskirts
of large towns.
   Western diplomats say Iraq appeared to be trying to end decades
of simmering rebellion among Kurds by eliminating remote village
sanctuaries and putting the general population into more easily
controlled centers.
   But the Dihok governor said the program was ``a general
decision'' applied across the country, although outside observers
have not noted movements on a similar scale outside the Kurdish
region.
   Tens of thousands of Kurds from villages have fled into Turkey
and Iran during the latest fighting.
   In another development Iraq's information minister, Latif
Nassayif Jassim, said Saturday Israel would ``pay very dearly'' if
it attacked targets on the pretext they were chemical weapons
plants, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
   In June 1981, Israel carried out what it called a pre-emptive
air strike against the French-built reactor west of Baghdad to
prevent Iraq from developing an atomic bomb.
</TEXT>
