<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     09-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Mass at Controversial Soviet Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people formed a human chain at a
nuclear power plant in the Baltic republic of Lithuania on Saturday
to protest the facility's threat to the environment, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said people from all over Lithuania
locked arms at the Ignalina Atomic Electric Station in the north
east of the republic.
   Fire broke out Sept. 5 in a control cable of the No. 2 reactor,
but no radiation was released, Tass reported at the time.
   During Saturday's demonstration, people cleaned up the area
around the plant located near a lake and planted trees, Tass said.
Some of the protesters were invited to tour the plant.
   Tass did not give a precise number of demonstrators, saying only
that there were thousands, or give their demands.
   The demonstration was part of a growing environmental campaign
in the Soviet Union. Soviets are increasingly taking advantage of
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness, to speak out.
   Gorbachev himself has said the government should pay more
attention to preserving the environment and earlier this year
created an agency to oversee environmental protection.
   Concern over the dangers of nuclear power heightened in the
Soviet Union and worldwide after the April 26, 1986, explosion at
the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the Ukraine. The accident sent
a cloud of radioactivity worldwide and killed 31 people.
   Eight U.S. senators and 20 congressmen sent letters Thursday to
U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz urging him to discuss the
Ignalina plant's problems with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnandze, a U.S.-based group of Lithuanian emigres reported.
Lithuanian Catholic Religious Aid said the letters call for an
international commission to investigate the plant's safety.
   Shultz is to meet Shevardnadze in Washington on Sept. 22-23.
</TEXT>
