<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-17 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Spawns Tornadoes In Texas, Rain in Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert produced dozens of tornadoes in eastern Texas
on Saturday as it weakened and was downgraded to a tropical
depression, and it continued to push rain and thunderstorms across
the southern Plains.
   Eight tornadoes touched down in the San Antonio, Texas, area and
three near Del Rio, Texas. Twisters also touched down near the
Texas communities of Devine, Jourdanton, Fischer, Sattler and Brady.
   Saturday afternoon, Gilbert's center was about 230 miles
west-southwest of Brownsville, Texas, on the Texas-Mexico border.
   Rain and thunderstorms extended across the southern Plains and
into eastern Arkansas, northern Mississippi and northern Alabama,
the Appalachians, from Florida across New York state and western
New England.
   Rain also was scattered over northwest Montana.
   Rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 2.10
inches at Bluefield, W.Va.; 1.96 inches at the Air Force Base near
San Antonio; 0.84 of an inch at Greer, S.C.; and 0.83 of an inch at
Hickory, N.C.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Saturday night and Sunday
for western and central Montana. Cold rain was expected to become
locally heavy snow in the mountains and passes. As much as 8 inches
of snow was expected over the southwest and central mountains by
Sunday, with up to a foot of new snow in the higher mountains.
   The cold and rain also were expected to reach across northern
Wyoming and snowfall of 2 to 5 inches was possible in the mountains
of northern Wyoming, including the Yellostone National Park area.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at both Cutbank and Great Falls, Mont., to 96 degrees at
Palm Springs, Calif. The nation's low Saturday was 22 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Sunday's forecast was for rain and thunderstorms from the
eastern two-thirds of Texas across Oklahoma and eastern Kansas,
from northern Arkansas across Iowa, Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana,
northwest Kentucky, western Tennessee, northern Mississippi,
Alabama, Georgia and northwest Florida. Showers also were expected
from Maine across east-central New England and thunderstorms were
to extend from Montana across Wyoming into the western portion of
the northern Plains, with rain becoming snow in the mountains.
   High temperatures were to be in the 40s and 50s over the
northern half of the Rockies and the upper Missouri Valley. Highs
in the 60s and 70s were forecast from New England across New
Jersey, the northern Appalachians, the remainder of the upper
Midwest and Rockies and the Pacific Northwest, with 70s along the
California coast. Temperatures were to reach the low 90s in
Florida, southern Mississippi and Louisiana, and from southwest
Texas through the desert Southwest, with 80s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
