<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Famine     09-17 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Famine,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Obstructing Relief Supplies to Southern Sudan, Government
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel attacks are preventing convoys of
relief supplies from reaching the famine-stricken south, a
provincial governor was quoted Saturday as saying.
   The Sudan Peoples' Liberation Army is ``obstructing relief
operations to southern Sudan and that has stopped the works of the
Red Cross there,'' Mauris Lawya, governor of Equatoria Province,
said in a statement to the Sudanese daily Al-Nahar.
   Lawya said rebel attacks during the past few days forced an
army-escorted convoy of 912 trucks headed for the provincial
capital Juba, 750 Miles south of to return back to Yie, 70 miles to
the northwest.
   Lawya said only 96 out of 1,080 supply trucks from neighboring
Uganda were able to make the journey to Juba, 750 miles south of
the capital Khartoum, because of such attacks.
   The rebels believe the government might use relief convoys as a
cover to move military reinforcements into areas under guerrilla
control.
   Meanwhile, the rebel group claimed in a radio broadcast
monitored Saturday that it captured Katre, a garrison town 20 miles
from the border with Uganda and warned aircraft not to fly over
southern Sudan without its permission.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nairobi, also called on civilians to
evacuate Juba and nine other southern Sudan towns.
   Pacifico Lado Loleik, who represents South Sudan in the
sovereign council, which acts as head of state, said earlier this
week that rebel attacks are stopping food trucks from reaching
Malakal, an Upper Nile city 425 miles south of Khartoum.
   Officials have said thousands of people in the south have died
and tens of thousands more may also perish without food shipments.
   The rebels, mostly Christians and animists, are seeking more
autonomy as well as economic and administrative reforms from the
Moslem majority government in the north.
</TEXT>
