<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-LiPeng 1stLd-Writethru   09-17 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Li Peng, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0572,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Says Relations Improved With Moscow, Denies Leadership
Split</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT Keating title to board chairman,
sted executive board chairman; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Premier Li Peng said Saturday that China
and the Soviet Union could hold their first summit in three decades
if lower-level talks succeed.
   China's highest-ranking government official also denied strongly
that the Chinese leadership is divided over how to proceed with the
nation's economic reforms, now riddled with inflation, overspending
and corruption.
   Li spoke in an interview with The Associated Press board of
directors and executives. It was China's most positive response yet
to Soviet calls for an improvement in ties.
   On Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev called for ``full
normalization'' between the two Communist giants. Moscow and
Beijing have been politically at odds since an ideological falling
out in 1960.
   Li said he welcomed such a call.
   In a 40-minute interview at the Diaoyutai state guesthouse, Li
stressed that Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, often
regarded as Li's political rival, has been a full participant in
recent decisions to slow down reforms.
   ``Rumors going around the world'' of a serious rift in the
leadership are groundless, Li said. Minor differences over policies
are ``normal phenomena,'' he said. ``Our top leadership is united.''
   Li said China ``would like very much to normalize our relations
with the Soviet Union.''
   He noted that China and the Soviet Union share 4,300 miles of
common border, ``so the strain on relations between the two
countries is not in the interest of China because we need to
modernize our country in a peaceful environment.''
   He also emphasized that China has no intention of becoming an
ally of the Soviet Union or returning to the relationship of the
1950s, when Moscow acted as a big brother to the fledgling
Communist government in Beijing.
   The premier also refuted the idea that better Chinese-Soviet
ties would be a threat to the West.
   ``Let me tell you a secret,'' he said with a smile. ``Recently
when your Defense Secretary (Frank) Carlucci was here I asked him
some questions about the Soviet military strength and he told me a
lot of things I did not know.''
   Li also left open the possibility of the first Chinese-Soviet
summit since Nikita Khrushchev met Mao Tse-tung in 1959.
   Gorbachev, in his speech in Siberia Friday, renewed overtures
for a summit he first made in Vladivostok in 1986.
   Although Li noted China's longstanding ``three obstacles'' to a
Chinese-Soviet summit, he seemed to play down the differences while
emphasizing that China ``would like very much to normalize
relations.''
   The three obstacles are the Soviet troop presence in
Afghanistan, the nine-year occupation of Cambodia by Soviet-allied
Vietnam, and the heavy Soviet troop presence on its border with
China.
   Progress recently has been made in all three areas.
   He said Chinese-Soviet talks on Cambodia in Beijing last month
had ``reached certain results.''
   He said some disagreements remain on other issues, but ``once
there is further agreement the subject of a summit meeting will be
placed on the agenda.''
   Li tried to dispel reports of dissension within China's
political ranks by explaining that all top decisions are made by
the Communist Party Politburo, which is headed by party chief Zhao
and includes Li.
   He said decisions made in the past month to calm consumers and
cool off the economy, including a ban on further price increases
this year, were made ``under the directorship of General Secretary
Zhao Ziyang and some were proposed by him himself.''
   Some Western and Hong Kong reports have speculated that Zhao,
who advocates bold policies of introducing market-oriented reforms,
is in trouble because of the current serious side-effects of the
reforms.
   Li said the reforms, initiated by senior leader Deng Xiaoping 10
years ago, will proceed, but there is a need to stabilize an
economy battered by a 20-percent inflation rate, rising government
deficits and uncontrolled spending on public projects.
   The Associated Press delegation was led by William J. Keating,
AP board chairman and chief executive officer of the Detroit
Newspaper Agency, and AP President and General Manager Louis D.
Boccardi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
