<HEAD>Former Panamanian Ambassador To Washington Arrested, Relative Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dominador Kayser Bazan, a former Panamanian
ambassador to the United States, has been arrested by the security
forces of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Bazan's brother said
Saturday.
   Rey Bazan said men in civilian clothes went to his brother's
home with an arrest warrant issued by the district attorney's
office.
   Noriega, as the commander of Panama's 15,000 member Defense
Forces, controls the civilian government.
   Dominador Bazan, an associate of President Eric Delvalle who was
deposed by Noriega last Februay, had resigned as ambassador to
Washington in late 1987.
   Delvalle was ousted after he tried to fire Noriega as the
military commander. Noriega had been indicted in February by two
federal grand juries in Florida that accused him of drug
trafficking.
   Dominador Bazan had been named foreign minister only a few hours
before Delvalle was removed, and he also left the government.
   He was a director of a television station owned by Delvalle that
was shut down by the government earlier this year.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle as Panama's
president and has imposed economic sanctions against Panama.
Noriega has defied U.S. pressure to resign and leave the country.
