<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-UN     09-17 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-UN,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Says U.N. Chief To Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Saturday
that U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will visit
South Africa soon to discuss a regional peace initiative.
   Roland Darroll, a spokesman for the Department of Foreign
Affairs, said he did not know the exact date of Perez de Cuellar's
planned visit and additional details would be released Monday.
   A U.N. spokeswoman in New York said Tuesday that Perez de
Cuellar had accepted an invitation from President P.W. Botha to
visit South Africa.
   Spokeswoman Nadia Younes said, ``A mutually convenient time for
the visit is being discussed. When the visit materializes, the
secretary-general will use the opportunity to visit certain other
countries in the region.''
   The U.N. General Assembly will formally open its 43d annual
session on Tuesday. The guerrilla wars in Angola and South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia, are on the agenda in coming weeks.
   South Africa has administered Namibia under a mandate issued by
the League of Nations after World War I and has rejected U.N.
resolutions repudiating that mandate and calling for independence
for the territory.
   South Africa has said it is willing to grant independence to the
territory next June 1 if the estimated 50,000 Cuban military
personnel supporting the Marxist government in neighboring Angola
have been withdrawn by that date.
   Angolan, Cuban and South African troops have been observing a
cease-fire since Aug. 8 in the 13-year-old war in Angola. South
Africa and the United States back the rebels of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola.
   In Namibia, guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's
Organization have been fighting for independence from
white-controlled South Africa since 1966.
   Angolan, Cuban and South African representatives and U.S.
mediators have held several rounds of talks in recent months and
another set of negotiations may be held this week in Brazzaville,
Congo.
   They have not been able to agree on a date for Namibian
independence and the removal of the Cubans from Angola.
   Perez de Cuellar has frequently criticized South Africa's system
of apartheid, under which the 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs and the 5 million whites control the country.
</TEXT>
