<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GrapeBoycott-Beating     09-17 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grape Boycott-Beating,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Reassigned As Beating Incident Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer was reassigned after
videotapes showed him thrusting his baton into a crowd
demonstrating outside a hotel where Vice President George Bush was
holding a fund-raiser, the mayor said Saturday.
   United Farm Worker leader Dolores Huerta, who was distributing
information about a table grape boycott, was injured during the
demonstration Wednesday.
   Mayor Art Agnos said Huerta was cleary visible in the group seen
on the videotape. Huerta suffered two broken ribs and a ruptured
spleen.
   Police said there were about 100 officers and 850 protesters at
the demonstration outside the hotel where Bush was holding a
$1,000-a-plate fund-raiser. Earlier that day, Bush had announced
his opposition to the union's table grape boycott.
   Huerta, 58, a union vice president, co-founded the union in 1964
with her brother-in-law Cesar Chavez.
   Agnos said he, Police Chief Frank Jordan and other top police
officials reviewed videotapes of the protest provided by television
station KRON before deciding to reassign officer Francis Achim to
administrative duty, pending the outcome of several investigations
into the incident.
   The mayor said that he has asked the police department to review
its policies for use of batons in crowd-control situations.
   ``Police face a difficult task when outnumbered by large numbers
of demonstrators and I want to be sure they use the most prudent
methods _ methods that minimize the risk of injury to themselves or
anyone else,'' Agnos said.
   Agnos, a UFW supporter for 20 years, has visited Huerta at the
hospital at least twice. He said she has not been interviewed about
the incident yet, on the request of her doctor.
   According to Huerta's son, Emilio, an officer took a UFW flag
she was carrying, threw it to ground and stomped on it. He also
said the same officer poked her several times above her left hip.
   In Southern California on Saturday, actor Martin Sheen led 350
supporters of the union's ``Boycott Grapes'' campaign on a
traffic-stopping march down Pacific Coast Highway in Malibu. The
march was dedicated to Huerta.
   Chavez staged a 36-day fast that ended Aug. 21 to protest
pesticide use on grapes. Union officials charge that excess use of
the chemicals has caused cancer in farm worker families, a charge
that government and industry officials strongly deny.
</TEXT>
