<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint Committee Discusses Arab Financial Backing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian and Jordanian officials met
Saturday to discuss aid from Arab countries to help Palestinians in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Jordan's news media
reported.
   The joint Jordanian-Palestinian Committee on the Steadfastness
of Palestinians Living in Israeli-Occupied Territories ``reviewed
its financial situation and ways of contacting some Arab countries
for funds needed so that the committee can continue its
activities,'' the official news agency said.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the committee wants to raise
$450 million to finance economic and social projects in the
territories.
   The official, speaking with the condition he not be identified,
said the committee would contact Arab countries that have not paid
promised commitments to the fund.
   Mahmoud Abbas, member of the executive committee of the
Palestine Liberation organization, headed the Palestinian side at
the meeting and Foreign Minister Taher Masri led the Jordanian side.
   King Hussein and PLO leader Yasser Arafat formed the joint
committee in 1980 to channel economic and other aid to 1.5
Palestinians living under Israeli occupation. It became the only
formal link between Jordan and the PLO after Hussein's decision in
July to his government from Palestinian affairs in the occupied
territories.
   A 9-month-old uprising against Israeli occupation in the
territories has left 268 Palestinians and six Israelis dead.
   According to resolutions of the Arab League's Baghdad summit in
1980, oil-rich Arab countries agreed to contribute $100 million to
help finance development projects in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
captured by Israel from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
War.
   Among those countries _ Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates and
Saudi Arabia _ only the Saudi government kept its promise and paid
its $30 million share, the official said.
   Palestinian and Jordanian officials were not available for
comment.
</TEXT>
