<HEAD>Remains of Two U.S. World War II Soldiers Found In Glacier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COURMAYEUR, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police retrieved the remains of two
American servicemen from an icy glacier where their plane crashed
shortly after the end of World War II, the Italian news agency ANSA
reported Saturday.
   The two men, a colonel and a corporal, were killed in 1946 when
their Boeing B-17 crashed at an altitude of 10,000 feet on a snowy
Alpine mountain.
   The wreckage was discovered several years ago embedded in the
ice, but there had been no sign of remains or of documents to
identify the victims, ANSA said.
   Police confirmed the discovery but they refused to release the
identities of the servicemen or say how the remains were found on
Friday.
   Search crews were looking for remains of other victims of the
crash.
