<HEAD>U.N. Human Rights Panel Begins Interviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with meeting with legislative
leaders. Pickup 7th graf pvs `The delegation's...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. human rights delegation met Saturday
in Havana with Cuban activists, religious groups and legislative
leaders, the official Cuban news agency Prensa Latina said.
   Cuban President Fidel Castro invited the Geneva-based U.N. Human
Rights Commission to Havana to investigate U.S. allegations that
his government is guilty of serious human rights violations.
   The delegation, which arrived in the Cuban capital Friday for a
nine-day visit, met at the Hotel Commodore with six members of the
Pro-Human Rights Committee of Cuba and with four members of the
executive committee of the Ecumenical Council of Cuba, Prensa
Latina said in a dispatch monitored in Mexico City.
   It reported the president of the ecumenical council, Raul
Suarez, said his delegation ``didn't denounce anyone. We just
represented the 18 churches and seven ecumenical movements that are
part of the council.''
   Prensa Latina said the hotel lobby was packed with reporters,
onlookers and several people who described themselves as formerly
imprisoned ``counterrevolutionaries'' who want to leave Cuba.
   The agency's report said that later the U.N. delegation had a
two-hour meeting with legislative leaders. It quoted the head of
the National Assembly as saying he and other lawmakers described
Cuba's legislative system and ``responded to a number of
questions.''
   Cuban officials have said the U.N. delegation members can talk
to whomever they like.
   The delegation's spokesman, Roger Han-Moevi of Benin, said the
panel planned to interview private citizens, government officials
and representatives of non-governmental organizations during the
visit, the news agency reported.
   On Sunday, the U.N. delegation planned to visit the Island of
Youth, where 20,000 people from all over the Third World work and
study, Prensa Latina said.
