<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-USBases     09-17 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US Bases,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Aquino Says She Is Still Hopeful On U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Friday
she hoped the Philippines and the United States could resolve their
differences and end a deadlock over compensation and other issues
in negotiations over U.S. bases.
   ``Well, they have their position, and we have ours,'' she said
of the disagreement.
   Mrs. Aquino made her remarks before Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev offered to give up the Soviet base at Cam Ranh Bay,
Vietnam, if the United States closes its six installations in the
Philippines.
   She told reporters Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus was trying
to narrow differences in his talks with Secretary of State George
P. Shultz in the United States, ``so I'm hoping they will.''
   The Filipino-U.S. talks are to set compensation and other terms
for the final two years of the bases agreement, which expires in
1991. Mrs. Aquino refuses to say if she will support extending the
agreement.
   On Thursday, Shultz said in Washington that the United States
wants to keep the giant Clark Air Base, Subic Navy Base and other
installations but Filipino money demands were too high.
   U.S. officials say Washington is considering moving the bases to
Guam or other sites.
   The United States now pays about $180 million a year to use the
bases. Congressional sources have said Washington offered to
increase the compensation to nearly $500 million, including
doubling direct bases-related aid to $360 million.
   Manila newspapers say the Philippines has demanded up to $1.2
billion a year, although Manglapus refuses to confirm that figure.
   Many Filipinos see the bases as an odious vestige of American
rule here, which ended with Philippine independence in 1946.
   In addition, Manglapus and other officials maintain the bases do
not serve Philippine interests because the country does not
perceive an external threat.
   Last week, Deputy Foreign Secretary Jose Ingles told a meeting
of non-aligned nations in Nicosia, Cyprus, that the bases may
threaten national security by making the Philippines a target in a
future superpower confrontation.
</TEXT>
