<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-TrainCrash     09-17 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Train Crash,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Chain of Circumstances' Behind Deadly June Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report on a June train crash that killed 57
people said a radio alert from the train hurtling out of control 90
seconds before impact was not relayed over loudspeakers at the
station until 30 seconds before it hit.
   An investigating commission's findings, made public Friday, said
the accident at the Gare de Lyon station was due to a ``chain of
circumstances'' implicating both personnel and the complex rules of
the state-run train authority.
   The 36-page report recommended better training for personnel,
modification of some equipment and an improved radio network.
   It stressed the ``unfavorable circumstances'' caused by a
passenger who pulled an alarm to automatically stop the suburban
train shortly before it was to enter Paris at rush hour June 27.
   The train restarted, then hurled without breaks into the
station, crashing into a standing train about to depart.
   The report said that from the moment the conductor tried
rearming the breaks after the unscheduled stop, a series of
technical and human errors took place.
   The report noted that a radio alert was given just 1{ minutes
before the accident while loudspeakers warned of the impending
crash just 30 seconds in advance, leaving passengers on the
standing train little time to evacuate. Most of the dead were in
the standing train.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre said the report had been
handed over to the head of the train authority, Jacques Fournier,
for study before a board meeting scheduled for Oct. 26.
</TEXT>
