<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RailEquipment-Justice     09-17 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Equipment-Justice,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Opposes Rail-Equiqment Makers' Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has advised the
Canadian and Illinois-based makers of railroad maintenance
equipment that it will file a lawsuit to block their proposed joint
manufacturing venture, a department official said Friday.
   The $30 million project proposed by Ivaco Inc. of Montreal and
Jackson Jordan Inc. of Schaumburg, Ill., would violate federal
antitrust laws, said Charles F. Rule, the assistant attorney
general in charge of the department's antitrust division.
   In a statement issued late Friday, Rule said the venture might
lessen competition in the production and sale of automatic tampers,
large pieces of equipment used to level and allign railroad tracks.
   ``The proposed joint venture would control over 70 percent of
the automatic tampers sold in the United States,'' he said. ``We
are particularly concerned ... because it would reduce to only two
the number of United States sellers of automatic tampers. As a
result, railroad companies would face higher prices.''
   Sales of the tampers totalled about $15 million last year, the
Justice Department said.
   Ivaco is the largest domestic producer of the equipment, made by
its Canron Inc. subsidiary at plants in Columbia, S.C., Toronto,
and Queensland, Australia, the department said.
   It said Jackson Jordan, which produces tampers at a plant in
Ludington, Mich., ranks third in U.S. production behind Plasser &
Theurer of Austria, which operates a plant in Chesapeake, Va.
   A receptionists answering the telephone at Jackson Jordan
headquarters said the company's offices were closed for the weekend
and that officials could not be reached for comment. Calls to Ivaco
in Montreal were unanswered.
</TEXT>
