<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BenzeneRegulations     09-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Benzene Regulations,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Must Decide If It Will Regulate All Benzene Emissions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency must
decide by March 13 whether to regulate benzene emissions from at
least nine additional sources, according to a federal judge's
ruling.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge June L. Green declined,
however, to impose a deadline sought by an environmental group for
tightening controls on evaporation of gasoline, one source of
benzene, from cars.
   Benzene is a major chemical building block for producing other
chemicals. Breathing benzene causes leukemia, according to studies
of industrial workers.
   Though EPA has made decisions about several sources of benzene,
and is considering major regulations for some of them, the judge
said the Clean Air Act requires the agency to make explicit
decisions on benzene emissions from other sources the agency has
identified _ plants making ethylene, chlorobenzene, nitrobenzene,
linear alkyl benzene and cyclohexane; chemical and refinery waste
disposal; industrial solvent usage and the bulk handling and
transportation of gasoline.
   If the agency decides these sources deserve regulation, it must
adopt regulations within six months, the judge said in the ruling
issued Thursday.
   EPA expects to adopt a tightening of auto gasoline evaporation
regulations by the end of the year.
   David Doniger, attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, the plaintiff in the case, said Friday the ruling applied
to all hazardous air pollutants over which EPA has jurisdiction.
``EPA can't just pick one source, regulate it and say, `That's
it,''' Doniger said.
   The sources in question were identified in the 1970s ``but just
dropped off the agency's scopes,'' he said.
   Alan Eckart, associate general counsel of EPA, said: ``We have a
lot of doubt whether she had jurisdiction to issue the order,'' and
for the plaintiff, ``the proper way would have been a petition to
use to regulate those sources.'' However, he said EPA has not
decided whether to appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
