<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ETHoax     09-17 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ET Hoax,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoaxers Hoaxes Special Hoaxing Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the syndicated television show
``Entertainment Tonight'' planned a show on media hoaxers, they
contacted veteran hoaxer Joey Skaggs _ who quickly hoaxed them by
sending a friend to do the interview.
   ``How could I resist?'' Skaggs asked after the program aired
Friday night. ``I mean, who did they think they were dealing with?''
   Skaggs, speaking by telephone from his Manhattan apartment, was
ecstatic after viewing the opening segment on the show, which
featured co-host Mary Hart delivering this caveat:
   ``The hoaxers are honest enough to admit they enjoy the
attention. But their bottom line is this: Let the talk show
bookers, the newspaper assignment editors and the viewers beware.''
   Laughed Skaggs: ``The only problem is they didn't take their own
advice.''
   ``Joey pulled a fast one on us,'' said ET producer Kevin
Narblock from Los Angeles, adding he suspected Skaggs might have
been up to something when a picture of the hoaxer in Penthouse
magazine didn't match the fellow on the film.
   Hart introduced the phony Skaggs, played by writer-teacher
Norman Savage, by detailing a hoax perpetrated on ``Good Morning
America'' where Skaggs offered a cure for the common cold: the
common cockroach.
   Savage, wearing a pair of dark sunglasses, then says, ``What I
hope to achieve is that the public becomes more skeptical. And if
they're more skeptical, maybe they're more discerning, more
demanding. And so the media, then, has to police themselves a
little better.''
   Skaggs said he was doubly tickled because he had appeared
previously on ``Entertainment Tonight,'' so the program should have
footage of what he really looks like.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
