<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EmergencyLanding     09-17 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commuter Plane Belly-Lands At Stapleton Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental Express commuter plane from North
Platte, Neb., belly-landed at Stapleton International Airport
Friday night after the pilot reported landing gear problems, but
there were no reports of injuries.
   Flight 2063, a Beechcraft 1900 propjet scheduled to arrive at
Denver at 5:25 p.m., made the emergency landing at 6:30 p.m.,
Stapleton officials said.
   Stapleton spokesman Richard Boulware said none of the seven
passengers or two crew members appeared to have been injured, and
there was little damage to the plane.
   He said the pilot notified Stapleton officials that he was
having problems lowering the plane's landing gear. Authorities
cleared the runway and posted emergency personnel as the plane went
into its landing pattern.
   The landing itself, telecast by Denver television stations,
appeared smooth, with the plane sliding to a halt without flames or
smoke evident, even though the runway had not been prepared for the
landing with foam.
   Boulware said the propeller was stopped when the plane descended
to 5 feet above the ground. The craft skidded a half-mile down the
runway before coming to a stop, he said.
</TEXT>
