<DOCNO> AP880917-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Korea-Movies     09-17 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea-Movies,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Film Exporters Charge Unfair Trade, Threat of Snakes in
Cinemas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major American motion picture exporters asked
anew Friday for U.S. government intervention to enable them to
operate film distribution offices in South Korea.
   The Motion Picture Export Association of America, in a formal
unfair trade complaint to the U.S. Trade Representative, accused
South Korea of violating a 1985 agreement permitting independent
U.S. distribution of major Hollywood productions, of discrimination
and of failure to crack down on pirating of video cassettes.
   Announcing the action, MPEAA Chairman Jack Valenti told
reporters the South Korean film importing and distributing industry
has launched a ``very aggressive attack to make sure that Americans
never get to open their own offices'' as promised in 1985.
   Seoul cinema houses bypassing local distributors to deal
directly with the American exporters have been threatened with
having ``live snakes let loose in their theaters'' to frighten away
audiences, Valenti said, quoting Korean press reports.
   Two Seoul cinemas that made direct bookings with the U.S.
exporters to show ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``Batteries Not
Included,'' pictures that were hits elsewhere in Asia, were
expelled from their industry association and may be forced to
cancel the openings later this month, Valenti said.
   It is a coincidence that the trade complaint is being filed at
the start of the Seoul Olympic Games, when Korea is at the center
of international attention, Valenti said. MPEAA has been warning
for weeks it would take action unless Korean authorities agreed to
negotiate the issues and a recent meeting with the South Korean
ambassador produced no results, he said.
   The South Korean Embassy did not respond immediately to requests
for comment on the MPEAA complaints.
   The 1985 accord allowed MPEAA companies to import and distribute
their motion pictures in Korea, he said. That accord prompted MPEAA
to withdraw an earlier formal complaint it had filed with the U.S.
trade representative charging unfair trade.
   But three years later, the country's domestic film distribution
industry, ``literally defying their government,'' has made it
economically impossible for U.S. exporters to operate distribution
offices, Valenti said.
   Valenti said South Korea is the only country outside the Soviet
bloc where the U.S. film industry cannot freely operate its own
distribution system and split profits directly with cinemas. South
Korea's 673 cinemas showed 11 MPEAA pictures in 1984, 18 in 1985,
28 in 1986, 30 in 1987 and nine the first half of this year, he
said.
   But independent U.S. film-makers not belonging to MPEAA operate
in South Korea by selling films outright and 75 percent of the
movie houses show American pictures, Valenti acknowledged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
