<1ST_LINE>r a AM-McSleep     09-17 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McSleep,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against Use Of McSleep Inns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quality Inns International Inc. must stop using
the name ``McSleep Inns'' for its economy hotels because the public
would believe the hotels are owned by the fast-food giant
McDonald's Corp., a judge ruled Friday.
   U.S. District Judge Paul Niemeyer said the use of the prefix
``Mc'' is a ``deliberate attempt to benefit by the good will and
reputation of McDonald's.''
   He granted McDonald's a permanent injuction and gave Quality
Inns 30 days to comply with the injunction.
   The company immediately responded to the injunction by changing
the name of their new hotel chain to ``Sleep Inns,'' which will
offer a night's lodging for $20 to $29. The first two ``Sleep
Inns'' will break ground next week in Nova Scotia, Canada, and
Salisbury, N.C., the company said.
   ``The last thing we wanted for our lodging product is to be
confused with some hamburger chain,'' said Gerald Petitt, executive
vice president and chief operating officer for Quality Inns.
``We'll change the name to eliminate any chance of anyone being
confused.''
   Last September, Quality Inns, based in Silver Spring, announced
the new chain of economy hotels to be marketed under the name
``McSleep Inns.''
   Three days later McDonald's demanded that the name not be used.
   After repeated warnings from McDonald's, Quality Inns filed suit
against the hamburger chain, asking the court to declare that
``McSleep'' does not infringe on the chain's trademark. Quality
Inns said the ``McSleep'' name was selected because it connotes a
clear impression of value.
   McDonald's counter-sued Quality Inns in U.S. District Court in
Baltimore, charging that the use of the name constitutes an
infringement and that the public will confuse the hotels with
McDonald's.
   Niemeyer heard the case without a jury in July.
   ``The court has reaffirmed the rights of our customers not to be
confused or mislead by companies trying to profit from our name and
image,'' Chuck Rubner, a McDonald's spokesman, said Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
