<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert roared northward
today, weakened but still flinging tornadoes and sheets of rain at
thousands of shuttered evacuees along the Texas-Mexico border and
threatening flash flooding inland.
   At least 70 people have been killed and more than 800,000 left
homeless since Gilbert ripped through the Caribbean and Mexico with
175-mph winds earlier this week.
   But by this morning, the once massive hurricane's maximum
sustained winds had flagged to 80 mph, and forecasters said the eye
had all but disappeared from the deteriorating storm.
