<DOCNO> AP880917-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Munich-Britain ADV25   09-17 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Munich-Britain, ADV 25,0651</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun Sept. 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For Britain, a Legacy of Appeasement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOUGLAS, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With loyalty unshaken by hindsight,
Lord Home, Neville Chamberlain's aide at the 1938 Munich Pact talks
with Adolf Hitler, defends an episode long ranked among the most
shameful in British history.
   ``Chamberlain decided to continue with this peaceful diplomacy
in order to try to persuade Hitler that war would be a tragedy not
only for Germany, but for Europe,'' Home (pronounced Hume) said in
an interview as the 50th anniversary of the Munich Pact approached.
   ``He thought that Hitler must be sufficiently reasonable to
understand that.''
   Chamberlain bought peace, but Hitler quickly overran all of
Czechoslovakia and started World War II with his invasion of Poland
in 1939.
   Winston Churchill, Chamberlain's successor as prime minister in
1940, sharply assailed his predecessor for signing the Munich Pact.
   Chamberlain died haunted by the words he blurted out to cheering
crowds outside No. 10 Downing St. on Sept. 30, 1938, as he
brandished the piece of paper he'd brought home that day.
   ``I believe it is peace in our time.''
   Home, who as Sir Alec Douglas-Home served as prime minister
himself in 1963-64, sticks to a generous judgment of the leader he
served as parliamentary private secretary from 1937 to 1940.
   ``If you are a prime minister leading a democracy and you want
the nation to go united into a war, then you've got to carry
diplomacy as far as you conceivably can,'' Home said in the
interview at his 50-room estate, Castlemains.
   Home, at 85, is still active politically as a member of the
unelected House of Lords.
   Self-effacing and impeccably mannered, Home recalls both the
chilling details and the vain hopes of the face-to-face talks with
Hitler.
   ``Hitler was in a crude and rude and aggressive mood _ a very
unattractive character,'' he said.
   ``But Chamberlain was concerned to get this bit of paper out of
him, which he'd drafted that morning himself, saying that Britain
and Germany would settle their differences by peaceful means, so a
bit of that short time was taken up with that.''
   The rest consisted of allowing Hitler to annex the Sudetenland
from Czechoslovakia, which the Nazis overran entirely the following
March. Six months later German troops marched into Poland and
Chamberlain finally declared war on Sept. 3, 1939.
   Chamberlain, Home said, never expressed any regrets about the
Munich Pact, but knew he'd blundered with his ``peace in our time''
remark.
   ``As soon as he said the words, he knew that he'd made a mistake
because it was an unjustifiable claim,'' Home added.
   ``He'd gone back to Downing Street from the aerodrome. The
crowds were enormous. I was inside, we were packed like sardines,
and I heard somebody on the staircase say to him, `Well, Neville,
go up to the historic window and say peace in our time.'
   ``And he turned on whoever it was _ I couldn't see who is was _
and said, `I don't do that kind of thing,' ... and somebody in the
next four or five yards must have said, `Oh, Neville, look at the
crowd, go on, do it.' And that's how it happened.''
   Home said the justification for Munich is that it saved a vital
year for British air rearmament.
   ``It could have made all the difference between victory and
defeat.''
   To Churchill, who replaced Chamberlain as prime minister in May
1940, Britain ``chose shame'' at Munich.
   ``We have sustained a defeat without war, the consequences of
which will travel far with us along our road,'' he declared in the
House of Commons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Munich-France ADV25   09-17 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Munich-France, ADV 25,0347</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun Sept. 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For France, a Symbol of Caution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Premier Edouard Daladier returned to France 50
years ago after signing the Munich Pact with Adolf Hitler, Neville
Chamberlain and Benito Mussolini, he received a delirious hero's
welcome.
   In most French eyes he had saved their country and averted war.
   But today, for many French citizens the Munich Pact and the name
Daladier are synonymous with appeasement, even cowardice. It also
may be one of the reasons why the pacifist movement has never
gained much ground in France.
   ``To criticize somebody as a ``Munichois'' is an insult,'' said
Jean-Pierre Azema, a historian at Paris' prestigious Political
Science Institute. ``Somebody who lacks courage is called
Munichois.''
   Yet, at the time, the agreement that gave Czechoslovakia's
Sudetenland to Germany was approved by 60-65 percent of the French
people, despite French military accords with the Prague government
in force since World War I.
   But the French themselves became the victims of Hitler's
ambitions when the Nazis occupied France in 1940.
   Daladier, then minister of war, was interned by the
collaborationist Vichy government. In 1943 he was taken to Germany
and imprisoned until the end of the war.
   Daladier never recovered politically. He died in 1970, having
never again held office.
   ``Even though his attitude during the war was irreproachable, he
never recuperated politically because of Munich,'' said Azema.
   The Munich generation is now in its twilight years. The majority
of today's Frenchmen have no firsthand memory of the times, its
dangers, its fears, its politics.
   Nonetheless, Munich remains a strong symbol.
   ``I have the impression that it rendered the French
non-pacifist,'' said Azema, noting stronger movements in other
European countries.
   ``Politically, mentally, pacifism was killed by Munich. No
French politician can support a pacifist policy, a pacific policy
yes, but not a pacifist policy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880917-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Munich-Italy ADV25   09-17 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Munich-Italy, ADV 25,0420</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun Sept. 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For Italy, An Illusion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IGOR UBOLDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of Benito Mussolini remembers that Italy's
fascist dictator, like Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain of
Britain, thought the Munich Pact of 1938 had saved the world from
war.
   ``I remember he came home from Munich and said, `Peace is
safe,''' said Vittorio Mussolini, who was 22 when his father went
to the Munich Conference.
   But Giovanni Spadolini, the Republican president of today's
Italian Senate and a professor of contemporary history at the
Univeristy of Florence, said the Munich agreement to cede the
Czechoslovakia's Sudentenland to Germany ``generated negative
beliefs within the dictatorships and within the democracies.''
   ``Hitler was convinced that France and Great Britain would never
have gone to war to defend the Eastern states,'' said Spadolini.
   ``Mussolini, who had taken a role that was unnatural for him,
that of the apostle of peace, was convinced of playing a
determinant role within the Axis. Above all, Munich contributed to
the infusing in him the ... conviction that the British were
decadent and faint-hearted and could be provoked without impunity.''
   Said Bruno Bottai, the secretary general of the Italian Foreign
Ministry: ``Munich was also the last conference in which the
destiny of other peoples was decided in an abstract, arrogant way.
   ``Then, people thought they could still solve war and peace with
political agreements, now we try to deal with this through the more
complex mechanism of the United Nations, together with the concept
of armaments reduction, which is new and more complex.''
   Sen. Gaetano Arfe, a member of the independent left who also is
professor of history of parties and political movements at the
University of Florence, said the advent of the atomic bomb marks a
great difference between then and now.
   ``At the time, one could aim for war. Now this is no longer
possible. ... The European countries can no longer have autonomous
foreign policies. These have to lie within the systems of NATO and
the EEC (European Economic Community).''
   Bottai said Italian diplomacy at the time was against an
excessive alignment with Germany. The Munich conference was seen as
a chance to widen the dialogue with France and Britain, he said.
   ``Unfortunately that was an illusion, which lasted for a short
time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
