<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ Bitterness still in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half a century after the Munich
Pact dismembered their country, many Czechs still feel they were
betrayed by nations they thought were their allies.
   British, French and Italian leaders joined Adolf Hitler in
Munich, Germany, in September 1938 to sign a pact allowing the
Nazis to swallow the German-speaking Sudetenland. The following
year, Hitler occupied the remainder of Czechoslovakia as well and
the nation no longer existed.
   ``In the history of nations there are events ... which even
decades later bring about strong feelings of patriotism,''
historian Jan Anger wrote in his book ``Munich 1938,'' published in
Prague this past August.
   Czechoslovakia's president in 1938, Edvard Benes, had relied on
a treaty with France and the loyalty of Britain to protect his
country from Hitler's fascism.
   Britain and France were the country's two main allies on which
Czechoslovakia had modeled its democracy.
   In a 1947 biography of Benes, Compton Mackenzie wrote: ``What
finally broke Benes' heart was the betrayal of France.''
   Bitter feelings have lasted long after the end of World War II
and the reconstruction of Czechoslovakia, including the
Sudetenland, under Communist leadership.
   Milos Jakes, who became the Communist Party leader in December,
said in February that the 1948 Communist takeover guaranteed an
alliance with the Soviet Union instead of dependence ``on
imperialist states, for which a tragic price was paid after
Munich.''
   However, many Czechs and Slovaks have felt equally betrayed by
their Soviet allies.
   Many of them are younger people who are bitter about the
Soviet-led invasion 30 years later to crush the ``Prague Spring''
of reforms.
   On the 30th anniversary of the Munich Pact in 1968,
Czechoslovaks were reeling from the shock of the Warsaw Pact
invastion Aug. 20-21 that crushed the reform movement of Alexander
Dubcek, the Communist Party leader at the time.
   On Aug. 21 of this year, thousands of mostly young Czechoslovaks
turned out on Prague's Wenceslas Square to protest the 1968
invasion. An estimated 10,000 demonstrators chanted ``Dubcek'' and
demands for truth and freedom.
   While bitter about Munich, Czechoslavaks see the Nazi era as
being over and West German visitors today are warmly welcomed in
Czechoslovakia.
   ``We usually hate the most those we have loved the most, and
vice versa,'' said one long-time political observer who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Look at the eager welcome given to the thousands of West
Germans swarming the streets of Prague today. One could almost
forget the way they (Germans) came to this country 50 years ago.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
