<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept 17-18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Toyota Unit Makes Rare Foray By Japanese into US Public Debt
Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. bond market, which has proven
attractive in recent years for Japanese investors, showed it can be
gracious on those rare occasions when it gets a call from a
borrower affiliated with a Japanese company.
   The market provided a warm reception this past week for a $200
million issue of three-year notes from Toyota Motor Credit Corp.,
the U.S. finance subsidiary of the Japanese automaker Toyota Motor
Corp.
   The notes, sold in denominations of $1,000, were priced to yield
8.826 percent, or a slim 38-hundredths of a percentage point more
than Treasury securities with a similar maturity.
   ``We were very pleased. It went very well and sold out within
one hour,'' said Wolfgang Jahn, vice president for Toyota Motor
Credit in Torrance, Calif.
   He said while the company has no specific plans for additional
offerings, he said he expects to be back.
   According to the research firm Securities Data Co., the sale was
the first straight public debt offering in the United States in 10
years by an affiliate of a Japanese company other than a bank or a
concern controlled by the government.
   The last such issue was the sale a $20 million in five-year
notes by Ito-Yokado Ltd., a Japanese department store company, in
June 1978, according to Fran Wissak of Securities Data in Newark,
N.J.
   Mark J. Lerner, head of the Japan Banking Group at Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets, which led the underwriters of the issue, said
Japanese companies have been deterred from the U.S. debt market
because of Securities and Exchange Commission requirements.
   But he said he suspects other Japanese companies will be
watching the Toyota note sale and may be encouraged to try it as
well.
   A wholly-owned subsidiary of Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc.,
Toyota Motor Credit makes loans to U.S. Toyota dealers and their
customers.
   It has grown rapidly over the past three years, and counts over
$3 billion in accounts receivable on its books, according to Jahn.
   Jahn said the company started out raising money in the
Euromarkets because they offered ready access and cheaper rates,
initially, than the U.S. markets.
   But Jahn said as the company's growth accelerated, it found it
needed to return to the Euromarket more frequently.
   Over the past three years, he said Toyota Motor Credit raised $2
billion in 16 separate offerings and that in recent months, found
itself going back to the market with new offerings every six to
eight months.
   ``We realized that we couldn't raise all our funds in Europe,''
he said. ``It was time for us to enter the U.S. market.''
   Lerner said Merrill Lynch worked for nine months to come up with
documents acceptable to the company and the SEC. He said a
first-time issuer could get into the Euromarkets, on the other
hand, in two weeks.
   Nonetheless, Jahn said Toyota Motor Credit wanted ``to make sure
we have the capability of going into the U.S. market'' to
accommodate the company's expected growth.
   ``It is the deepest and most liquid debt market in the world,''
added Lloyd Misteli, assistant treasurer at Toyota Motor Credit.
   Lerner said he expects Toyota Motor Credit will become one of
the most active issuers in the U.S. debt markets within two years,
joining a group that included the financing arms of the Big Three
U.S. automakers.
   He said other Japanese companies may also decide to start
borrowing here.
   The increasing frequency of Japanese acquisitions in the United
States may accelerate that development as Japanese companies look
for new sources of funds to help them finance those purchases, he
said.
   ``Now that a major leader among Japanese companies has taken
this initial step, other Japanese companies will follow suit,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept 17-18</NOTE>
</DOC>
