<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... very boring.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for September delivery settled Friday at $4.03 a bushel,
up slightly from $4 a week earlier; September corn fell to $2.78} a
bushel from $2.85}; September oats dropped to $2.58 a bushel from
$2.63; and September soybeans declined to $8.47{ a bushel from
$8.77{.
   Livestock and meat futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   October live cattle rose to 69.95 cents a pound from 69.60
cents; September feeder cattle improved to 79.80 cents a pound from
79.77 cents; October hogs advanced to 37.97 cents a pound from
37.92 cents; and February frozen pork bellies jumped to 50.65 cents
a pound from 47.30 cents.
   Precious metals futures fell sharply on the Commodity Exchange
in New York.
   October gold skidded to $412.90 a troy ounce from $423.10;
September silver dipped to $6.326 a troy ounce from $6.440.
   Energy futures advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   October West Texas Intermediate crude oil rose to $14.57 a
barrel from $14.18; October heating oil rallied to 41.37 cents a
gallon from 40.97 cents; and October unleaded gasoline improved to
44.22 cents a gallon from 42.06 cents.
</TEXT>
